Narrowing of the larynx, commonly occuring during viral respiratory tract infections, in particular in children, leads to symptoms such as hoarseness, a barking cough, stridor, and sometimes dyspnea and respiratory failure.
Subglottic laryngitis
A wart-like lesion (papilloma, i.e., benign epithelial tumors that are caused by infection with the human papilloma virus) located on the larynx.
Laryngeal papilloma
A wart-like lesion (papilloma, i.e., benign epithelial tumors that are caused by infection with the human papilloma virus) located on a bronchus.
Bronchial papilloma
A wart-like lesion (papilloma, i.e., benign epithelial tumors that are caused by infection with the human papilloma virus) located on the trachea.
Tracheal papilloma

Multiple verrucous lesions on the skin of the palm. These lesions are raised, have a thickened and rough surface, and may display prominent black dots (thrombosed capillaries). Palmar warts are caused by human papillomavirus (HPV).
Palmar warts

Multiple verrucous lesions on the skin of the sole of the foot. These lesions are raised, have a thickened and rough surface, and may display prominent black dots (thrombosed capillaries). Palmar warts are caused by caused by human papillomavirus (HPV).
Plantar warts

Diffuse alveolar damage (DAD) describes a common histologic injury pattern of the lung. The early stages are characterized by epithelial cell necrosis and sloughing, fibrous exsudate, edema, and hyaline membranes made of surfactant and proteins, filling the alveoli. This results in impaired gas exchange. In later stages, type II cells and myofibroblasts proliferate within the interstitium and airspaces. The corresponding clinical entity is acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS). DAD may result from pulmonary drug toxicity, occurs in immunosuppressed, severe viral infections, acute interstial pneumonitis, and crack cocaine inhalation.
Diffuse alveolar damage

Architectural distortion is characterized by abnormal displacement of bronchi, vessels, fissures, or septa caused by diffuse or localized lung disease, particularly interstitial fibrosis. This is visible in lung biopsy and CT scans in a distorted appearance and is usually associated with pulmonary fibrosis and accompanied by volume loss.
Architectural distortion of the lung
Abnormally increased width of the Z-disk of the sarcomere, resulting from splitting or opening of the Z-disc (c.f., Figure 2 of PMID:28732005).
Increased Z-disc width
Abnormally high concentration of coproporphyrin 1 in feces.
Increased fecal coproporphyrin 1
Abnormally high concentration of coproporphyrin 3 in feces
Increased fecal coproporphyrin 3
Extreme width of the skull in the occipital region, with anterior narrowing and prognathism.
Platystencephaly
Any deviation from the normal concentration of a metabolite in saliva.
Abnormal salivary metabolite concentration
Any deviation from the normal concentration of cortisol in saliva.
Abnormal salivary cortisol level
Abnormally reduced concentration of cortisol in saliva.
Decreased salivary cortisol level
Abnormally elevated concentration of cortisol in saliva.
Increased salivary cortisol level
A lasting reduction beneath the normal level of total immunoglobulin D (IgD) in the blood.
Chronic decreased circulating IgD
A temporary reduction beneath the normal level of total immunoglobulin D (IgD) in the blood circulation.
Transient decreased circulating IgD
A lasting absence of immunoglobulin D (IgD) in the blood, whereby at most trace quantities of IgD can be measured.
Chronic absent circulating IgD
A neoplasm that affects the male reproductive system.
Male reproductive system neoplasm
A neoplasm that affects the female reproductive system.
Female reproductive system neoplasm
A temporary reduction beneath the normal level of total immunoglobulin E (IgE) in the blood.
Transient decreased circulating IgE
A lasting reduction beneath the normal level of total immunoglobulin E (IgE) in the blood.
Chronic decreased circulating IgE
A lasting absence of immunoglobulin E (IgE) in the blood circulation, whereby at most trace quantities of IgE can be measured.
Chronic absent circulating IgE
A temporary reduction beneath the normal level of total immunoglobulin A (IgA) in the blood circulation.
Transient decreased circulating IgA
A lasting absence of immunoglobulin G (IgG) in the blood, whereby at most trace quantities of IgG can be measured.
Chronic absent circulating total IgG
A small circumscribed whitish change in the color of the oral mucosa that is neither elevated nor depressed.
White oral mucosal macule
A pebbly orange appearance of the fundus that is said to resemble the skin of an orange.
Retinal peau d'orange
The presence autoantibodies in the serum that react to proteins (70 Kd, A, C) that are associated with U1 RNA and form U1snRNP.
Anti-U1 ribonucleoprotein antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react to the glomerular basement membrane.
Anti-glomerular basement membrane-antibody positivity
An extreme elevation of core body temperature above normal defined as a rectal temperature of 41.1 degrees Celsius (106 degrees Fahrenheit).
Hyperpyrexia
Applies to a sign or symptom that is induced by an abusive adult (usually a parent).
Triggered by an abusive adult
The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react to Anti-MDA5 (Anti-melanoma differentiation-associated proteine 5).
Anti-MDA5 antibody positivity
The presence autoantibodies in the serum that react do different citrullinated antigens, including filaggrin, fibrinogen, vimentin and collagen.
Anti-citrullinated protein antibody positivity
Abnormality of schwann cells, glial cells that ensheath axons of neurons in the peripheral nervous system and are necessary for their maintenance and function.
Abnormal Schwann cell morphology

Reduced level of nasal nitric oxide (nNO). Current American Thoracic Society/European Respiratory Society (ATS/ERS) guidelines for nNO measurements recommend air aspiration via a nasal probe while the subject exhales through the mouth against resistance in order to maintain velum closure.
Decreased nasal nitric oxide
Migratory arthritis
The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react to RNA-polymerase III.
Anti-RNA-polymerase-III-autoantibody positivity
The presence of high titers of antigen-precipitating IgG in the serum.
Increased circulating precipitin level
The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react to seven proteins that consist of a core of small nuclear ribonucleoprotein (snRNP) particles.
Anti-Sm antibody positivity
Excessive or uncontrolled release of proinflammatory cytokines.
Cytokine storm
Any structural anomaly of the fetal part of the placenta, which is known as the chorion.
Abnormal chorion morphology
Swelling of the chorionic villi owing to fluid accumulation.
Edematous chorionic villi
Loss of previously achieved motor skills, as manifested by loss of developmental motor milestones.
Motor regression
A palpable swelling in both feet and ankles caused by an increase in interstitial fluid volume (excess fluid).
Bipedal edema
Basophilic intracytoplasmic inclusions in macrophages. The inclusions have a small, round laminated appearance. Electron microscopy of Michaelis-Gutmann bodies exhibits partially digested bacteria.
Michaelis-Gutmann bodies

Body ache is a complaint that is often used to denote vague symptoms of mild fatigue, lethargy, or dull aches. We will define it here to mean a dull and poorly localizable pain that is described by the affected individual to affect multiple joints or body parts or even the entire body.
Body ache
Hypointence (dark) appearance of the substantia nigra inmagnetic resonance imaging using susceptibility weighted imaging (SWI).
Substantia nigra hypointensity on susceptibility-weighted imaging
Hypointence (dark) appearance of the globus pallidus inmagnetic resonance imaging using susceptibility weighted imaging (SWI).
Globus pallidus hypointensity on susceptibility-weighted imaging
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) and perceived to originate in the throat.
Pharyngalgia

A disturbance of executive functioning, which is broadly defined as the set of abilities that allow for the planning, executing, monitoring, and self-correcting of goal-directed behavior while inhibiting task-irrelevant behavior. At least some degree of executive skill is needed to complete most cognitive tasks, and deficits in executive abilities are central to many clinical conditions, including fronto-temporal dementia.
Impaired executive functioning

Psychogenic non-epileptic seizures (PNES) are not abnormal perceptions or abnormal beliefs/judgments, nor are they epileptic attacks. They are behaviors that simulate epileptic attacks, not fully consciously.
Non-epileptic seizure
Sudden, involuntary seizure-like attacks that, unlike epileptic seizures, are not related to electrographic ictal discharges.
Pseudoseizure

A tremor-like cortical myoclonus. The tremulous movements are in fact small, high-frequency myoclonic jerks, induced by posture or action. They can be mild, but can also be more incapacitating. When present in the lower limbs, these may lead to gait disorders and even drop attacks. These tremor-like movements during action can be mistaken for essential tremor or epileptic seizures.
Myoclonic tremor
Impaired ability to anticipate future events, implement instructions or goals, and develop appropriate steps ahead of time in order to carry out a task or activity.
Impaired ability to plan
Impaired ability to bring order to information, actions, or materials to achieve a goal or to follow an established organized routine.
Impaired ability to organize

Concentration below the lower limit of normal of one or more components of the the terminal membrane attack complex (MAC) portion of complement, which represents the lytic, pore-forming part of the system. The MAC comprises seven components: C5b, C6, C7, C8 (a heterotrimer composed of C8alpha, C8beta and C8gamma) and multiple copies of C9.
Decreased circulating terminal complement component concentration
Concentration of the complement component C7 in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating complement C7 concentration
Concentration of the complement component C6 in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating complement C6 concentration
Concentration of the complement component C5 in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating complement C5 concentration
Elevated activity of coagulation factor IX. Factor IX, which itself is activated by factor Xa or factor VIIa to form factor IXa, activates factor X into factor Xa.
Increased factor IX activity
Abnormal activity of coagulation factor IX. Factor IX, which itself is activated by factor Xa or factor VIIa to form factor IXa, activates factor X into factor Xa.
Abnormal factor IX activity
A tendency to sleep fewer hours than usual while feeling well-rested.
Shortened sleep phase
Accumulation of globotriaosylceramide (GL-3) in kidney tissues, which can be quantified as the number of globotriaosylceramide (GL-3) inclusions/kidney interstitial capillary (KIC).
Renal interstitial globotriaosylceramide inclusions
The presence of mildly increased concentrations of albumin in the urine, defined as an albumin-creatinine ratio (ACR) less than 30 mg/gm (less than 3.4 mg/mmol).
Mild albuminuria
The presence of severely increased concentrations of albumin in the urine, defined as an albumin-creatinine ratio greater than 300 mg/gm (greater than 34 mg/mmol).
Severe albuminuria
Cystine crystalluria

A variety of drugs may occasionally cause transient crystalluria, in isolation or in conjunction with other urinary abnormalities. Overdose, dehydration, or hypoalbuminaemia, which increases the unbound drug which is ultrafiltrated by the glomerulus, are the factors usally favoring the precipitation of crystals within the tubular lumina. In some cases, medication-induced crystalluria has a distinct phenotypic appearance. For instance, Sulphadiazine crystals appear as strongly birefringent 'shocks of wheat' or 'shells' with an amber colour. Acyclovir crystals are birefringent and needle-shaped, and when present in abundance give to urine a silky and opalescent macroscopic appearance.
Medication crystalluria
An increased number of IgG4+ plasma cells in the interstitial space of the kidney.
Renal interstitial IgG4+ plasma cell infiltration
Impaired ability to track awareness of the effect that one's behavior has on others and how it compares with standards or expectations for behavior.
Impaired self monitoring
Impaired ability to keep track of one's problem-solving success or failure, and to identify and correct mistakes during performance of a goal.
Impaired task monitoring
Anomalous physical appearance (color, cloudiness, clarity) or odor of urine.
Abnormal macroscopic urine appearance

Intradermal urate crystal deposits appeared as small, superficial, pustule-like, whitish lesions. The lesions may be the focus of inflammatory episodes with increasing pain, swelling, and erythema of the intradermal tophi.
Urate tophus
Amelioration of anemia upon treatment with a steroid medication.
Steroid-responsive anemia
A normal or elevated serum thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) level in the face of an elevation in circulating FT4 and/or FT3.
Inappropriately normal thyroid-stimulating hormone level

A deviation from the normal concentration of free thyroxine (T4) in the blood circulation. Circulating T4 is almost entirely bound to specific transport proteins such as thyroxine-binding globulin (TBG) but it is the unbound (free) fraction that is able to enter tissues and exert effects.
Abnormal circulating free T4 concentration
An elevated concentration of free thyroxine (fT4) in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating free T4 concentration
A reduced concentration of free thyroxine (fT4) in the blood circulation.
Decreased circulating free T4 concentration
Absence or underdevelopment of the thyroid gland.
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the thyroid gland

Thyrotrophin-releasing hormone (TRH) is a hypothalamic tripeptide synthesized by, stored within, and released from the hypothalamus. It stimulates the synthesis and release of thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) from the anterior pituitary gland. Following administration of exogenous TRH, a transient increase in serum TSH is expected. This term refers to an abnormal response in the TRH stimulation test.
Abnormal TSH response to thyrotrophin-releasing hormone stimulation test
Failure to increase serum TSH levels in response to a TRH stimulation test.
Absent TSH response to thyrotrophin-releasing hormone stimulation test
A lower than normal TSH response to thyrotrophin-releasing hormone stimulation test.
Reduced TSH response to thyrotrophin-releasing hormone stimulation test
An elevated level of farnesol in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating farnesol concentration

Any deviation from a count of antral follicles that is normal for age. Antral follicles appear as small fluid-filled sacs that contain an immature egg. Antral follicle count can be measured (usually on day 2-5 of the menstrual cycle) by transvaginal ultrasound. The number of antral follicles may reflect ovarian reserve.
Abnormal antral follicle count
A count of antral follicles that is lower than normal for age.
Reduced antral follicle count
A count of antral follicles that is higher than normal for age.
Increased antral follicle count
Fever that occurs at daily intervals.
Quotidian fever
Urine valine level above the normal range.
Valinuria
An increased level of a branched chain family amino acid in the urine.
Branched-chain aminoaciduria
An elevated level of an aromatic amino acid in the urine.
Increased aromatic amino acid level in urine
An abnormally increased level of tyrosine in the urine.
Tyrosinuria
The concentration of succinate in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Increased urine succinate level
An elevated level of an glutamine family amino acid in the urine.
Increased glutamine family amino acid level in urine
An increased concentration of glutamate in the urine.
Increased urine glutamate level
An elevated level of a sulfur-containing amino acid in the urine.
Increased sulfur amino acid level in urine
An elevated level of an aspartate family amino acid in the urine.
Increased aspartate family amino acid level in urine
An elevated urine level of a compound that is derived from an amino acid.
Increased urine proteinogenic amino acid derivative level
An increased level in the urine of an alpha-amino acid which is not a member of the group of 23 proteinogenic amino acids.
Increased urinary non-proteinogenic amino acid level
An increased level of a serine family amino acid in the urine.
Increased serine family amino acid in urine

An elevated level of a proteinogenic amino acid in the urine. These are the 23 alpha-amino acids that are precursors to proteins, and are incorporated into proteins during translation. The group includes the 20 amino acids encoded by the nuclear genes of eukaryotes together with selenocysteine, pyrrolysine, and N-formylmethionine.
Increased proteinogenic amino acid level in urine
An abnormally increased level of aconitic acid in the urine.
Elevated urine aconitic acid level

The femoral neck region shows medial metaphyseal beaking and a significant enlargement of the lesser trochanter (with some enlargement also of the greater trochanter), producing a monkey wrench (Swedish key) configuration of the proximal femur. A monkey wrench refers to a type of adjustable wrench with one fixed and one adjustable jaw at right angles to a straight handle.
Monkey wrench femoral neck
Increased concentration of chitinase 3-like 1 (CHI3L1) in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating CHI3L1 level
Failure to develop fever in the presence of an infection that normally would be expected to elicit a febrile response.
Inappropriate absence of fever
An abnormal parenchymal band connecting the medial margins of the left and right hypothalami across the third ventricle.
Interhypothalamic adhesion
An increased concentration of D-dimers, a marker of fibrin degradation, in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating D-dimer concentration

An elevated level of a proteinogenic amino acid in the blood circulation. These are the 23 alpha-amino acids that are precursors to proteins, and are incorporated into proteins during translation. The group includes the 20 amino acids encoded by the nuclear genes of eukaryotes together with selenocysteine, pyrrolysine, and N-formylmethionine.
Abnormal circulating proteinogenic amino acid concentration
Any deviation from the normal concentration in the blood circulation of a compound that is derived from an amino acid.
Abnormal circulating proteinogenic amino acid derivative concentration
Any deviation from the normal concentration in the blood circulation of an alpha-amino acid which is not a member of the group of 23 proteinogenic amino acids.
Abnormal circulating non-proteinogenic amino acid concentration

An abnormally increased level of alpa-aminobutyric acid in the blood circulation. Alpha-aminobutyric acid alpha-amino acid that is butyric acid bearing a single amino substituent located at position 2.
Elevated circulating alpha-aminobutyric acid concentration
Concentration of 3-hydroxyisovaleric acid in the urine above the normal range.
3-hydroxyisovaleric aciduria

An increased concentration in blood of apolipoprotein C-III, a protein component of triglyceride (TG)-rich lipoproteins (TRLs) including very low density lipoproteins (VLDL), high density lipoproteins (HDL) and chylomicrons.
Elevated circulating apolipoprotein C-III concentration

In the normal heart cycle, two heart sounds can be heard by auscultation per cycle: S1 and S2. A gallop rhythm refers to the presence of three or four heart sounds per cardiac cycle, which is said to resemble the gallop of a horse.
Gallop rhythm
A type of gallop rhythm in which both the third and the fourth sounds are present.
Quadruple gallop rhythm
Abnormally increased concentration of tenascin-C in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating tenascin-C level

Foci of gastric-type mucus-secreting cells interspersed between duodenal enterocytes. These foci of gastric epithelial cells contain Periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive neutral mucin and lack a brush border.
Duodenal gastric metaplasia
Inflammation of the lining of the upper small intestine (duodenum).
Duodenitis
Anomalous physiology (function) of the right ventricle.
Abnormal right ventricular function
Elevation of right ventricular systolic pressure (RVSP) above normal limits. In adults, RVSP is normally 20-30 mmHg.
Elevated right ventricular systolic pressure

A type of eczema characterized by pruritic coin-shaped patches on the skin. Nummular eczema most commonly occurs on the extremities, particularly the legs, but may occur anywhere on the trunk, hands, or feet
Nummular eczema
A cough with a characteristic sound that has been compared to a seal's bark.
Barking cough
The P wave that normally precedes each QRS complex by a fixed PR interval of 120 to 200 milliseconds is not present.
Absent P wave
Abnormally increased level of osteopontin in the blood circulation
Elevated circulating osteopontin level
An increased level of sorbitol in the blood circulation.
Increased serum sorbitol concentration

An indolent B cell lymphoproliferative disorder of transformed follicular center B cells. Follicular lymphoma is characterized by diffuse lymphadenopathy, bone marrow involvement, splenomegaly and less commonly other extranodal sites of involvement.
Follicular lymphoma

Skin and subcutaneous tissue necrosis (tissue death). Clinically, cutaneous necrosis may present as a painful and extremely tender black eschar (dead tissue found in a full-thickness wound) surrounded by dusky grey-red coloured skin.
Cutaneous necrosis

An anomaly of the musculoskeletal system, which consists of the bones of the skeleton, muscles, cartilage, tendons, ligaments, joints, and other connective tissue. The musculoskeletal system supports the weight of the body, maintains body position and produces movements of the body or of parts of the body.
Abnormality of the musculoskeletal system

A failure to achieve the ability to crawl at an appropriate developmental stage. Normal infant motor development is marked by a series of postural milestones including learning to crawl on hands and knees between the ages of 6 and 10 months.
Delayed ability to crawl

Anopmalous function of the shoulder. The shoulder is a ball-and-socket joint that is made up of humerus, scapula and clavicle, which are connected by the sternoclavicular joint (SC), the acromioclavicular joint (AC), the glenohumeral joint (GH), and the scapulothoracic joint (ST). The GH, AC and SC joints link the upper extremity to the axial skeleton at the thorax and enable movement at the shoulder joint: flexion, extension, and rotation of the arm.
Abnormal shoulder physiology
Anomalous echogenicity of the kidney on ultrasound examination.
Abnormal renal echogenicity
Increased echogenecity of the medullary region of the kidney.
Renal medullary hyperechogenicity
Increased echogenecity of the kidney cortex.
Renal cortical hyperechogenicity
Renal cortical hypoechogeneity
Fibrous bands (i.e., bands of scar-like tissue) that span two or more intra-abdominal organs and/or the inner abdominal wall (i.e. peritoneal membrane).
Abdominal adhesions

Hepatic infarction is defined as areas of coagulative necrosis from hepatocyte cell death caused by local ischemia. Liver infarctions appear as hypoechoic nonvascular regions on conventional and Doppler sonography.
Hepatic infarction
An inflamed lymph node that is filled with pus.
Lymph node abscess
A structural abnormality of the pulmonary acinus, alveolar parenchyma, or alveoli.
Abnormal pulmonary alveolar system morphology
A thrombus (i.e., a blood clot formed in situ within the vascular system) located in the right atrium of the heart.
Right atrial thrombus
Concentration of uracil in the blood circulation is above the normal range.
Elevated circulating uracil concentration
The presence of an upwardly displaced normal cerebellar vermis, normal appearance of the fastigium, tentorium and size of the cisterna magna.
Blake's pouch cyst

Unusually severe clinical course of SARS-CoV-2 infection, manifested clinically by features such as dyspnea and hypoxia with diffuse bilateral ground-glass opacities of the lungs on computed tomographic scan with progressive respiratory insufficiency necessitating oxygen supplementation or mechanical ventilation.
Severe SARS-CoV-2 infection
Increased superior-inferior length of the nasal bridge, which is the saddle-shaped area that includes the nasal root and the lateral aspects of the nose.
Long nasal bridge
Inflammation of the lining of the middle section of the small intestine.
Jejunitis
Any deviation of the concentration of ceruloplasmin in the blood from the normal range.
Abnormal circulating ceruloplasmin concentration
Elevated concentration of ceruloplasmin in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating ceruloplasmin concentration
Increased concentration of methylsuccinic acid in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating methylsuccinic acid concentration
Any deviation from the normal concentration of a short-chain fatty acid in the blood circulation.
Abnormal circulating short-chain fatty-acid concentration
Increased concentration of isovaleric acid, a C5, branched-chain saturated fatty acid, in the blood concentration.
Increased circulating isovaleric acid concentration
Increased diameter (caliber) of intrahepatic bile ducts (bile ducts that transport bile between the Canals of Hering and the interlobar bile ducts).
Intrahepatic bile duct dilatation
An abscess located at the junction of the anal canal and the rectum.
Anorectal abscess
A structural anomaly of the pharynx.
Abnormal pharynx morphology
A functional anomaly of the pharynx.
Abnormal pharynx physiology
An abnormally increased circulation of dodecenoylcarnitine, C12:1, in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating dodecenoylcarnitine concentration
An increased concentration of lysyl-pyridinoline (deoxypyridinoline) cross-links in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating deoxypyridinoline concentration
Abnormally increased concentration of L-alloisoleucine in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating L-alloisoleucine concentration
Abnormally increased level of L-alloisoleucine in the urine.
Elevated urine L-alloisoleucine level
Abnormal increase of the concentration of 3-methylhistidine in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating 3-methylhistidine concentration
An abnormal reduction in the number of beats per unit time of the respiratory cilia.
Reduced respiratory ciliary beating frequency

The amount of inosine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal. Inosine is a purine nucleoside in which hypoxanthine is attached to ribofuranose via a beta-N(9)-glycosidic bond.
Reduced urinary inosine level

The amount of guanosine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal. Guanosine is a purine nucleoside in which guanine is attached to ribofuranose via a beta-N(9)-glycosidic bond.
Decreased urinary guanosine level

Any deviation from the normal amount of a purine compound in the urine. Purines are aromatic heterocyclic compounds containing a purine moiety, which is formed a pyrimidine-ring ring fused to an imidazole ring. Two of the four deoxyribonucleotides (deoxyadenosine and deoxyguanosine) and two of the four ribonucleotides (adenosine, or AMP, and guanosine, or GMP) are purines.
Abnormal urinary purine level

Any deviation from the normal amount of a pyrimidine compound in the urine. Pyrimidines and pyrimidine derivatives are compounds containing a pyrimidne ring, which is a six-member aromatic heterocycle which consists of two nitrogen atoms (at positions 1 and 3) and four carbon atoms. The nucleotides cytosine, thymine and uracil are pyrimidines.
Abnormal urinary pyrimidine level

An increased number and/or abnormal type of bacteria in the small bowel. Small intestinal bacterial overgrowth has been defined as the presence of greater than one hundred thousand bacteria (i.e. colony-forming units, CFU) per mL of proximal jejunal aspiration. The normal value is ten thousand or few CFU/ml.
Small intestinal bacterial overgrowth

Focal active colitis (FAC) is characterized by focal crypt damage caused by neutrophils. FAC is characterized by an inflammatory infiltrate consisting of intraepithelial neutrophils and/or neutrophils invading the lumen of the criptae, with no other microscopic alteration of the colonic mucosa and, in particular, without the presence of signs of chronic inflammation.
Focal active colitis
Inflammation of the intestine leading to bacterial invasion causing cellular damage and death which causes necrosis of the colon and intestine.
Necrotizing enterocolitis
An increased susceptibility to viral upper respiratory tract infections as manifested by a history of recurrent viral upper respiratory tract infections (otitis, sinusitis, pharyngitis, tonsillitis).
Recurrent viral upper respiratory tract infections
A neutrophilic interstitial, perivascular and/or perieccrine infiltrate with leukocytoclasia. Notably, leukocytoclastic vasculitis is not present.
Neutrophilic urticarial dermatosis
Abnormally reduced activity of mevalonate kinase, which is a key enzyme in the mevalonate biosynthetic pathway that leads to the synthesis of both cholesterol and nonsterol isoprenoids.
Reduced mevalonate kinase activity
Abnormally reduced volume of air in the lungs upon the maximum effort of inspiration.
Reduced total lung capacity
Any deviation from the normal range of a skinfold thickness, which quantifies the amount of subcutaneous fat when the skin is pinched by specialized calipers.
Abnormal skinfold thickness measurement
Any deviation from the normal range of the thickness of the triceps skinfold, which quantifies the amount of subcutaneous fat when the skin is pinched by specialized calipers.
Abnormal triceps skinfold thickness
Increased thickness of the triceps skinfold, which is measured halfway down the back of the upper arm is increased.
Increased triceps skinfold thickness
Return of lavage fluid with a milky appearance due to the accumulation of a mixture of pulmonary surfactant, which is a lipoprotein complex, in the alveolar space.
Milky appearance of bronchoalveolar lavage fluid

Return of lavage fluid characteristically has a bloody appearance in pulmonary alveolar hemorrhage. This is due to admixture of blood, which typically increases with each consecutive lavage portion. Microscopically erythrocytes can be seen. After 24 to 48 h macrophages contain phagocytosed erythrocytes, indicating previous bleeding.
Bloody bronchoalveolar lavage fluid
Concentration of L-pyroglutamic acid in the blood is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating 5-oxoproline concentration
Increased size of the lymph nodes that are located beneath the mandible (lower jaw).
Submandibular lymph node enlargement
An increased concentration of suberic acid in the blood circulation. Suberic acid is an alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is the 1,6-dicarboxy derivative of hexane.
Elevated circulating suberic acid concentration
An increased concentration of interleukin-8 in the circulation.
Increased circulating interleukin 8 concentration
Concentration of aconitic acid in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating aconitic acid concentration

The appendix testis or hydatid of Morgagni, is a vestigial remnant of the MÃ¼llerian duct located on the superior pole of the testicle between the testis and epididymis. Although this appendage has no vital function, it is present in 50% of males. Torsion of twisting of this vestigial remnant can be incredibly painful, but usually requires no medical intervention.
Torsion of appendix of testis

Spinal epidural abscess (SEA) is caused by a suppurative infection in the epidural space. The mass effect of the abscess can compress and reduce blood flow to the spinal cord, conus medullaris, or cauda equina.
Spinal epidural abscess
An increase in concentration of cathepsin D in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating cathepsin D level
A developmental defect of pulmonary lobation characterized by the presence of only two lobes of the right lung.
Bilobed right lung
Triggered by infection
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by infection by the Epstein-Barr virus.
Triggered by EBV infection

The term is commonly used to describe a putative abnormal location of pulmonary vein branches adjacent to pulmonary arteries within the same adventitial sheath. However, evidence has been provided that the vessels in question are not pulmonary veins, however represent dilated bronchial veins.
Misalignment of the pulmonary veins
Elevated levels of proline-containing dipeptides in urine.
Hyperimidodipeptiduria
A severe type of acne characterized by the formation of cysts enclosing a mixture of keratin and sebum.
Cystic acne
Tooth root length more than 2 SD above mean, or subjectively apparently increased tooth root length.
Radiculomegaly
A large nonpalpable spot of the skin over 1 cm in dimension with increased pigmentation and increased hair growth.
Hypertrichotic hyperpigmented patch
An increased concentration of selenium in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating selenium concentration
An abnormally reduced concentration of selenium in the blood circulation.
Decreased circulating selenium concentration

Swelling of the hepatocyte, rounding of its contour, and alteration of the cytoplasm, which takes on a reticulated, rarefied, or flocculant quality. The cytoplasm of the ballooned hepatocytes often contains clumps of eosinophilic ropey material known as Mallory-Denk bodies (MDBs) or Mallory hyaline, which is composed of hyperphosphorylated misfolded intermediate filaments, ubiquitin, and ubiquitin-binding protein P62.
Ballooning hepatocyte degeneration
Erythema (Redness of the skin caused by hyperemia of the capillaries in the lower layers of the skin) localized to the region surrounding the mouth.
Perioral erythema
Erythema (Redness of the skin caused by hyperemia of the capillaries in the lower layers of the skin) localized to the region surrounding the anus.
Perianal erythema
Infiltration of portal fields by inflammatory cells.
Portal inflammation

Infiltration of inflammatory cells in lobules of the liver. A focus of lobular inflammation can be defined as two or more inflammatory cells (neutrophils, lymphocytes and other mononuclear cells, eosinophils and microgranulomas) within the lobule present within the sinusoids or surrounding injured hepatocytes (ballooned or apoptotic hepatocytes).
Hepatic lobular inflammation
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by infection by a virus.
Triggered by viral infection
An elevation of the concentration of interleukin 10 in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating interleukin 10 concentration
Reduced intensity of the triceps tendon reflex.
Triceps hyporeflexia
Reduced intensity of the biceps tendon reflex.
Biceps hyporeflexia
Reduced intensity of the brachioradialis tendon reflex.
Brachioradialis hyporeflexia
Increased intensity of the brachioradialis reflex.
Brachioradialis hyperreflexia
Increased intensity of the triceps reflex.
Triceps hyperreflexia
Increased intensity of the biceps reflex.
Biceps hyperreflexia
Increased intensity of the Achilles reflex.
Hyperactive Achilles reflex

Increased proportion relative to B-lymphocytes of a subset of B lymphocytes characterized by dim/low levels of CD21, i.e., CD21-/low, in flow cytometry, and additionally enriched in autoreactive clones as determined for instance by clonse showing rheumatoid factor (anti-IgG) reactivity and antibodies recognizing cytoplasmic and to a lesser extent nuclear structures.
Increased proportion autoreactive unresponsive CD21-/low B cells

A developmental defect of the alveolar airspace during cananicular lung development characterized by a decreased number of pulmonary capillaries located away from the alveolar epithelium, thickened alveolar septae, media hypertrophy of small pulmonary arteries and muscularization of distal arterioles, and in some cases lymphangiectasis.
Alveolar capillary dysplasia

Arrest of lung development in the pseudoglandular stage (weeks 8 to 16 of human gestation) resulting in small sized lungs, predominantly composed of bronchial and bronchiolar structures embedded in abundant loose mesenchyme that is poorly vascularized. Acinar structures are essentially absent, with no significant formation of saccules and no alveoli.
Acinar dysplasia

Arrest of lung development in the cananicular stage (weeks 18 to 26 of human gestation) resulting in simplified acinar spaces, frequently with abundant intervening mesenchyme and no alveoli. In later arrest growth stages early saccular formations may be seen. May resemble the lobular maldevelopment often seen in alveolar capillary dysplasia/misaligment of the pulmonary veins without vein misalignment or marked hypertensive changes of the pulmonary arteries.
Congenital alveolar dysplasia

A reduction in the total-iron binding capacity, which measures how much serum iron is bound if an excess of radioactive iron is added. The latent (or free) iron binding capacity is the difference between the TIBC and the measured serum iron, corresponding to the transferrin not bound to iron, i.e., free iron binding capacity.
Decreased total iron binding capacity
Any deviation from the normal total-iron binding capacity, which measures how much serum iron is bound if an excess of radioactive iron is added.
Abnormal total iron binding capacity
The concentration of suberic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine suberic acid level
Increased susceptibility to viral pneumonia, as manifested by recurrent episodes of viral pneumonias.
Recurrent viral pneumonia
Obliterative abnormality of the renal glomerulus

Accumulation of amorphous, eosinophilic, glassy, periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive, silver-negative material in the glomerulus. Distribution can include vascular pole, perihilar, tip or neither tip, perihilar or vascular.
Glomerular hyalinosis
Accumulation of amorphous, eosinophilic, glassy, periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive, silver-negative material in the glomerulus at the vascular pole/perihilum.
Perihilar glomerular hyalinosis
Accumulation of amorphous, eosinophilic, glassy, periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive, silver-negative material in the glomerulus at the tip/tubular pole.
Glomerular hyalinosis at the tubular pole

Accumulation of amorphous, eosinophilic, glassy, periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive, silver-negative material in the glomerulus at neither tip nor perihilar/vascular poles. Both the vascular and the tubular pole are present in the glomerular cross section.
Glomerular hyalinosis away from the vascular and tubular poles
An increased concentration of 2-ethylhydracylic acid in the urine.
2-ethylhydracylic aciduria
An abnormal elevation of the relative proportion of CD4+ to CD8+ T cells.
Increased CD4:CD8 ratio
An abnormal reduction of the relative proportion of CD4+ to CD8+ T cells.
Decreased CD4:CD8 ratio

Any structural abnormality of the parietal epithelial cells that line the inside of Bowman's capsule and form an inconspicuous sheet of flat epithelial cells in continuity with the proximal tubular epithelial cells at the urinary pole and with the podocytes at the vascular pole.
Abnormal glomerular parietal epithelial cell morphology
Increased number of parietal epithelial cells lining Bowman's capsule. Hyperplasia leads to the cells being present in 2 or more layers, often with crowding and multilayering.
Glomerular parietal epithelial cell hyperplasia

An abnormality of the glomerular parietal epithelial cells characterized by (1) Increased parietal epithelial cell size, with or without cytoplasmic protein droplets; or (2) enlarged nuclei with prominent nucleoli. Both features can be present
Glomerular parietal epithelial cell hypertrophy

An insudative accumulation of amorphous, eosinophilic, periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive, silver-negative material protruding from Bowman's capsule into the urinary space. Although not always evident by light microscopy, this material is located between Bowman's capsule and the parietal epithelial cells, in some cases associated with newly formed matrix material.
Bowman capsular hyaline drops
An area of basement membrane continuity between the glomerular tuft and Bowman's capsule, without intervening crescent and not adjacent to an area of segmental sclerosis.
Glomerular synechial adhesion
Inability to elicit triceps tendon reflex.
Triceps areflexia
Inability to elicit brachioradialis tendon reflex.
Brachioradialis areflexia
Inability to elicit biceps tendon reflex.
Biceps areflexia
Abnormal number of its constituent cells of the mesangium of the glomerulus of the kidney.
Abnormal glomerular mesangial cellularity

Any structural anomaly of the glomerular matrix. Mesangial cells generate and embed in their own extracellular matrix. The mesangial matrix is different in composition from the glomerular basement membrane. Its constituents are type IV collagen (but only the alpha1 and alpha2 chains); type V collagen; laminin A, B1, and B2; and considerable amounts of fibronectin, heparan sulfate and chondroitin sulfate proteoglycans, entactin, and nidogen. Furthermore, small amounts of the proteoglycans decorin and biglycan are found in the mesangial matrix.
Abnormal glomerular mesangial matrix morphology
Mesangial immune deposit located adjacent to the paramesangial glomerular basement membrane.
Paramesangial deposits
Extracellular mesangial accumulation of moderately electron-dense, generally homogenous, amorphous-appearing extracellular material.
Mesangial hyaline deposition
Reduced ability to desscend stairs.
Difficulty descending stairs
A failure to sustain attention that requires self-motivation to optimize performance.
Cognitive fatigue

Detachment of visceral epithelial cells (podocytes) from underlying glomerular basement membrane with intervening new loose basement membrane material (pale on Hematoxylin and eosin, periodic acid-Shiff, trichrome, or silver stain) forming a so-called 'halo'.
Visceral epithelial cell detachment
Cytoplasmic projections into the urinary space from the luminal side of the podocyte.
Podocyte microvillous transformation
Layer of hypertrophied visceral epithelial cells overlying a sclerosed segment of the tuft of the glomerulus.
Visceral epithelial cell capping

An increase in the ratio of residual volume (RV) to total lung capacity (TLC) on pulmonary function testing. RV is the amount of air remaining aftermaximal expiration and TLC is the total amount of air in theungs at full inspiration. These volumes cannot be determined by spirometry, but can be measured by inert gas dilution, nitrogen washout, and (3) body plethysmography. An elevated RV/TLC can be interpreted as a sign of air trapping and hyperinflation.
Elevated RV/TLC ratio

An elevation of the total count of alveoli as determined by microscopic point-counting of randomly taken lung sections, not secondary to abnormalities in number, size and structure of the airways. In polyaveolar lobe, the number of alveoli is generally increased three to fivefold.
Polyalveolar lobe
A horseshoe lung is an uncommon congenital abnormality caused by the partial fusion of the bases of both lungs behind the pericardial sac.
Horseshoe lung
Cellular death affecting one or more parts of the lung. Necrosis is caused by diverse external and internal factors which result in the unregulated digestion of cell components.
Pulmonary necrosis
Accumulation of immature interstitial cells containing abundant cytoplasmic glycogen defined by periodic acid-Schiff (PAS) positive cells.
Glycogen accumulation in pulmonary interstitial cells
Any structural abnormality of alveolar type 2 (ATII) cells.
Abnormal alveolar type II pneumocyte morphology

Increase in size of type II pneumocytes, characterized by qualitative morphologic alterations, including cuboidal shapes, increased nucleocytoplasmic ratio, enlarged nuclei, prominent nucleoli, and various alterations in their nuclear chromatin.
Type II pneumocyte hypertrophy

Extracellular deposition in lung tissue of a proteinaceous material that, when stained with Congo red, demonstrates apple-green birefringence under polarized light and that has a distinct color when stained with sulfated Alcian blue. Viewed with electron microscopy, the amyloid deposits are seen to be composed of a beta-sheet fibrillar material. These nonbranching fibrils have a diameter of 7.5 to 10 nm and are the result of protein misfolding.
Pulmonary amyloidosis
Fibrosing nodules, consisting of either unilateral or bilateral central whorled deposits of lamellar collagen hyalin.
Multiple pulmonary interstitial hyalinized nodules
Hyperintense lesion in the substantia nigra on magnetic resonance T2 imaging.
Focal substantia nigra T2 hyperintensity
An increased number of turns of the blood vessels of the nailfold with a charactereistic winded or twisted appearance of the blood vessels.
Nailfold capillary tortuosity
Increase in the amount of air remaining in a person's lungs after full exhalation.
Elevated residual volume
Exaggerated skin markings (dermatoglyphics) on the palms of the hand.
Palmar hyperlinearity
A reduction in the concentration of interferon gamma measured in the blood circulation.
Reduced circulating interferon gamma concentration
Narrowing of the anorectum associated with inflammation or scar tissue.
Anorectal stricture
A congenital malformation characterized by an overdistended segment of lung, affecting an party of a lobe or the entire one. It results in progressive overinflation of one or more lobes.
Congenital lobar overinflation
Inflammation of the entire colon.
Pancolitis
A failure to achieve the ability to walk with support (cruise) at an appropriate developmental stage.
Delayed ability to walk with support

Sudden unexpected death in epilepsy (SUDEP) is a sudden, unexpected, witnessed or unwitnessed, non-traumatic and non-drowning death, occurring in benign circumstances, in an individual with epilepsy, with or without evidence for a seizure and excluding documented status epilepticus, in which postmortem examination has not revealed a cause of death.
Sudden unexpected death in epilepsy

A seizure with clinical manifestation but without motor signs (other than possible behavior arrest) as its initial clinical manifestation. The electrographic onset may be generalized, focal, or unknown.
Non-motor seizure

Livedo racemosa describes a reddish-blue mottling of the skin in an irregular, reticular pattern. It differs from the more common livedo reticularis by its shape. Livedo racemosa consists of broken circular segments resulting in a seemingly larger pattern, as opposed to the fine, regular, complete network of livedo reticularis. Livedo racemosa results from permanent impairment of peripheral blood flow and, unlike livedo reticularis, it persists on warming.
Livedo racemosa

Increase in diameter of a segment of the renal artery that can be defined as a focal, isolated dilatation of all three layers of the arterial wall over 1.5 times the diameter of the disease-free proximal adjacent arterial segment.
Renal artery aneurysm
A fracture through the distal humeral physis that separates the entire distal humeral epiphysis from the metaphysis.
Transphyseal fracture of the distal humerus
Lack of platelet dense granules, a type of platelet organelles.
Absent platelet dense granules
Increased size of platelet dense granules.
Enlarged platelet dense granules
Lamellated intracytoplasmic lipid inclusions within podocytes.
Podocyte myelin figures

Visceral epithelial cell hyperplasia with resulting cellular crowding of the the urinary space. In contrast with true crescents, these proliferations lack inflammatory cells and fibrin. The cells are typically plump (not spindle-shaped) and often vacuolated, and Bowman's capsule is usually intact.
Glomerular pseudocrescent
Abnormal structural characteristics of the interior space of the capillary of the renal glomerulus.
Abnormal glomerular capillary lumen morphology

Wrinkling and folding of the capillaries without epithelial cell (podocyte) hyperplasia (formerly called ischemic type of collapse) involving o 80% of the glomerular tuft. The wrinkling is generally made by small regular folds of the glomerular basement membrane.
Deflation of the glomerular tuft

Collapse is generally accompanied by other descriptors such as hypertrophy and hyperplasia of overlying glomerular epithelial cells, halo, protein droplets in podocytes and glomerular parietal epithelial cells (PECs).
Glomerular capillary collapse
Global distention of glomerular capillaries with intraluminal intact red blood cells.
Glomerular capillary congestion
Glomerular capillary dilatation due to loosening/detachment of the glomerular basement membrane (GBM) from its anchoring points, usually in the context of mesangiolysis or nodular glomerulosclerosis.
Glomerular capillary microaneurysm
An abnormal structure of the glomerular endothelial cells, which are highly specialized cells with fenestrae and a charged luminal glycocalyx layer that contribute to the filtration barrier.
Abnormal glomerular endothelial cell morphology
Loss of round to oval discontinuities normally present in the glomerular capillary endothelial cell cytoplasm.
Loss of glomerular endothelial cell fenestration
Enlargement of glomerular endothelial cells by cytoplasmic swelling with resulting partial or complete occlusion of the lumen.
Glomerular endotheliosis
Inter-anastomosing tubular structures located within cisternae of endoplasmic reticulum, most often within endothelial cells and associated with exposure to interferon.
Glomerular endothelial tubuloreticular inclusion
Fibrin associated with glomerular basement membrane disruption and/or lysis of the mesangial matrix; this lesion does not require the presence of karyorrhexis.
Glomerular fibrinoid necrosis

Reduced amount of programmed cell death in peripheral blood lymphocytes following exposure to CD95 (APO-1/Fas), which is a member of the death receptor family, a subfamily of the TNF-R superfamily. Crosslinking of CD95 with its natural ligand CD95L (CD178) or with agonistic antibodies such as anti-APO-1 induces apoptosis in sensitive cells.
Reduced CD95-induced lymphocyte apoptosis
An abnormal connection (fistula) between the intra-abdominal intestinal tract and the skin.
Enterocutaneous fistula
Enlargement of lymph nodes surrounding the trachea.
Paratracheal lymphadenopathy
The presence of nucleated red blood cells in the peripheral blood circulation.
Circulating nucleated red blood cells
Any abnormal sttructure of the glomerular basement membrane.
Abnormal glomerular basement membrane morphology

Prominent glomerular basement membrane (GBM) reflecting a segmental and increase in thickness (subjective estimate) with no evidence of electron dense deposits by EM. Thickening is measured from endothelial to visceral epithelial plasma membrane and mainly attributable to an increase in thickness of the lamina densa, generally to an overall thickness more than 2 standard deviations greater than that of the normal mean GBM thickness for health age- and sex matched individuals.
Segmentally thickened glomerular basement membrane

Prominent glomerular basement membrane (GBM) reflecting an diffuse and relativly uniform increase in thickness (subjective estimate) with no evidence of electron dense deposits by EM. Thickening is measured from endothelial to visceral epithelial plasma membrane and mainly attributable to an increase in thickness of the lamina densa, generally to an overall thickness more than 2 standard deviations greater than that of the normal mean GBM thickness for health age- and sex matched individuals.
Diffusely thickened glomerular basement membrane
Prominent glomerular basement membrane (GBM) reflecting an increase in thickness (subjective estimate) with no evidence of electron dense deposits by electron microscopy.
Thickened glomerular basement membranes with no electron dense deposits
Thickened glomerular basement membranes with electron dense deposits
Lucent zones within the glomerular basement membranes. May reflect remote/resolved deposits.
Glomerular basement membrane lucencies
Glomerular basement membrane spikes
Irregular folding of the glomerular basement membrane with an intact lamina densa.
Glomerular basement membrane wrinkling
Expansion of the space between the glomerular endothelium and lamina densa by electron-lucent material.
Glomerular subendothelial widening
Apoptotic, pyknotic, and fragmented nuclei within the glomerulus.
Glomerular karyhorrhectic debris
An aggregate of coagulated blood containing fibrin, with or without entrapped cellular elements, within a glomerular capillary lumen.
Glomerular fibrin thrombus
Intracapillary amorphous, eosinophilic material consisting of immune deposits.
Glomerular hyaline pseudothrombus
Intracapillary silver-positive material that is finely vacuolated and laminated, and stains with oil red O on frozen sections.
Glomerular lipoprotein thrombus

Extracellular meangial accumulation of finely granular material corresponding to immunoglobulin and/or complement by immunofluorescence/immunohistochemistry; most typically electron-dense although this may decrease with resorption of the deposit.
Mesangial Immune complex deposition
Visceral epithelial cells with 2 nuclei. Can be observed on light or ultrastructral microscopy.
Binucleated visceral epithelial cells
Visceral epithelial cells with more than two nuclei. Can be observed on light or ultrastructral microscopy.
Multinucleated visceral epithelial cells
A deviation from the normal concentration in blood of factor H-related protein 1 (FHR-1)
Abnormal circulating complement factor H related protein 1 concentration
Decreased level of circulating complement factor H related protein 1 concentration in the blood circulation.
Reduced circulating complement factor H related protein 1 concentration
Elevated level of circulating complement factor H related protein 1 concentration in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating complement factor H related protein 1 concentration
An abnormally increased level of 1-methylhistidine in the blood circulation. 1-methylhistidine is a derivative of L-histidine.
Elevated circulating 1-methylhistidine concentration
The concentration of 4-Hydroxyphenylacetic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating 4-hydroxyphenylacetic acid concentration
Abnormally increased amount of a monocarboxylic acid in the urine. Monocarboxylic acids are molecules with one COOH functional group.
Elevated urinary monocarboxylic acid level
Any deviation from the normal concentration of fetuin A in the blood circulation.
Abnormal circulating fetuin A concentration
A reduction below normal of fetuin A in the blood circulation.
Decreased circulating fetuin A concentration
An elevation above normal of fetuin A in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating fetuin A concentration
Excessive growth of the kneecap (patella).
Patellar overgrowth
A type of intussusception of the small intestine in which one part of the ileum invaginates (telescopes) into another part of the ileum.
Ileoileal intussusception
Osmotic diarrhea results from the presence of osmotically active, poorly absorbed solutes in the bowel lumen that inhibit normal water and electrolyte absorption.
Osmotic diarrhea
A tear in the intimal layer of the abdominal aorta causing a separation between the intima and the medial layers.
Abdominal aortic dissection
Structural anomaly located in Bowman's space, which represents the beginning of the urinary space and is contiguous with the proximal convoluted tubule of the nephron.
Abnormal Bowman space morphology
Acellular collagenous matrix within Bowman's space, not associated with extracapillary hypercellularity or necrosis, associated with sclerosis or deflation of the tuft.
Urinary space collagenization
Increased number of visceral epithelial cells (2 or more layers), often with crowding and multilayering, but without continuity with the parietal epithelium.
Visceral epithelial cell hyperplasia
Round to ovoid, Periodic acid-Schiff (PAS)-positive, fuchsinophilic cytoplasmic inclusions within visceral epithelial cells.
Visceral epithelial hyaline droplets

Glomerular crescent refers hyperplastic lesions involving 10% or more of the circumference of Bowman's capsule. Crescents can be composed of a variable mixture of epithelial/leukocyte hypercellularity, fibrous matrix, and fibrin.
Glomerular crescent formation

A type of glomerular crescent characterized by extracapillary hypercellularity of greater than two cell layers and involving more than 10% of the capsular circumference, composed of greater than 75% cells with or without fibrin, and less than 25% fibrous matrix.
Cellular crescent

A type of glomerular crescent characterized by extracapillary hypercellularity of more than 2 cell layers and involving over 10% of the capsular circumference, composed of 25% to 75% cells with or without fibrin, and the remainder fibrous matrix.
Fibrocellular crescent

A type of glomerular crescent characterized by extracapillary fibrosis composed of greater than 75% matrix and of less than 25% cells with or without fibrin, usually associated with disruption of Bowman's capsule and involving over 10% of the capsular circumference.
Fibrous crescent
Loss of mesangial cells segmentally or globally.
Mesangial cell loss

Globally sclerotic glomeruli are that are small and without hyalinosis and may appear with collapse of the tuft with collagenization of the urinary space. Bowman's capsule is completely or partially absent and there is no periglomerular fibrosis and glomerular size is decreased by more than 50% compared to all other glomeruli in the same biopsy. Obsolescent glomeruli may appear to be receding into the interstitium.
Glomerular obsolescence

Double contouring of the original glomerular basement membrane (GBM)/additional layer(s) of overlying basement membrane matrix, with or without endocapillary hypercellularity and no evidence of interposed migrated cells (mesangial, endothelial, monocytes) between the layers of original GBM and de novo GBM.
Glomerular capillary wall duplication without cellular interposition

Double contouring of the original glomerular basement membrane (GBM)/additional layer(s) of overlying basement membrane matrix with interposed migrated cells (mesangial, endothelial, monocytes) between the layers of original GBM and de novo GBM.
Glomerular capillary wall duplication with cellular interposition
The concentration of homovanillic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating homovanillic acid concentration
Increased concentration of sebacic acid in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating sebacic acid concentration
An increased concentration of 4-hydroxyphenlyllactic acid in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating hydroxyphenlyllactic acid concentration

Psoriatic nail abnormality characterized by the presence of neutrophils in the nail bed epithelium, hyperkeratosis with parakeratosis, presence of exudates on the corneal epithelium, focal hypogranulosis and psoriasiform hyperplasia of the nail bed.
Nail psoriasis
Increase in the number of type II pneumocytes.
Type II pneumocyte hyperplasia
Anomaly of the physiological response to maintain the body's posture when movement and position is altered.
Abnormal postural reflex

Abnormal neck-righting response, which is said to be a physiological response when a child is placed flat on his or her back and the head is turned 90 degrees to the right or the left. With a normal neck-righting response, there follows a reflected torsion of the vertebral column in the same direction as the induced rotation of the neck. That is, the whole body follows the direction in which the head was turned. The response is present from birth to the age of five years.
Impaired neck-righting reflex

Presence of one or more manifestations of the acute phase response. Acute phase proteins (APP) are blood proteins primarily synthesized by hepatocytes as part of the acute phase response (APR). The APR is part of the early-defense or innate immune system, which is triggered by different stimuli including trauma, infection, stress, neoplasia, and inflammation. The APR results in a complex systemic reaction with the goal of reestablishing homeostasis and promoting healing.
Acute phase response
An increased concentration of serum amyloid A in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating amyloid A
Limitation of motion of the jaw due to structural changes in a muscle such as the massseter responsible for jaw movement.
Jaw contracture
An anomaly in the development of the embryo, that is, of the early developmental stage of development that follows the fertilization of an egg by sperm.
Abnormal embryonic development
An anomaly in the development of the embryo in a stage prior to implantation.
Abnormal preimplantation embryonic development
Failure of a fertilized oocyte to undergo the first round of cell division.
Zygotic cleavage failure

An anomaly in the process by a a haploid cell is formed from a diploid cells through meiosis. In males, diploid spermatogonia produce two haploid cells (secondary spermatocytes) in meiosis I and four haploid spermatids in meiosis II. In females, primordial germ cells under meiosis II before birth to form primary oocytes. Once puberty cell begins, these cells form secondary oocytes through meiosis II.
Abnormal gametogenesis
Anomalous oocyte meiosis
Abnormal female meiosis
An increased concentration of inosine in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating inosine concentration
Increased concentration of guanosine in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating guanosine concentration
An increased concentration of beta-sitosterol in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating sitosterol concentration
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against aquaporin-4.
Anti-aquaporin 4 antibody positivity
Passage of an increased number of stools containing mucus, a thick fluid substance secreted by mucous membranes.
Mucoid diarrhea

A pleural cobblestone appearance characterized by irregular bumps surrounded by depressed lines in open lung biopsy. Caused by underlying scarring causing retraction of the interlobular septa where they insert on the pleura.
Pleural cobblestoning
Pain (An unpleasant sensory and emotional experience) along the course of a nerve.
Neuralgia
Aura with affective, mnemonic or composite perceptual phenomena including illusory or composite hallucinatory events.
Psychic epileptic aura
A purely subjective manifestation of an epileptic seizure pertaining to altered cognition.
Cognitive epileptic aura

An epileptic aura is a purely subjective clinical manifestation of an epileptic seizure. If an epileptic aura is not followed by loss of awareness or propagation to a bilateral tonic-clonic seizure then it is a type of focal aware non-motor seizure.
Epileptic aura

A fourfold or greater increase of usual seizure frequency within a 3-day period, where the patient demonstrates full recovery between seizure events within the cluster. The seizure cluster should be recognisable by the primary clinician, carer or patient.
Seizure cluster
An increase in the amount of air a person can forcefully expel in one second, compared to some standard or previous measure of same subject.
Elevated forced expiratory volume in one second

Candida infections of the esophagus are considered opportunistic infections and are seen most commonly in immunosuppressed patients, the most common symptoms being dysphagia, odynophagia, and retrosternal pain.
Candida esophagitis

Pulmonary hypertensive crisis involves sudden and potentially lethal increases in PAP and PVR that cause acute rise in right atrial and right ventricular end-diastolic pressure accompanied by low cardiac output.
Pulmonary hypertensive crisis
Any structural anomaly of a blood vessel (artery, arteriole, capillary, venule, or vein).
Abnormal blood vessel morphology
Any deviation from the normal amount of a metabolite in urine.
Abnormal urine metabolite level

An increased level of deoxypyridinoline in the urine. Deoxypyridinoline is a crosslink product of collagen molecules found in bone and excreted in urine during bone degradation, has been described as a marker of bone turnover.
Increased urine deoxypyridinoline level
An abnormally increased level of o-phosphoserine in the blood circulation. o-phosphoserine is a derivative of serine.
Elevated circulating o-phosphoserine concentration
Reduced range of motion turning the head side to side.
Limited head rotation
A deviation from the normal range of concentration of particles in urine.
Abnormal urine osmolality
An abnormally high urinary specific gravity, i.e., increased concentration of solutes in the urine.
Hyperosthenuria

A behavioral abnormality whereby a person is unable to move freely from one situation, activity or aspect of aa problem to another as circumstances demand. Key aspects of shifting include the ability to make transitions, problem solve flexibly, switch or alternate attention, and change focus from one mind-set or topic to another. Mild deficits in the ability to shift compromise the efficiency of problem solving, whereas more severe difficulties are reflected in perseverative behaviors. Sometimes this is described as being rigid or inflexible.
Impaired ability to shift attention
An open sore of the nasal mucosa.
Nasal ulcer
Repeated occurrence of episodes of coughing, with each episode consisting of at least five minutes of continuous coughing.
Recurrent coughing spasms

Hyaline membranes are homogeneous eosinophilic material composed of cellular debris, plasma proteins, and surfactant plastered against alveolar ducts and alveolar walls. The hyaline membranes are deposited along the walls of the alveoli, where gas exchange typically occurs, thereby making gas exchange difficult.
Hyaline membranes
A specific form of lung inflammation that results from accumulation of lipids in the alveoli. Lipoid pneumonia can be either exogenous or endogenous in cause based on the source of the lipid.
Lipoid pneumonia

A type of lipoid pneumonia in which the source of the lipids is the body itself. When an airway is obstructed, it is often the case that distal to the obstruction, lipid-laden macrophages and giant cells fill the lumen of the disconnected airspace.
Endogenous lipoid pneumonia
A type of lipoid pneumonia in which the source of the lipids is external to the body.
Exogenous lipoid pneumonia
Low level of blood oxygen induced by changing from a recumbent to an upright position.
Orthodeoxia
A type of dyspnea that occurs when the affected person changes from a recumbent to an upright position.
Platypnea

A type of leukodystrophy characterized by multiple small cavitations typically in the periventricular and deep cerebral white matter. The cavitations are visible as a central cavity with cerebrospinal fluid-like signal intensity.
Cavitating leukodystrophy
Telangiectasias (small dilated blood vessels located near the surface of the skin or mucous membranes) located in the trachoebronchial system.
Bronchial telangiectasia

Granulomatous inflammation that surrounds the bronchi and bronchioles, replacing bronchial walls and mucosa. In bronchocentric granulomatosis, the lumen of the airway contains necrotic debris, and palisaded histiocytes surround the lumen.
Bronchocentric granulomatosis

Any deviation from the normal range of KCO. The KCO is a measurement of the rate constant for alveolar uptake of CO during breath-holding in the single breath measurement of DLCO at full inflation. The DLCO is derived as the product of the KCO and the single breath alveolar volume (VA) divided by PB-PH2O.
Abnormal KCO
Increased diffusion capacity of the lung for carbon monoxide (CO) rate constant (efficiency index).
Increased KCO
Decreased diffusion capacity of the lung for carbon monoxide (CO) rate constant (efficiency index).
Decreased KCO

Anthracosis is the deposition of black carbon pigment. It is commonly seen in perihilar lymph nodes as well as within lung parenchyma. There can be prominent storiforming (i.e., spiral patterning) of histiocytes, to such an extent as to mimic a neoplastic lesion histologically. Anthracosis is a common finding in smokers and polluted city dwellers.
Anthracosis
Increased width of the alveolar septum, which is the structure that separates neighboring alveoli. This finding can be appreciated on histology.
Alveolar septal thickening

Presence of increased numbers of bombesin-immuno-positive neuroendocrine cells (NECs) within distal airways. There are no formal criteria for an increase (which is also dependend on the sensitivity of the staining method), findings of neuroendocrine cells in at least 70% of bronchioles by lung biopsy and at least 10% NECs in an individual airway are consistent with the diagnosis of Neuroendocrine cell hyperplasia of infancy in the appropriate clinical setting. Increases are also seen in other clicnial settings. Neuroendocrine neoplasms of the lung encompass NE tumors (NETs), which split into typical and atypical carcinoids, and NE carcinomas (NECs).
Increased airway neuroendocrine cells
Presence of increased numbers of bombesin-immuno-positive neuroendocrine cell cluster (neuroepithelial bodies) in the alveolar ducts.
Increased airway neuroepithelial bodies
The presence of a left and a right superior vena cava.
Bilateral superior vena cava
Inflammation of the cartilage of the nose.
Nasal chondritis
Abnormally increased concentration of O-stearoylcarnitine in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating stearoylcarnitine concentration
Abnormally increased concentration of palmitoylcarnitine in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating palmitoylcarnitine concentration
Reduced level of the compound muscle action potential (CMAP), which is recorded following electrical stimulation of a nerve from surface electrodes overlying a muscle supplied by that nerve.
Decreased compound muscle action potential amplitude
Increased level in the urine of a metabolite that results from collagen degradation, e.g., a fragment of a collagen produced by a collagenase or serine protease.
Elevated urinary collagen degradation products
An increased amount of pyridinoline in the urine.
Elevated urine pyridinoline level
Abnormal concentration in the blood circulation of a metabolite that results from collagen degradation, e.g., a fragment of a collagen produced by a collagenase or serine protease.
Abnormal circulating collagen degradation product concentration
An increased concentration of hydroxylysyl-pyridinoline (pyridinoline) in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating pyridinoline concentration
Any structural abnormality of a bronchial artery.
Abnormal bronchial artery morphology
Abnormal arterial anastomosis (connection) between bronchial and pulmonary arteries.
Bronchopulmonary anastomosis
Increased caliber of a bronchial artery, which can be defined as a bronchial artery diameter that exceeds 2 mm.
Bronchial artery dilatation
Increase in the volume of bronchial artery wall due to the enlargement of its component cells.
Bronchial artery hypertrophy
Inflammatory cell infiltration surrounding precapillary pulmonary arteries (arterioles; 20-70 micrometer).
Perivascular pre-capillary pulmonary artery inflammation
Irregular or changing caliber (diameter) along the tail of the sperm.
Irregularly shaped sperm tail
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against carbonic anhydrase II.
Anti-carbonic anhydrase II antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against lactoferrin.
Antilactoferrin antibody positivity
Presence of ropey, eosinophilic material (brght red on Trichrome staining) consistent with extracapillary fibrin outside of capillary lumina.
Glomerular extracapillary fibrin
The presence of eosinophilic Periodic Acid Schiff (PAS)-positive cell free, protein-derived material occupying Bowman's space.
Bowman-space proteinaceous debris
Deposits of hyalinized collagen fibres in the parietal pleura (preferentially pleura adjacent to ribs, particularly the sixth through ninth ribs).
Pleural plaque

Fever that persists longer than expected for an acute infectious disease. No precise threshold exists, and the clinical interpretation of fever is context-dependent, but as a rule of thumb, this term refers to fever that persists longer than 2-3 weeks.
Persistent fever
A sudden onset of abdominal pain with associated nausea or vomiting. The acute abdomen may be caused by an infection, inflammation, vascular occlusion, or obstruction.
Acute abdomen

Ischemia is defined as a restriction of arterial blood supply to a tissue associated with insufficient oxygenation to support the metabolis requirements of the tissue. Depending on the involved tissues, clinical manifestations may include pain, pallor, lack of pulse, coldness, paresthesia, and paralysis. Additional associated manifestations include hemodynamic parameters (reduced blood pressure distal to the site of restricted arterial supply) and angiographic evidence of arterial occclusion.
Tissue ischemia

Restriction of arterial blood supply to a digit (finger or toe) associated with insufficient oxygenation to support the metabolic requirements of the digit. Clinical manifestations may include pain, pallor, lack of pulse, coldness, paresthesia, and paralysis.
Digital ischemia

Restriction of arterial blood supply to a testis associated with insufficient oxygenation to support the metabolic requirements of the tissue. Clinical manifestations may include pain and swelling of the affected testis.
Testicular ischemia

Restriction of arterial blood supply to the intestine associated with insufficient oxygenation to support the metabolic requirements of the tissue. Acute intestinal ischemia can involve the small or large intestine, and usually presents with sudden severe non-specific abdominal pain.
Intestinal ischemia
Any deviation from the normal concentration of an organic amino compound, defined as a compound formally derived from ammonia by replacing one, two or three hydrogen atoms by organyl groups.
Abnormal circulating organic amino compound concentration
An increased concentration of o-phosphoethanolamine in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating o-phosphoethanolamine concentration
Elevated amount of acetoacetic acid in the urine.
Elevated urine acetoacetic acid level
An increased level of acetoacetic acid in the blood circulation. Acetoacetic acid is one of the predominant ketone bodies.
Elevated circulating acetoacetic acid concentration
An increased amount of 2-hydroxybutyric acid in the urine.
Elevated urinary 2-hydroxybutyric acid
An increased blood concentration of cartilage oligomeric matrix protein (COMP).
Elevated circulating cartilage oligomeric matrix protein concentration
Inability to initiate changes in activity or movement and to perform ordinary volitional movements rapidly and easily in the lower extremities.
Lower extremity akinesia
Inability to initiate changes in activity or movement and to perform ordinary volitional movements rapidly and easily in the upper extremities.
Upper extremity akinesia

Abnormally diminished movement of the upper extremities. In contrast to paralysis, hypokinesia is not characterized by a lack of motor strength, but rather by a poverty of movement. The typical habitual movements (e.g., folding the arms, crossing the legs) are reduced in frequency.
Upper extremity hypokinesia

Abnormally diminished movement of the lower extremities. In contrast to paralysis, hypokinesia is not characterized by a lack of motor strength, but rather by a poverty of movement. The typical habitual movements (e.g., folding the arms, crossing the legs) are reduced in frequency.
Lower extremity hypokinesia
The accumulation of pericardial fluid with subsequent compression of all cardiac chambers which prevents cardiac filling.
Cardiac tamponade
Reduced ability to bring the leg toward the midline of the body.
Hip adductor weakness
An increased concentration in the blood circulation of a hydroxybutyric acid, that is, of a compound comprising a butyric acid core carrying at least one hydroxy substituent.
Elevated circulating hydroxybutyric acid concentration
Elevation of the 2-hydroxybutyric acid concentration in the blood above the normal range.
Elevated circulating 2-hydroxybutyric acid concentration
Elevation of the 3-hydroxybutyric acid concentration in the blood above the normal range.
Elevated circulating 3-hydroxybutyric acid concentration
Focal proliferation of pulmonary artery endothelial cells, leading to the formation of complex capillary-like channels.
Pulmonary arterial plexiform lesion

Increased thickness of the intimal layer of the pulmonary artery. Throughout the pulmonary arterial tree, the thin intima consists of a non-fenestrated monolayer of endothelial cells lining the vessel lumen, as well as a sub-endothelial interstitium that extends to the internal elastic lamina. Intimal thickness in human lung ranges from 1-16% of total wall thickness. Pulmonary artery intimal thickening can be defined as a relative intima thickness to the thickness of the vessel wall of over 10%.
Pulmonary artery intimal thickening
Increased amount of collagen, proteoglycans, and other extracellular matrix proteins resulting in scarring and thickening in the adventia of the pulmonary arterial tree.
Pulmonary artery adventitial fibrosis

A form of pulmonary arterial hypertension in which there is a reduction of mean pulmonary artery pressure (mPAP) at leasy 10 mmHg to reach an absolute value of mPAP not more than 40 mmHg with an increased or unchanged cardiac output (CO) in response to inhaled nitric oxide at 10-20 ppm.
Pulmonary arterial hypertension with positive acute response to NO challenge

A form of pulmonary arterial hypertension with lack of adequate hemodynamic response to NO challenge (adequate response is defined as a reduction of mean pulmonary artery pressure (mPAP) of at least 10 mmHg to reach an absolute value of mPAP 40 mmHg or less with an increased or unchanged cardiac output (CO) in response to inhaled nitric oxide at 10-20 ppm).
Pulmonary arterial hypertension with lack of acute response to NO challenge
Erythema (redness of the skin caused by hyperemia in superficial capillaries) in the region surrounding a fingernail or toe nail.
Periungual erythema

Venous air embolism is a consequence of air being introduced into the venous circulation, and subsequently to the right heart, and pulmonary circulation. When small amounts of air reach pulmonary circulation they can be removed by gas diffusion across the arteriolar wall into the alveoli, amounts of gas exceeding 50 ml can cause pulmonary outflow tract obstruction with or without concomitant arterial embolisation.
Pulmonary air embolism
Focal accumulation of dilated pulmonary capillaries.
