It is characterized by features including (i) Round or pyramidal shape instead of ovoid shape; (ii) Medial position of the hippocampus on the hippocampal sulcus; (iii) The collateral sulcus is excessively deep or verticalized; (iv) Fimbria located medial to the hippocampus; (v) Small or displaced fornix; (vi) Enlarged temporal horn and empty choroid fissure; (vii) Thickened subiculum; (viii) Reduced upper horizontal portion of the parahippocampal gyrus.
Hippocampal malrotation
Claw toes are characterized by hyperextension at the metatarsal-phalangeal joints and flexion of the interphalangeal joints.
Claw toe deformity

Abnormal positioning of toe phalanges. Deformities of the lesser toes often occur gradually, though they can be brought on by trauma. The main adult sagittal plane deformities consist of claw toes, hammer toes and mallet toes. Axial plane deformities include crossover toes.
Toe deformity

Increased duration of the central motor conduction time (CMCT). The CMCT estimates the conduction time of corticospinal fibers between motor cortex and spinal (or bulbar) motoneurons. It includes the times for excitation of cortical cells, conduction via the corticobulbar-corticospinal tract and excitation of the motoneuron sufficient to reach its firing threshold. CMCT is calculated by subtracting the peripheral conduction time from the MEP latency recorded after cortical stimulation.
Prolonged central motor conduction time
Ringed creases of the skin of the extremities related to folding of excess skin.
Circumferential skin creases on extremities

An aggressive malignant embryonal neoplasm arising from the central nervous system. It is composed of cells with a large eccentric nucleus, prominent nucleolus, and abundant cytoplasm. Mutations of the SMARCB1 gene or very rarely SMARCA4 (BRG1) gene are present. The vast majority of cases occur in childhood. Symptoms include lethargy, vomiting, cranial nerve palsy, headache, and hemiplegia.
Atypical teratoid/rhabdoid tumor

A highly aggressive, extremely rare neoplasm of the kidney that is usually seen in children. The term rhabdoid is used because the tumor cells resemble rhabdomyoblasts but lack myogenic markers, and pathologic diagnosis requires familiarity with these microscopic features plus awareness that adult onset is possible. It can be associated with abnormalities of chromosome 22. It is characterized by the presence of cells with a large eccentric nucleus, prominent nucleolus, and abundant cytoplasm.
Rhabdoid tumor of the kidney
A form of T-cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma in which cytotoxic CD8+ T cells infiltrate adipose tissue forming subcutaneous nodules.
Subcutaneous panniculitis-like T-cell lymphoma
Presence of hyphae (long, branching, filamentous structures produced by fungi) in sputum.
Fungal hyphae in sputum
Increasaed size of the tectum, which is the region of the midbrain posterior to the cerebral aqueduct of Sylvius. The midbrain is the most superior portion of the brainstem.
Enlarged tectum
Elevated CSF angiotensin-converting enzyme concentration
Decreased concentration of 3-ketoacyl-CoA thiolase in th blood circulation.
Reduced circulating 3-ketoacyl-CoA thiolase concentration

A dark, keratotic papule about 2-10 mm in diameter, usually occuring on the lower extremeities. Usually the lesions begin as bright, soft, and nonkeratotic paules which grow larger and change to a firm, blue to black and keratotic stage.
Solitary angiokeratoma

A type of angiokeratoma that most commonly occurs on the scrotum of patients who are 40 years old or older. The typical single lesion is a dark red to blue dome-shaped papule 2-4 mm in diameter with a very discrete keratotic surface. Typically, they are multiple and arranged in a line parallel to the raphe mediana of the scrotum. They also occur on the vulva and less commnly on the penis.
Fordyce angiokeratoma

A type of angiokeratoma that typically presents in childhood as a large, mostly linear and unilateral hyperkeratotic plaque which is composed of confluent keratotic papules. The size ranges from a few centimeters up to a major part of the body surface. Initially the lesions present asa multile reddish macules, clinically similar to a nevus flammeus. Within several years they develop into acanthokeratotic papules that agrregate into plaques which may have a hyperkeratotic surface.
Angiokeratoma circumscriptum naeviforme
A type of angiokeratoma that typically presents in women on the dorsa of fingers and toes and multiple dark red papules with a slightly verrucous surface, each measuring about 3-5 mm in diameter.
Angiokeratoma of Mibelli

A lump in the region of the larynx. A mass is any lump in the body that can be caused by the abnormal growth of cells, a cyst, hormonal changes or an immune reaction. Typically a mass is an initial finding that will lead to additional workup. Laryngeal masses can be visualized by multiple methods include computed tomography.
Laryngeal mass

A lump in the region of the palate. A mass is any lump in the body that can be caused by the abnormal growth of cells, a cyst, hormonal changes or an immune reaction. Typically a mass is an initial finding that will lead to additional workup.
Palate mass
Increased thickness of an oral frenulum, flaps of mucous membrane that extend from the midline gingiva to the upper or lower lip.
Thick oral frenulum
A type of dental trauma characterized by total dislocation of the tooth from its socket.
Tooth avulsion
Laceration or tear of an oral frenulum, flaps of mucous membrane that extend from the midline gingiva to the upper or lower lip.
Torn oral frenulum
A wound of the mucosa within the oral cavity covering lips, tongue, palate, gingiva, pharynx, or retropharynx.
Intraoral laceration

An erythematous lesion of the oral mucosa may result from a variety of tissue alterations, including inflammation, erythrocyte extravasation, and atrophy or reduced keratinization of the surface epithelium.
Erythematous oral mucosa
Breakage of the chordae tendinae of the mitral valve. This can lead to loss of tension of one of the mitral valve leaflets and mitral regurgitation.
Mitral chordae tendinae rupture
Indicates that a cardiovascular procedure such as stenting, bypass, catherization was performed on a patient.
History of cardiovascular procedure

A high-pitched sound that occurs at the moment of maximal opening of the aortic or pulmonary valves. They are heard just after the first heart sound. The sounds occur in the presence of a dilated aorta or pulmonary artery or in the presence of a bicuspid or flexible stenotic aortic or pulmonary valve. Ejection clicks may also be called ejection sounds.
Ejection click
Cryofibrinogen is an abnormal protein that forms precipitate only in plasma. consisting of fibrinogen, fibronectin, alpha1-antitrypsin and alpha2-macroglobulin.
Cryofibrinogenemia
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to allergens.
triggered by allergens
A type of tinnitus that presents as clicks, resembling the noise made by the snapping together of 2 fingers.
Clicking tinnitus
Abnormally low amount of sulfur in hair.
Reduced hair sulfur content
Secretion of colored sweat.
Chromhidrosis
Secretion of pus-like (purulent) material from the eye, which may caused the eyelids to be matted together.
Purulent eye discharge
Disproportionately large eyelids
Megaloblepharon
Presence of bacteria in the cerebrospinal fluid, as manifested by visual inspection or bacterial culture results.
Bacteria in cerebrospinal fluid
Abnormal joint physiology
A popping, clicking or crackling sound that accompaniees movement of a joint.
Joint crepitus
Applies to the localization of a skin lesion involving any area of the body where two opposing skin surfaces can touch and rub or chaff.
Intertriginous distribution

Applies to the localization of a skin lesion that correspond to skin tension lines, which are linear clefts in the skin that indicate the direction of orientation of the underlying collagen fibers. Skin tension lines are also known as Langer's lines or lines of cleavage.
Distributed along skin tension lines
Presence of any form of communication (e.g., verbal or non-verbal) that does not align with cultural expectations or developmental level.
Abnormal communication

Any abnormality of eye contact behavior. We define eye contact as a form of nonverbal communication between two individuals who are facing each other in which an individual directs the eyes towards the eyes or face of the other individual. Eye contact occurs frequently and voluntarily during face-to-face verbal communication. The duration and frequency of eye contact that is interpreted to be appropriate may follow social and situational norms.
Abnormal eye contact
A deliberate avoidance of eye contact.
Gaze avoidance
Tendency to maintain sustained eye contact for an inappropriately long period of time.
Excessive eye contact
Inflammation of glans penis
Balanitis
Applies to an abnormality that is situated in the arched middle portion of the foot in front of the ankle joint (i.e., instep).
Instep location
Applies to a skin lesion that is improved or made more bearable by exposure to ultraviolet light (sunshine or phototherapy).
Ameliorated by ultraviolet light exposure
An reduced concentration of aspartic acid in the blood circulation.
Decreased circulating aspartic acid concentration

Any deviation from the normal concentration of erythropoietin in the blood circulation. Erythropoietin is a glycoprotein hormone produced by the peritubular cells of the kidney that stimulates red blood cell production.
Abnormal circulating erythropoietin concentration
Decreased concentration of erythropoietin in the blood circulation. Erythropoietin is a glycoprotein hormone produced by the peritubular cells of the kidney that stimulates red blood cell production.
Reduced circulating erythropoietin concentration
Any deviation from the normal level of the enzyme gamma-glutamyltransferase (GGT). GGT is mainly present in kidney, liver, and pancreatic cells, but small amounts are present in other tissues.
Abnormal gamma-glutamyltransferase level
Decreased level of the enzyme gamma-glutamyltransferase (GGT). GGT is mainly present in kidney, liver, and pancreatic cells, but small amounts are present in other tissues.
Reduced gamma-glutamyltransferase level
Increased concentration of histamine in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating histamine concentration
An increased concentration of interleukin-18 in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating interleukin 18 concentration
Any deviation from the normal ratio of blood phytanic acid concentration to pristanic acid concentration.
Abnormal phytanic acid:pristanic acid ratio
An elevation above the normal ratio of blood phytanic acid concentration to pristanic acid concentration.
Increased phytanic acid:pristanic acid ratio
A reduction below the normal ratio of blood phytanic acid concentration to pristanic acid concentration.
Decreased phytanic acid:pristanic acid ratio
An aberrant, pathological communication between the rectum and the bladder.
Rectovesical fistula
An abnormal connection (fistula) between the rectum and the ureter.
Rectoureteral fistula
Underdevelopment of the umbilicus.
Hypoplastic umbilicus

Arachnoid granulations (AGs) are tufts of arachnoid membrane invaginated into the dural sinuses through which cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) enters the venous system. The lesions are primarily located in the parasagittal region along the superior sagittal sinus, which is occasionally seen at the transverse sinus. Normally dural venous sinus AGs typically range from 2 to 8 mm in size, but may grow enough to expand the dural sinuses, and even the inner table, diploic space and outer table of the skull.
Arachnoid granulation
Increased concentration of taurine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
Increased CSF taurine concentration
An abnormally increased level of glutathione in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating glutathione concentration
The concentration of hawkinsin in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Hawkinsinuria
An abnormally increased amount of phenylpyruvic acid in the urine.
Elevated urinary phenylpyruvic acid level
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by lumbar puncture.
Ameliorated by lumbar puncture
An increased level of uracil in the cerebrospinal fluid.
Increased CSF uracil concentration
An abnormally increased amount of kynurenine in the urine.
Elevated urine kynurenine level
An abnormally increased concentration of L-alloisoleucine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
Increased CSF L-alloisoleucine concentration

An increased concentration of hydroxylysine in the blood circulation. Hydroxylysine arises from a post-translational hydroxy modification of lysine and is unique to collagen and proteins containing collagen-like sequences. Elevated concentrations of hydroxylysine may indicate increased bone turnover.
Hydroxylysinemia

An increased amount of L-homocitrulline in the urine. L-homocitrulline is an L-lysine derivative that is L-lysine having a carbamoyl group at the N(6)-position. It is found in individuals with urea cycle disorders.
Homocitrullinuria
An increase in the level of 2-hydroxyadipic acid in the urine.
2-hydroxyadipic aciduria
An increased amount of homoarginine in the urine. Homoarginine is a nonproteinogenic alpha amino acid.
Homoargininuria
An increased concentration of cysteine in the urine.
Increased urinary cysteine level
Gastric xanthomas (also known as xanthelasmas) are are plaque-like red lesions defined by the presence of histiocytic containing lipids.
Gastric xanthoma
Reduced amount of pancreatic elastase in the stool. This feature may be observed with pancreatic insufficiency.
Decreased stool elastase level
Elevated amount of chloride in the stool.
Elevated stool chloride content
Abnormal relative increase in the amount of fecal coproporphyrin III as compared to coproporphyrin I in the feces.
Increased fecal coproporphyrin III:coproporphyrin I ratio
Abnormally high concentration of harderoporphyrin in feces.
Increased fecal harderoporphyrin
Abnormally high concentration of heptacarboxylporphyrin in feces.
Increased fecal heptacarboxylporphyrin
Abnormally high concentration of pentacarboxylporphyrin in feces.
Increased fecal pentacarboxylporphyrin
Abnormally high concentration of isocoproporphyrin in feces.
Increased fecal isocoproporphyrin
Identification of Clostridium botulinum toxin in the feces.
Positive fecal Clostridium botulinum test

Abnormal union of the membranous surfaces of the liver capsule and the parietal peritoneum due to inflammation or injury. Adhesions may be visualized by laparoscopy and may have a violin string appearance.
Perihepatic adhesions
Abnormal increase in diameter (expansion) of the vas deferens.
Dilated vas deferens
Abnormal increase in the size of the epididymis.
Enlarged epididymis
Absent epididymidis

Spontaneous production of communicative gestures that are perceived as odd or mechanical, or are poorly integrated with other means of communication. This may include inaccurate mimicry of typical gestures.
Atypical gestures
Abnormal spinal cord physiology
The presence of lymphocytes with multilple vacuoles (a membrane-bound cell organelle) in the bone marrow.
Bone marrow vacuolated lymphocytes
The presence of calcium deposition in the spinal cord.
Spinal cord calcifications

A benign epithelial-lined cystic lesion that can occur anywhere in the neuraxis. Neuroepithelial cysts are ependymal or epithelial lined fluid collections of unknown etiology within the central nervous system parenchyma with no obvious ventricular or subarachnoid connection. Most cysts are asymptomatic, however, some present with seizures, mass effect, or rarely with movement disorders. On imaging, they present as CSF-like parenchymal cysts with smooth, rounded borders and minimal or no surrounding signal intensity abnormality.
Neuroepithelial cyst
A diminished concentration of interleukin-7 in the circulation.
Reduced circulating interleukin 7 concentration
An increased concentration of interleukin-12 in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating interleukin 12 concentration
An increased concentration of interleukin-13 in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating interleukin 13 concentration
An increased concentration of interleukin-2 in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating interleukin 2 concentration
An increased concentration of interleukin-4 in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating interleukin 4 concentration
An increased concentration of interleukin-5 in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating interleukin 5 concentration
An inflammation of the fallopian tube.
Salpingitis
A tubo-ovarian abscess (TOA) is a complex infectious mass of the adnexa that forms as a sequela of pelvic inflammatory disease.
Tubo-ovarian abscess
White appearance (radio-opaqueness) of a paranasal sinus on radiography.
Opacified paranasal sinuses
An increased in the level of glutamine in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Elevated brain glutamine level by MRS
A deviation from normal in the level of glutamine in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Abnormal brain glutamine level by MRS
The concentration of hexanoic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Increased urinary hexanoic acid level

Hepatic focal nodular hyperplasia (FNH) is a benign hepatic tumor. FNH develops within hepatic parenchymal tissue that is otherwise histologically normal. Macroscopically, the tumor is characterized by the presence of depressed, grayish-white scar, which is generally (but not always) located at the center of the lesion, with fibrous septa radiating outward, toward the periphery of the tumor. This stellate scar is found in only 50% of all FNH nodules, but its presence is regarded as pathognomonic. The lesion itself is usually lighter in color than the tissue that surrounds it, and it sometimes has a yellowish hue. FNH nodules are generally not capsulated; their margins are well defined, and they are sometimes lobulated.
Hepatic focal nodular hyperplasia
An increased amount of iron in the bone marrow.
Increased bone marrow iron
A fracture of the glenoid fossa, a relatively shallow dish is located on the lateral scapula and is the socket portion of the shoulder joint that meets to articulate the humeral head.
Glenoid fracture
Abnormal increase in the width of the mediastinum, often defined as being greater than 6 to 8 cm.
Widened mediastinum
Abnormal decrease in the width of the mediastinum.
Narrow mediastinum
Ovarian torsion is a twisting of the ligaments that support the adnexa, cutting off the blood flow to the ovary.
Ovarian torsion

Septate gallbladder is characterized by the presence of a septum that divides the gallbladder in two chambers. When the septum dividing the gallbladder lies longitudinally it is called bilobed gallbladder and when there is a transverse septum separating the fundus from the rest of the gallbladder it is called an hour-glass gallbladder.
Septate gallbladder
Abnormal increased in the thickness of the wall of the gallbladder.
Gallbladder wall thickening
Abnormal increased in the thickness of the size of the gallbladder.
Gallbladder enlargement
An abnormal lesion or swelling seen on gallbladder imaging.
Gallbladder mass

Fingerprint bodies are inclusion bodies located at the periphery of the muscle fibers underneath the sarcolemma (subsarcolemmal), consisting of non-membrane-bound packed lamellae arranged in concentric patterns resembling fingerprints.
Fingerprint bodies

An accumulation of myofilamentous material within individual muscle fibers, forming usually round but occasionally elongated bodies ranging from 2 to 15 pm in size. The so-called spheroid bodies stain green with the modified trichrome preparation and are mainly present in the periphery of type 1 muscle fibers, where they may occupy large sectors sharply demarcated from the remainder of the cross-sectioned muscle fiber.
Spheroid bodies
Any deviation from the normal activity or histological staining of an enzyme in muscle tissue, usually measured in a muscle biopsy specimen.
Abnormal muscle tissue enzyme activity or level
Diminished activity of the enzyne aconitase in muscle tissue.
Reduced muscle aconitase activity

A cancer of the ureter that most often arises in the distal third of the ureter and is often diagnosed during the sixth and seventh decades of life. The most common presentation is gross hematuria or flank pain.
Transitional-cell carcinoma of the ureter
An elevation in the concentration of interferon alpha measured in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating Interferon-alpha concentration
A benign (noncancerous) tumorlike malformation made up of an abnormal mixture of cells and tissues that originates in the liver.
Liver hamartoma

Ameloblastoma is a benign odontogenic tumor generally present in the jaw bone. The tumor originates from the residual epithelium of the tooth germ, epithelium of odontogenic cysts stratified squamous epithelium and epithelium of the enamel organ.
Ameloblastoma
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by following a ketogenic diet.
Ameliorated by ketogenic diet
Darkening of the area of skin that overlies the shin.
Pretibial hyperpigmentation
Gums that are easily damaged.
Gingival fragility
The presence of inclusion bodies within the cytoplasm of muscle cells that react positively with acid fuchsin.
Muscle fiber fuchsinophilic inclusion bodies
Deterioration of the cells of the myenteric plexus (also known as the Auerbach plexus) located between the layers of the muscular propria of the esophagus.
Esophageal myenteric plexus degeneration
Scaling and overgrowth of horny tissue of the skin surrounding body orifices (including peri-auricular, peri-oral, peri-anal areas.
Periorificial hyperkeratosis
Presence of an elevated number of eosinophils in a lymph node (usually as demonstrated by lymph node biopsy).
Eosinophilic lymph node infiltration

Detection of a parasitic organism in the blood stream. Blood parasites include malaria plasmodia, microfilaria species, trypanosomes (the causative agents of African sleeping sickness and South American Changas disease) and the causative agents of schistosomiasis of the bladder and the intestine.
Blood parasite
Presence of trypomastigote parasites in the blood stream. This finding can be demonstrated by the identification of trypomastigote parasites on peripheral blood smear.
Bloodstream trypomastigotes

A primary low-grade, malignant bone tumor that is predominantly located in the mid-portion of the tibia. Histologically, classic adamantinoma is a biphasic tumor characterized by epithelial and osteofibrous components that may be intermingled with each other in various proportions and differentiating patterns.
Adamantinoma
Deviation from the normal activity of an enzyme in muscle tissue.
Abnormal enzyme activity in muscle tissue

Reduced activity of phosphoglycerate kinase (PGK) in muscle tissue. PGK is a glycolytic enzyme that catalyses one of the two ATP-producing reactions in the glycolytic pathway, through the conversion of 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate to 3-phosphoglycerate.
Reduced muscle phosphoglycerate kinase activity
Diminished production of type III procollagen by cultured skin fibroblasts.
Reduced fibroblast type III procollagen synthesis

Diminished activity of the enzyme myoadenylate deaminase. Myoadenylate deaminase is the muscle isoform of adenosine monophosphate (AMP) deaminase and catalyzes the deamination of AMP to inosine monophosphate and ammonia.
Reduced muscle myoadenylate deaminase activity
A developmental defect of a long bone, such as the femur or the humerus, characterized by a sharply curve deviation located in the metaphysis (shaft) of the bone.
Bent long bone
A break or tear in the trachea.
Tracheal rupture
Elevated amount of glycogen in the myocardium.
Increased myocardial glycogen content
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to a monoamine oxidase inhibitor.
Triggered by monoamine oxidase inhibitor
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to a serotonin reuptake inhibitor.
Triggered by serotonin reuptake inhibitor
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with acetazolamide.
Ameliorated by acetazolamide

Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with a medication. Terms in this subhierarchy are intended to be used for cases in which the fact that a manifestation of a disease responds to a specific treatment can be used in the differential diagnosis.
Ameliorated by exposure to medication
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with vitamin B12.
Ameliorated by vitamin B12
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with thiamine.
Ameliorated by thiamine
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with dantrolene.
Ameliorated by dantrolene
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with biotin.
Ameliorated by biotin
Decreased in average size (diameter) of megakaryocytes in the bone marrow. Megakaryocyte diameter can be assessed as using automated cellular imaging systems.
Reduced bone-marrow megakaryocyte size
Long narrow depressions running lengthwise in hairshafts. This feature can be appreciated by scanning electron microsopy.
Hairshafts with longitudinal grooves
Presence of viable mycobacteria in the blood.
Mycobacterium bacteremia
Reduced activity of the enzyme delta-aminolevulinate dehydratase. The enzyme is active in erythrocytes.
Decreased delta-aminolevulinate dehydratase activity
Increased activity of the enzyme pancreatic secretory trypsin inhibitor in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating pancreatic secretory trypsin inhibitor activity

A developmental anomaly in which an individual with an X chromosome and a Y chromosome (usually 46,XY) has a uterus. The uterus and Fallopian tubes are derived from the MÃ¼llerian duct and thus this phenotype is generally also associated with the presence of Fallopian tubes.
Presence of uterus in 46,XY individual
Deposition of calcium in meconium present in the internal cavity of the fetal bowel. This manifestation may be the result of any distal intestinal obstruction.
Intraluminal meconium calcification
A developmental defect characterized by underdevelopment of hte portal vein.
Portal vein hypoplasia
Adrenal leiomyoma is a rare, benign solid tumor that develops from the smooth muscle of the adrenal vein and its tributaries
Adrenal leiomyoma
Infiltration of the wall of the small intestine by lymphocytes and mature plasma cells.
Small intestinal lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to neuroleptic (also known as antipsychotic) medication.
Triggered by neuroleptic medication
Structural anomaly of peroxisomes, which are small, membrane-enclosed metabolic organelles with roles in the metabolism of complex lipids and reactive ionic species.
Abnormal peroxisomal morphology
Lack of observable peroxisomes. This feature can be observed by immunohistochemical staining of cultured cells (such as fibroblasts) or by electronmicroscopy.
Absence of peroxisomes
Reduced number of observable peroxisomes per cell. This feature can be observed by immunohistochemical staining of cultured cells (such as fibroblasts) or by electronmicroscopy.
Paucity of peroxisomes
Reduced activity of the enzyme sulfide:quinone oxidoreductase, which typically is measured in a biopsy specimen from liver or muscle.
Reduced sulfide:quinone oxidoreductase activity
Refers to distribution of neurological deficits that corresponds to a deficit of a specific spinal segment and all segments below it.
Deficit at segmental level

Rhabdoid tumors are rare aggressive malignancies in infants and young children with a poor prognosis. The most common anatomic localizations are the central nervous system, the kidneys, and other soft tissues.
Rhabdoid tumor
A highly aggressive, extremely rare neoplasm of the ovary that is usually seen in children. The term rhabdoid is used because the tumor cells resemble rhabdomyoblasts but lack myogenic markers.
Rhabdoid tumor of the ovary

A rare and aggressive neoplasms developing mainly in the kidney but also in cerebral and extra-cerebral tissues and rarely in the heart. Histologically, rhabdoid renal and extrarenal tumors share common characteristics. The cells are polygonal, with eccentric, vesicular nuclei and prominent nucleoli, eosinophilic cytoplasmic inclusions. The tumors have an infiltrative growth pattern, necrosis, and high proliferative index. The immunohistochemistry tools of investigation facilitate differential diagnosis by showing loss of INI-1 expression, usually accompanied by germline mutations of the SMARCB1 gene. When INI-1 is still expressed in the affected tissues, a rhabdoid tumor with SMARCA4 mutations should be considered.
Cardiac rhabdoid tumor
A rhabdoid tumor (a rare aggressive malignancies in infants and young children with a poor prognosis) originating in the urinary bladder.
Malignant rhabdoid tumor of the bladder

A malginant rhabdoid tumor (MRT) originating in the liver. MRT are best characterized by the presence of round or polygonal cells with abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm, typical eosinophilic perinuclear inclusions, vesicular nuclei and prominent nucleoli. Immunohistochemical expression of vimentin and epithelial markers and lack of staining for S-100, myoglobin and desmin are commonly found, but are non-specific.
Malignant rhabdoid tumor of liver
A malginant rhabdoid tumor (MRT) originating in muscle tissue.
Malignant rhabdoid tumor of muscle
A teratoma located in the neck.
Neck teratoma
A teratoma located in a kidney.
Kidney teratoma
Increased amount of 5-amino-4-imidazolecarboxamide(AICA)-riboside in the urine. AICA-riboside is the dephosphorylated counterpart of AICAR, an intermediate of de novo purine biosynthesis.
Elevated urinary 5-amino-4-imidazolecarboxamide-riboside level
A developmental anomnaly characterized by the lack of development of the posterior communicating artery.
Aplasia of posterior communicating artery
A developmental anomaloy characterized by congenital excavation of the optic nerve head.
Optic pit
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with naloxone, an opioid antagonist.
Ameliorated by naloxone
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by ingestion of pyridoxal phosphate (activated vitamin B6).
Ameliorated by pyridoxal phosphate
Increased width of the vascular wall of portal venules within the liver.
Thickened intrahepatic portal venules
Excessive proliferation of fibroblasts and deposition of extracellular matrix within the ovary.
Ovarian fibrosis

A process in which melanosomes (melanin granules) are deposited in the dermis. The dermal melanosomes are observed to be mainly in macrophages. This phenomenon of pigmentary incontinence usually follows an inflammatory process with the basic feature of basal cell damage, such as in lichen planus, lupus erythematosus, Riehl's melanosis, incontinentia pigmenti (Bloch-Sulzberger), and fixed drug eruption. Incontinence of pigment, or dropping off of epidermal melanin into the dermis, frequently produces a clinically recognizable and characteristic slate-gray pigmentation.
Pigment incontinence
Abnormal epidermal protein expression
Amount of keratin 10 in the epidermis below the lower limit of normal. The findiong is typically ascertained by immunofluorescent microscopy.
Reduced epidermal keratin 10 protein expression
Reduced epidermal collagen IV protein expression
Lower than normal amount of bullous pemphigoid antigen 1 (BP230) in the epidermis.
Reduced epidermal bullous pemphigoid antigen 1 protein expression
Reduced epidermal collagen VII protein expression
Reduced epidermal collagen XVII protein expression
Reduced epidermal integrin alpha6beta4 protein expression
Reduced epidermal plectin protein expression
Presence of Trypanosoma cruzi in the blood stream. Trypanosoma cruzii is the etiological agent of Chagas disease.
Bloodstream Trypanosoma cruzi
A deviation from the normal distribution of cell types or their relative proprotions in a lymph node.
Abnormal lymph node cell composition
Lymph node with increased numbers of macrophages heavily laden with lipids.
Lipid-laden lymph node macrophages
Structural anomal of pancreatic acinus.
Abnormal pancreatic acinus morphology
A developmental defect characterized by underdevelopment of the cochlear nerve.
Cochlear nerve hypoplasia
Level of glutathione in the urine above the upper limit of normal.
Glutathionuria

Nevus psiloliparus is a rare fatty tissue nevus that is a marker for encephalocraniocutaneous lipomatosis, a neurocutaneous syndrome with ocular and central nervous system anomalies. Clinically, nevus psiloliparus is often described as a congenital alopecia and appears as an irregularly shaped, circumscribed area of alopecia on the scalp. Histopathology demonstrates a near-complete absence of mature hair follicles with preservation of arrector pili muscles and mature adipocytes within the dermis.
Nevus psiloliparus

Crypt hyperplasia denotes elongation of the length of the crypts of Lieberkuhn, a process that initially precedes villous atrophy. Elongation may be caused by expansion of the lamina propria as a result of the proliferation of stromal cells, an influx of inflammatory cells and tissue remodelling.
Crypt hyperplasia
Concentration of dehydroepiandrosterone-sulfate in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Increased circulating dehydroepiandrosterone-sulfate concentration
Any deviation from the normal concentration of thyroxine-binding globulin (TBG) in the blood circulation.
Abnormal circulating thyroxine-binding globulin concentration
A reduction from the normal concentration of thyroxine-binding globulin (TBG) in the blood circulation.
Decreased circulating thyroxine-binding globulin concentration
An increased concentration of beta-aminoisobutyric acid in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating beta-aminoisobutyric acid concentration
An increased concentration of dihydrouracil in the blood circulation. Dihydrouracil is an intermediate in the catabolism of uracil that is also known as 5,6-dihydrouracil.
Elevated circulating dihydrouracil concentration
An increased concentration of dihydrothymine in the blood circulation. Dihydrouracil is an intermediate in the catabolism of thymine.
Elevated circulating dihydrothymine concentration
An increased concentrationof N-carbamoyl-beta-alanine in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating N-carbamoyl-beta-alanine concentration
An increased concentration of 5-hydroxymethyluracil in the blood circulation.
Elevated ciculating 5-hydroxymethyluracil concentration
Concentration of creatinine in the cerebrrospinal fluid below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased CSF creatinine concentration
An increased amount of creatine in the urine.
Elevated urinary creatine level
Concentration of biotin in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating biotin concentration

Concentration of thrombopoietin in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. Thrombopoietin is a glycoprotein hormone produced by the liver and kidney that stimulates the production and differentiation of megakaryocytes.
Elevated circulating thrombopoietin concentration

Concentration or activity of the C1q protein in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal. C1q is the first component of the classical pathway and is composed of the C1qA chain, C1qB chain, and C1qC chain, which are encoded by C1qA, C1qB, and C1qC genes.
Decreased circulating C1q concentration
Concentration of apolipoprotein A-II below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating apolipoprotein A-II concentration
Concentration of CA19-9 above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating CA19-9 concentration
Concentration of DOPA (3,4-dihydroxyphenylalanine) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating DOPA concentration
Concentration of DOPA (3,4-dihydroxyphenylalanine) in the cerebrospinal fluid above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF DOPA concentration

Concentration of porphyrins or of a specific porphryin above the upper limit of normal. The most commonly tested circulating porphyrins are coproporphyrin, protoporphyrin, and uroporphyrin. Normally protoporphyrin is present in the highest concentration.
Elevated circulating porphyrin concentration
Concentration of 17-hydroxyprogesterone in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating 17-hydroxyprogesterone concentration
Concentration of transcobalamin II in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating transcobalamin II concentration

Increased variation in the color of the erythrocytes (red blood cells), including pale red, normal or dark colors, indicating a highly variable hemoglobin concentration. Typically this indicates the release of immature erythrocytes in states of anemia.
Polychromasia
Concentration of myo-inositol in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating myo-inositol concentration
Concentration of arabinitol in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating arabinitol concentration
Amount of arabitol in the urine above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine arabitol level
Amount of erythritol in the urine above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine erythritol level
Concentration of erythritol in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating erythritol concentration
Concentration of matrix metalloproteinase 2 in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced circulating matrix metalloproteinase 2 concentration
Concentration of a coenzyme (an organic molecule that binds to the active sites of an enzyme to promote the catalysis of a reaction) is above or below the limits of normal.
Abnormal circulating coenzyme concentration
Concentration of S-adenosyl methionine (SAM) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal. SAM is a cosubstrate involved in methyl group transfers, transsulfuration, and aminopropylation.
Elevated circulating S-adenosyl methionine concentration

Concentration of membrane cofactor protein in the blood circulation outside the limits of normal. Membrane cofactor protein (MCP, CD46) is a cell surface complement regulatory protein which acts as a cofactor for the factor I-mediated cleavage of the activated complement components C3b/C4b.
Abnormal circulating membrane cofactor protein concentration
Concentration of membrane cofactor protein in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating membrane cofactor protein concentration
Concentration of membrane cofactor protein in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating membrane cofactor protein concentration
Lipid deposits localized within the liver. Xanthomas are benign but are often an important visible sign of systemic conditions such as familial hypercholesterolemia.
Hepatic xanthomatosis
Lipid deposits localized within the adrenal gland. Xanthomas are benign but are often an important visible sign of systemic conditions such as familial hypercholesterolemia.
Adrenal xanthomatosis
Lipid deposits localized within the spleen. Xanthomas are benign but are often an important visible sign of systemic conditions such as familial hypercholesterolemia.
Splenic xanthomatosis
Lipid deposits localized within the spinal cord. Xanthomas are benign but are often an important visible sign of systemic conditions such as familial hypercholesterolemia.
Spinal cord xanthomatosis
Lipid deposits localized within the brain. Xanthomas are benign but are often an important visible sign of systemic conditions such as familial hypercholesterolemia.
Brain xanthomatosis
Lipid deposits localized within the lung. Xanthomas are benign but are often an important visible sign of systemic conditions such as familial hypercholesterolemia.
Pulmonary xanthomatosis
Lipid deposits localized within the bone marrow. Xanthomas are benign but are often an important visible sign of systemic conditions such as familial hypercholesterolemia.
Bone marrow xanthomatosis
Lipid deposits localized within one or more lymph nodes. Xanthomas are benign but are often an important visible sign of systemic conditions such as familial hypercholesterolemia.
Lymph node xanthomatosis
Xanthoma of bone is an exceedingly rare benign primary bone tumor histologically characterized by mononuclear macrophage-like cells, abundant foam cells, and multinucleated giant cells.
Xanthoma of bone
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with folinic acid.
Ameliorated by folinic acid
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to a succinylcholine anesthetic such as suxamethonium.
Triggered by succinylcholine anesthetic
History of having been treated with an exogenous androgen medication.
Exogenous androgen exposure

Diminished activity of the enzyme enolase in muscle tissue. The enzyme enolase catalyzes the interconversion of 2-phosphoglycerate and phosphoenolpyruvate. In adult human muscle, over 90% of enolase activity is accounted for by the beta-enolase subunit, the protein product of the ENO3 gene.
Reduced muscle enolase activity
History of having been treated with a dopamine antagonist including metaclopramide, phenothiazine; haloperidol, chlorpromazine, promethazine, prochlorperazine, ziprasidone, and quetiapine.
Dopamine antagonist exposure
The presence of inclusion bodies within the cytoplasm of muscle cells that contain a mxiture of granules and filaments.
Muscle fiber granulofilamentous inclusion bodies
Formation of vacuoles (a space within a cell that is empty of cytoplasm, lined with a membrane, and filled with fluid) in the cytoplasm of myeloid precursors in the bone marrow.
Bone marrow myeloid vacuolization

A cylindroma located in the lung. Cylindromas are well-circumscribed, smooth, pale pink nodular tumors, often with arborizing vessels visible. The tumors are slow growing and vary in size from a few millimeters to over 5 mm.
Pulmonary cylindroma
Fluid visible on the colonic surface containing fibrin, inflammatory cells, and cellular debris.
Colonic fibrinopurulent exudate

Presence of filaria in the blood stream. Filariasis is a common cause of elephantiasis in Coastal Districts of India. The initial manifestations are repeated episodes of fever with chills and rigor, lymphadenopathy which gradually progress to elephantiasis. In India filarial infestation is commonly caused by W. bancrofti and Brugia malayi, the former responsible for almost 98 percent of all cases.
Bloodstream microfilaria
The presence of an infectious agent in the skin.
Skin infectious agent
Presence of filariae in the skin.
Dermal microfilaria
Accumulation of immunoglobulin A (IgA) surrounding dermal papillae, which are specialized cells that support the hair follicle.
Dermal papillary IgA deposition
Accumulation of antigen-bound antibody in the skin.
Dermal immune complex deposition
The concentration of a metabolite in the liver is above or below the limits of normal.
Abnormal liver metabolite concentration
Intracellular accumulation of polyglucosan bodies-containing amylopectinlike polysaccharide-in the liver.
Hepatic polyglucosan accumulation
A neurofibroma (benign peripheral nerve sheath tumor) located in the urinary bladder.
Urinary bladder neurofibroma
An aggregation of macrophages (forming in response to chronic inflammation) localized in the lining of a joint (synovium).
Synovial granuloma
The concentration of fumaric acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine fumaric acid level
Amoutn of N-acetylaspartate high in the urine above upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine N-acetylaspartic acid level
Level of suberylglycine in urine above upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine suberylglycine level
Level of phenylpropionylglycine in urine above upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine phenylpropionylglycine level
The concentration of octenedioic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine octenedioic acid level
Level of a monocarboxylic acid in the urine above the upper limit of normal. A monocarboxylic acid is an oxoacid containing one carboxy group.
Monocarboxylic aciduria
Amount of octanoic acid in the urine above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine octanoic acid level
The concentration of glutaconic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine glutaconic acid level
The concentration of 3-hydroxyglutaric acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine 3-hydroxyglutaric level
The concentration of malonic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine malonic acid level
Amount of propionylglycine in the urine above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine propionylglycine level
Amount of tiglylglycine in the urine above upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine tiglylglycine level
Amount of 2-methylacetoacetic acid in the urine above upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine 2-methylacetoacetic acid level
Amount of 3-hydroxypropionic acid in the urine above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine 3-hydroxypropionic acid level
Amount of 2-methylcitric acid in the urine above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine 2-methylcitric acid level
Amount of 4-hydroxyisovaleric acid in urine above upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine 4-hydroxyisovaleric acid level

Amount of 2-hydroxy-3-methylvaleric acid in the urine above the upper limit of normal. 2-Hydroxy-3-methylpentanoic acid or 2-hydroxy-3-methylvaleric acid (HMVA) is an organic acid generated by L-isoleucine metabolism.
Elevated urine 2-hydroxy-3-methylvaleric acid level

Lack of full passive range of motion (restrictions in flexion, extension, or other movements) of the shoulder joint resulting from structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules and/or skin.
Shoulder contracture

Lack of the full expected passive range of flexion of the shoulder joint (Shoulder flexion puts the arms from a resting position at one's sides to straight above the head; thus, with shoulder extension contracture it is not possible to raise the arms above the head fully).
Shoulder extension contracture

Movement in the sagittal plane that increases the angle of the thumb joint (straightens the joint); motion involving posterior bending of the vertebral column or returning to the upright position from a flexed position.
Thumb extension contracture
A myxoma (benign soft tissue neoplasm characterized by the presence of spindle and stellate cells, lobulated growth pattern, and myxoid stroma formation) localized in the tongue.
Tongue myxoma
A structural abnormality of the knee joint or surrounding structures.
Abnormal knee morphology
A functional anomaly of the knee joint.
Abnormal knee physiology

Lack of full passive range of motion (restrictions in flexion, extension, or other movements) of the knee joint resulting from structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules and/or skin.
Knee contracture
A type of knee joint contracture in which the knee lacks full expected flexion, such that the upper and lower leg cannot be brought together.
Knee extension contracture
A structural anomaly of the ankle.
Abnormal ankle morphology
A functional anomaly of the ankle.
Abnormal ankle physiology

Lack of full passive range of motion (restrictions in flexion, extension, or other movements) of a toe joint resulting from structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules and/or skin.
Toe joint contracture
A type of toe joint contracture in which the joint lacks full expected flexion, so that the two bony segments on either side of their connecting joint cannot be brought together.
Extension contracture of toe
Ankle contracture
Forefoot pronation contracture
Forefoot supination contracture
Forefoot adduction contracture

Lack of full passive range of motion (restrictions in flexion, extension, or other movements) of a finger joint resulting from structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules and/or skin.
Finger joint contracture
A type of finger joint contracture in which the joint lacks full expected flexion, so that the two bony segments on either side of their connecting joint cannot be brought together.
Extension contracture of finger
Amount of telethonin protein expression in muscle tissue below lower limit of normal. Telethonin is a 19-kDa sarcomeric protein, localized to the Z-disc of skeletal and cardiac muscles.
Reduced muscle telethonin level
Concentration or activity of an enzyme is above or below the limits of normal.
Abnormal enzyme concentration or activity
Concentration or activity of an enzyme is above or below the limits of normal in liver tissue.
Abnormal liver enzyme activity or concentration
Activity of urocanase in the liver below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic urocanase activity

Reduced hydrolysis (splitting of a bond and the addition of the hydrogen anion of water) of the sulfuric ester linkage in the molecule of cerebroside sulfate, possibly leading to accumuation of cerebroside sulfate.
Impaired cerebroside sulfate hydrolysis

Diminished enzyme activity of peroxisomal glutaryl-CoA oxidase, an enzyme that metabolizes glutaryl-CoA (a metabolite of L-lysine, L-hydroxy-lysine and L-tryptophan) by dehydrogenation to glutaconyl-CoA directly followed by decarboxylation of this to crotonyl-CoA.
Reduced peroxisomal glutaryl-CoA oxidase activity

Diminished activity of the enzyme sterol 27-hydroxylase, which participates in the degradation of cholesterol to bile acid. Sterol 27-hydroxylase catalyzes the first step in the normal oxidation of the steroid side chain, converting cholesterol, as well as different 7a-hydroxylated cholesterol metabolites, to 27-oxygenated steroids.
Reduced sterol 27-hydroxylase activity
Diminished activity of the enzyme Short-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase (SCAD), a key enzyme of fatty acid beta-oxidation that catalyses the first step in mitochondrial beta-oxidation of fatty acids.
Reduced short-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase activity

Diminished activity of the enzyme 3-phosphoglycerate dehydrogenase (PGDH), which catalyzes the first step in the pathway by converting D-3-phosphoglycerate (PGA), an intermediate in glycolysis, to phosphohydroxypyruvate concomitant with the reduction of NAD+.
Reduced 3-phosphoglycerate dehydrogenase activity
Increase in length of mitochondria.
Elongated mitochondria
Activity of methionine adenosyltransferase in the liver below the lower limit of normal. Note that there are multiple methionine adenosyltransferase isoezymes.
Reduced hepatic methionine adenosyltransferase activity
Degeneration and loss of neruons in the substantia nigra of the brain.
Substantia nigra dopaminergic neuron loss
A lipoma that is located within a muscle.
Intramuscular lipoma
Dilated blood vessels on the skin.
Cutaneous telangiectasia
Aromatase activity outside of the normal range.
Abnormal aromatase activity
Enzyme activity of aromatase above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated aromatase activity
Enzyme activity of aromatase below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced aromatase activity
A form of amyloidosis that is located in the cornea.
Corneal amyloidosis
Any structural anomaly of the keratinocyte. The keratinocyte is the major cell type of the epidermis and is responsible for generating the protective barrier.
Abnormal keratinocyte morphology
Increased number of vacuoles (membrane-bound organelles that areempty of cytoplasm, lined with a membrane, and filled with fluid) in keratinocytes.
Keratinocyte vacuolization
An adenocarcinoma that arises from the parotid gland.
Parotid gland adenocarcinoma
Cellular inflammation, vessel destruction, and tissue necrosis of the blood vessels of the lung.
Pulmonary vasculitis
Activity of D-glycerate kinase in the liver below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic D-glycerate kinase activity
Phagocytosis of erythrocytes, lymphocytes or other hematopoietic precursors by histiocytes or macrophages in a lymph node.
Lymph-node hemophagocytosis
Underdevelopment of the upper branch of the pubis bone (inferior pubic ramus).
Superior pubic ramus hypoplasia
A rare benign mullerian mixed tumor of the uterus composed of benign epithelial and mesenchymal components.
Uterine adenofibroma

A benign malformation of the lung that includes an abnormal mixture of tissue components such as cartilage, epithelium, fat, or muscle which are common to the lung but without preservation of the organ architecture.
Pulmonary hamartoma
An abnormal histological finding characterized by an increase in the cross-section area of peripheral nerve axons (up to 20-25 micrometers in diameter).
Peripheral axonal distension
Concentration or activity of alpha mannosidase below the lower limit of normal in the blood circulation.
Decreased circulating alpha-mannosidase activity
A structural anomaly of the hepatocyte, which is the main cell type that makes up the liver perncyhma. Hepatocytes are usually binucleated and appear as sheets in the liver tissue.
Abnormal hepatocyte morphology
Accumulation of dark, coarsely granular pigment localized in lysosomes of centrilobular hepatocytes.
Hepatic melanin-like lysosomal pigmentation
Activity of the enzyme uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase (UROD; EC 4.1.1.37) below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase activity
Activity of the enzyme heme oxygenase below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced heme oxygenase activity
The presence of enlarged and swollen neurons that lack Nissl bodies (the rough endoplasmic reticulum-achromasia refers to neurons that lack Nissl bodies) in the cortex of the brain.
Swollen achromatic neurons in the cerebral cortex
Presence of vacuoles (membrane-bound organelles that areempty of cytoplasm, lined with a membrane, and filled with fluid) in hepatocytes, which normally rarely contain vacuoles.
Vacuolated hepatocytes

An abnormality of oocyte maturation characterized by the inability of oocytes to form pronuclei after in vitro fertilization procedures. Oocytes normally show two pronuclei 17 to 20 hours after in vitro insemination.
Lack of oocyte pronucleus formation
A type of skin tumor that initially presents as a reddish macule and subsequently becomes papular, enlarged, ulcerated and ultimately heals leaving pitted scars.
Self-healing squamous epithelioma
Concentration of pristanic acid in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating pristanic acid concentration
Rounded or oval structures that appeared brown on hematoxylin and eosin and red on the modified Gomori trichrome stain.
Sarcoplasmic bodies
Elevated CSF hydroxyproline concentration

Concentration of cystine in the cerebrospinal fluid below the lower limit of normal. Cystine is sulfur-containing amino acid obtained by the oxidation of two cysteine molecules which are then linked via a disulfide bond.
Reduced CSF cystine concentration
Activity of the enzyme beta-mannosidase outside normal limits. Beta-mannosidase is a lysosomal enzyme that catabolizes oligosaccharides.
Abnormal circulating beta-mannosidase activity
Activity of the enzyme beta-mannosidase above the upper limit of normal. Beta-mannosidase is a lysosomal enzyme that catabolizes oligosaccharides.
Elevated circulating beta-mannosidase activity
Activity of the enzyme alpha-L-fucosidase below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced circulating alpha-L-fucosidase activity
Activity of the enzyme alpha-L-fucosidase in the blood circulation outside the limits of normal.
Abnormal circulating alpha-L-fucosidase activity
Activity of the enzyme alpha-L-fucosidase above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating alpha-L-fucosidase activity
Increased concentration of S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine concentration
Concentration S-adenosyl-L-methionine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating S-adenosyl-L-methionine concentration

Malignant hyperthermia that is characterized by exercise-induced life-threatening hyperthermia with a body temperature over 40 degrees C and signs of encephalopathy ranging from confusion to convulsions or coma. Incidence increases with rising ambient temperature and relative humidity. Manifestations may include rhabdomyolysis (presenting with myalgia, muscle weakness, and myoglobinuria), tachycardia, and in severe cases multiorgan failure.
Exercise-triggered malignant hyperthermia

Malignant hyperthermia that is characterized by a rapid increase in temperature to 39-42 degrees C in response to inhalational anesthetics such as halothane or to muscle relaxants such as succinylcholine.
Anesthesic-triggered malignant hyperthermia
Concentration of argininosuccinic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF argininosuccinic acid concentration
Concentration of aspartylglucosamine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF aspartylglucosamine concentration
Concentration of alpha-oxoadipic acid in the blood above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating alpha-oxoadipic acid concentration
A deviation from the normal range of a metabolite in red blood cells.
Abnormal erythrocyte metabolite concentration

Concentration of glutathione in red blood cells below the lower limit of normal. Glutathione (GSH) is an important redox active biomolecule critical in the maintenance and regulation of cellular and organismal health.
Reduced erythrocyte glutathione concentration
Concentration of sarcosine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF sarcosine concentration
Concentration of methionine in the cerebrospinal fluid below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced CSF methionine concentration
Concentration of homoarginine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating homoarginine concentration
The concentration of formiminoglutamic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary formiminoglutamic acid level
Concentration of proline in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF proline concentration
Level of S-sulfocysteine high in urine above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary S-sulfocysteine level
Concentration of S-sulfocysteine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating S-sulfocysteine concentration
Abnormal increase in the number of Sertoli cells in the testis.
Sertoli cell hyperplasia
The presence of an infectious agent in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
CSF infectious agent
Mycobacterium present in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). This feature can be ascertained by CSF microscopy.
CSF mycobacteria
Detection of a fungal organism (such as candida or coccidioides) in the blood stream.
Fungal bloodstream infection
Enlarged lymph node located just above the clavicle (collarbone).
Supraclavicular lymphadenopathy
Enlarged lymph node located in the inguinal region (groin).
Inguinal lymphadenopathy
Enlarged lymph node located in the axillary region (armpit).
Axillary lymphadenopathy

Murphy's sign is elicited in patients with acute cholecystitis by asking the patient to take in and hold a deep breath while palpating the subcostal region. In practice, Murphy's sign is performed by palpating the subcostal region during inspiration. If pain is elicited and the patient suddenly stops their inspiratory effort, a positive Murphy's sign has been elicited.
Positive Murphy sign
Vomiting whereby the vomit has the color of bile, yellowish-green.
Bilious emesis
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID).
Ameliorated by NSAID
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to a medication or other substance.
Fetal exposure history

A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to barbiturate medications such as phenobarbital. Barbiturates are used medically as anxiolytics, hypnotics, and anticonvulsants.
Fetal barbiturate exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to narcotic medications such as morphine or codeine. Narcotics are used medically to treat moderate or severe pain.
Fetal narcotic exposure
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by administration of ethosuximide. Ethosuximide is most often used to treat absence seizures.
Ameliorated by ethosuximide
Lower than normal amount of extracellular matrix protein 1 (ECM1) in the epidermis.
Reduced epidermal extracellular matrix protein 1 protein expression
Neurofibroma categorized according to the anatomical site of origin.
Neurofibroma by anatomical location
A neurofibroma (benign peripheral nerve sheath tumor) localized in the tongue.
Tongue neurofibroma
A neurofibroma (benign peripheral nerve sheath tumor) localized in the heart.
Cardiac neurofibroma
A neurofibroma (benign peripheral nerve sheath tumor) localized in the stomach.
Gastric neurofibroma
A neurofibroma (benign peripheral nerve sheath tumor) localized in the kidney.
Renal neurofibroma
Accumulation of a poorly branched and poorly spherical amylopectin-like glycogen (polyglucosan) in muscle fibers.
Muscle fiber polyglucosan inclusion bodies
Abnormal structure of the rete ridges (also known as rete pegs), which are downward projections of epithelium surrounding the connective tissue papillae in between the dermal papillae.
Abnormal rete ridge morphology
Increased length of the rete rdiges of the epidermis.
Rete ridge elongation
Accumulation of monoclonal CD1a-positive Langerhans cells in the bronchioles and alveolar interstitium that can cause damage to the lungs.
Pulmonary Langerhans cell histiocytosis
Flattening of a curve in the spine in the lumbar (lower back) region.
Lumbar hypolordosis

Battle sign is bruising over the mastoid process that is typically the result of head trauma. It is retroauricular or mastoid ecchymosis that is typically the result of head trauma. Battle sign typically requires significant head trauma and may indicate significant internal injury to the brain and not just the posterior cranial vault or mastoid.
Battle sign
Reduced anterioposterior dimension of the skull base.
Decreased skull base length
A visual disturbance in which objects in the visual field appear to oscillate (jump, jiggle, vibrate).
Oscillopsia
The frequency with which the eye is blinked is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased blink rate
A deviation from the normal frequency of blinking the eye.
Abnormal blink rate
The frequecy with which the eye is blinked is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated blink rate
Sputum contains pus.
Purulent sputum
The mother of a fetus or index patient has a history of hyperthyroidism during the corresponding pregnancy.
Maternal hyperthyroidism
Applies to an abnormality that affects the perineum (the region of skin between the genitals and the anus).
Perineal
History of exposure to gadolinium, a contrast medium often used for magnetic resonance imaging.
Gadolinium exposure
Excretion of pus (purulent discharge) from the opening of the parotid duct.
Purulent parotid gland drainage
Obstipation is the inability to pass either stool or flatus (gas).
Obstipation
Vomiting following a coughing spell.
Posttussive emesis
Vasculitis categorized according to the anatomical site where the finding is localized.
Vasculitis by anatomical site
Vasculitis categorized according to type of histological abnormality.
Vasculitis by histology
A type of vasculitis characterized by the presence of debris of neutrophils within the blood vessel walls.
Leukocytoclastic vasculitis
Accumulation of lipid droplets in small-bowel enterocytes
A pericardial friction rub is a grating, to-and-fro sound that occurs in phase with the heart sounds.
Pericardial friction rub
Muscular vasculitis
Any deviation from the normal amount of staining of succinate dehydrogenase in skeletal muscle tissue.
Abnormal muscle succinate dehydrogenase staining
Increased muscle succinate dehydrogenase staining
Decreased muscle succinate dehydrogenase staining
A benign (noncancerous) tumorlike malformation made up of an abnormal mixture of cells and tissues that originates in the small intestine.
Small intestinal hamartoma

Pyriform spermatozoa consist of a normally shaped acrosomal structure which can be normal in size or enlarged, while the post-acrosomal region shows severe elongation and an acute narrowing to the posterior end, ending in about the same thickness as the connecting mid-piece.
Pyriform sperm head

Excess residual cytoplasm is associated with abnormal spermatozoa produced from a defective spermiation process. This abnormal excess cytoplasm should not be confused with more physiological cytoplasmic residues that can be observed in direct microscopy of the ejaculate but not in dried, fixed and stained morphology smears.
Excess residual spermatozoal cytoplasm
Subsarcolemmal, eosinophilic glass-like regions within the cytoplasm of cardiomyocytes.
Cardiomyocyte hyaline bodies
Phagocytosis of erythrocytes, lymphocytes or other hematopoietic precursors by histiocytes or macrophages observed in the liver.
Hepatic hemophagocytosis
Phagocytosis of erythrocytes, lymphocytes or other hematopoietic precursors by histiocytes or macrophages observed in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
CSF hemophagocytosis
Phagocytosis of erythrocytes, lymphocytes or other hematopoietic precursors by histiocytes or macrophages observed in the spleen.
Splenic hemophagocytosis

The presence of multiple granulomas in the urinary bladder as based on pathological examination. Granulomas are small 0.5 to 2 mm collections of modified macrophages called epithelioid cells usually surrounded by lymphocytes.
Urinary bladder granulomatosis
Death of keratinocytes in the epidermis layer of the skin, which generally manifests as extensive exfoliation (separation of the epidermis from the underlying dermis).
Epidermal necrosis
Applied to a sign or symptom that is aggravated by (or made more painful by) bending of a limb or joint.
Exacerbated by flexion
The presence of blood in tears.
Hemolacria
A perception that an object is in contact with the eye.
Corneal foreign body sensation
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the buttock (round fleshy area at the lower rear area of a human trunk).
Buttock pain
A perception that an object located in the vagina.
Vaginal foreign body sensation
Attacks of breathlessness that occur at night and may awaken the sleeping patient.
Paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnea
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the eyelid.
Eyelid pain

Abnormality of a sperm function including protection of paternal DNA, traversing the female reproductive tract, oocyte localisation, penetration of the zona pellucida, oocyte activation and centriole deposition.
Abnormal sperm physiology

Reduction in size of the acrosome below the lower limit of normal. The acrosome is a unique membranous organelle located over the anterior part of the sperm nucleus. According to the World Health Organization criteria, the acrosome must be clearly visible, comprising approximately 40-70 percent of the sperm head.
Small acrosomal area
The proportion of sperm cells whose flagella is sharply curved or has a sharp angle is above normal limits.
Bent sperm flagella

Spermiation failure is indicated by apparently normal spermiogenesis, but the presence of retained Sd2 spermatids in stages III-V of human spermatogenesis, whereas maturation arrest is indicated by a lack of late Sd1 and Sd2 spermatids in the epithelium.
Spermiation failure

A morphological abnormality visible upon biopsy of the germinal epithelium of the testis in which the cellularity of the germinal epithelium is reduced in general, so that all stages of germ cells (spermatogonia, spermatocytes, and spermatids) are present but reduced in number. This term applies to biopsies with some tubules showing diminished amounts of qualitatively complete spermatogenesis in combination with a vast majority of tubules that lack germ cells.
Hypospermatogenesis
Formation of a sheet of tissue by coagulum of exudate over the conjunctiva of the eye that if removed leaves behind a denuded bleeding surface.
Conjunctival membrane

A type of oligozoospermia characterized by a total number of more than zero but less than 2 million sperm in the ejaculate or a concentration of more than zero but less than one million sperm per milliliter.
Extreme oligozoospermia

A type of oligozoospermia characterized by a total number of more than 30 but less than 39 million sperm in the ejaculate or a concentration of more than 10 but less than 15 million sperm per milliliter.
Mild oligozoospermia

A type of oligozoospermia characterized by a total number of more than 10 but less than 29 million sperm in the ejaculate or a concentration of more than 5 but less than 10 million sperm per milliliter.
Moderate oligozoospermia

A type of oligozoospermia characterized by a total number of more than 2 but less than 10 million sperm in the ejaculate or a concentration of more than 1 but less than 5 million sperm per milliliter.
Severe oligozoospermia
The presence of a nodule (small rounded lump of tissue) in the iris.
Iris nodule
A type of iris nodule consisting of inflammatory cell precipitates which lie at the pupillary margin.
Koeppe nodules
A type of iris nodule consisting of inflammatory cell precipitates which lie on the iris surface.
Bussaca nodules
Abnormal CSF ion concentration
Concentration of copper in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased CSF copper concentration

Diffuse lymphoid hyperplasia (DLH) describes the pathological entity that lies between follicular bronchiolitis and lymphocytic interstitial pneumonia (LIP). It is pathologically characterized by a diffuse peribronchiolar proliferation of hyperplastic lymphoid follicles (BALT), extended along the lymphatics to involve the interlobular septa and pleura. Unlike LIP, DHL does not show uniform involvement of the alveolar septa.
Diffuse pulmonary lymphoid hyperplasia
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with a steroid medication such as prednisone.
Ameliorated by steroid medication
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by administration of a medication.
Triggered by medication exposure
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by administration of levothyroxin (thyroid hormone).
Triggered by levothyroxin exposure
A decreased amount of laminin alpha-2 chain in muscle tissue. This feature can be shown by immunohistochemistry or Western blotting of muscle tissue.
Reduced muscle laminin alpha-2 chain staining
Abnormal thickening of of the outer layer (cortex) of the adrenal gland due to fibrosis.
Adrenal cortical sclerosis
Concentration or activity of fructose 1,6-bisphosphate aldolase in liver tissue below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic fructose-1,6-phosphate aldolase activity
A benign (noncancerous) tumorlike malformation made up of an abnormal mixture of cells and tissues that originates in the pancreas.
Pancreatic hamartoma
A benign liver neoplasm composed of fat, vascular, and smooth muscle elements.
Liver angiomyolipoma
A lipoma that is located within a the heart.
Cardiac lipoma
Accumulation of a poorly branched and poorly spherical amylopectin-like glycogen (polyglucosan) in peripheral nerve fibers.
Peripheral nerve polyglucosan inclusion bodies
Accumulation of a poorly branched and poorly spherical amylopectin-like glycogen (polyglucosan) in myocardial tissue.
Cardiac polyglucosan accumulation
A benign cystic neoplasm of the kidney.
Cystic nephroma
Elastic fibers not demonstrable in skin biopsy.
Absent dermal elastic fibers
Splitting of the skin (cell-cell adhesion of keratinocytes) localized to the interface between the stratum corneum and stratum granulosum layers of the epidermis.
Cleavage at junction of stratum corneum and stratum granulosum

An abnormal bone marrow finding characterized by many poorly circumscribed and occasionally confluent lymphoid nodules. The nodules contain small and uniform lymphocytes with rounded nuclei, clumped chromatin, and without prominent nucleoli.
Lymphoid hyperplasia

Lack of lamellar bodies (LBs) inthe epidermis. LBs are specialized organelles that contain pro-barrier lipids imparting a fully lamellar internal structure, but also other cargoes such as enzymes (lipid metabolizing and proteolytic), enzyme inhibitors, and antimicrobial peptides.
Absence of epidermal lamellar bodies

The presence of multiple granulomas in the gastrointestinal tract (Pylorus, esophagus, jejunum, ileum, cecum, rectum, perirectal area, esophagus) as based on pathological examination. Granulomas are small 0.5 to 2 mm collections of modified macrophages called epithelioid cells usually surrounded by lymphocytes.
Gastrointestinal granulomatosis

Increased size of sperm vacuoles, which are surface concavities typically located at the the tip or middle area of sperm heads. According to the WHO Laboratory Manual for the Examination and Processing of Human Semen, sperm head vacuoles are considered abnormal when exceeding 20% of the cross-sectional area of the head. Vacuoles are found in almost all samples with normal sperm morphology; this term applies if the proportion of sperm with abnormally large vacuoles is above the upper limit of normal.
Enlarged sperm head vacuole
A benign (noncancerous) tumorlike malformation made up of an abnormal mixture of cells and tissues that originates in the ureter.
Ureteral hamartoma
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to methimazole.
Fetal methimazole exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to procarbazine.
Fetal procarbazine exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to fluorouracil.
Fetal fluorouracil exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to cytarabine.
Fetal cytarabine exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to tetracycline.
Fetal tetracycline exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to quinine.
Fetal quinine exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to cyclophosphamide.
Fetal cyclophosphamide exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to metronidazole.
Fetal metronidazole exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to phenobarbital.
Fetal phenobarbital exposure
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to phenytoin.
Fetal phenytoin exposure
Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance are located at or near the umbilicus (belly button).
Periumbilical
A history of obesity, which can be defined as a body mass index of 30 or greater, in the mother of a fetus or index patient.
Maternal obesity during pregnancy
A history of amniocentesis having been performed in the mother of a fetus or index patient.
Maternal amniocentesis
Description of conditions in which age of onset is highly variable even in family members who share the same disease-associated variant or variants.
Typified by highly variable age of onset
Concentration or activity of an enzyme as measured in leukocytes is above or below the limits of normal in the blood circulation.
Abnormal leukocyte enzyme concentration or activity
Concentration or activity of an beta-glucuronidase as measured in leukocytes is below the limits of normal.
Reduced leukocyte beta-glucuronidase activity
Concentration or activity of an alpha-L-fucosidase as measured in leukocytes is below the limits of normal.
Reduced leukocyte alpha-L-fucosidase activity
Concentration or activity of an arylsulfatase B as measured in leukocytes is below the limits of normal.
Reduced leukocyte arylsulfatase B activity
Concentration or activity of an arylsulfatase C as measured in leukocytes is below the limits of normal.
Reduced leukocyte steroid sulfatase activity
Concentration or activity of the lysosomal enzyme arylsulfatase A (EC 3.1.6.8) as measured in leukocytes is below the limits of normal.
Reduced leukocyte arylsulfatase A activity
Activity of the enzyme alpha-galactosidase outsidebelow the lower limit of normal.
Decreased alpha-galactosidase A activity
Demonstration of parasite in stool specimen, e.g., Parasites present on wet mount of stool.e
Positive fecal parasite test
Any kind of test for an infectious agent in stool positive.
Positive stool infectious agent test
Test for giardia antigen in stool such as immune assay or DFA positive.
Positive stool giardia antigen
Demonstration of antibody directed against Entamoeba histolytica in stool.
Entamoeba histolytica antibody positive in stool
Concentration of porphyrin in erythrocytes below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced erythrocyte free porphyrin concentration
The concentration of urocanic acid in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced circulating urocanic acid concentration
The concentration of epinephrine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased urinary epinephrine level
Concentration of epinephrine in the cerebrospinal fluid below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased CSF epinephrine concentration
Concentration of epinephrin in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating epinephrine concentration
Concentration of norepinephrin in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating norepinephrine concentration
The concentration of norepinephrine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased urinary norepinephrine level
The concentration of metanephrine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased urinary metaepinephrine level
Concentration of metanephrine in the cerebrospinal fluid below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased CSF metanephrine concentration
Concentration of metanephrin in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating metanephrine concentration
A swelling or enlargment localized to the ovary. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Ovarian mass
