A swelling or enlargment localized to the adrenal gland. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Adrenal mass
A swelling or enlargment localized to the uterus. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Uterine mass
Calcium deposits in the prostate gland.
Prostatic calculus
A reduction in the velocity of portal venous flow, generally measured by Doppler ultrasound. Portal venous flow is normally towards the liver with peak systolic velocities in the range of 20-40 cm/s.
Decreased portal vein velocity
A swelling or enlargment localized to the cervis of the uterus. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Uterine cervix mass
The concentration of uromodulin (also known as Tamm Horsfall protein) in the urine, normalized for usine concentration, is outside the limits of normal.
Abnormal urinary uromodulin level
The concentration of uromodulin (also known as Tamm Horsfall protein) in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased urinary uromodulin level
The concentration of phenylacetylglutamine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Increased urine phenylacetylglutamine level
The concentration of guanidinoacetic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased urine guanidinoacetic acid level
Detection of DNA and RNA originating from an infectious agent (bacteria, viruses, parasites and fungi) in the urine.
Positive urine infectious agent nucleic acid test
Detection of Cytomegalovirus (CMV) nucleic acid in the urine by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.
Positive CMV urine nucleic acid test
Detection of Neisseria gonorrhoeae nucleic acid in the urine by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.
Positive Neisseria gonorrhoeae urine nucleic acid test
Detection of enterovirus nucleic acid in the urine by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.
Positive enterovirus urine nucleic acid test
An increase in the level of glycine in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Elevated brain glycine level by MRS
An increase in the level of polyol compounds in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Elevated brain polyol compounds by MRS
An increase in the level of gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Elevated brain gamma-aminobutyric acid by MRS
Medical history of ingestion of anticoagulants prior to presentation.
History of recent anticoagulant ingestion
Concentration of antidiuretic hormone, also known as vasopressin, is below the lower limit of normal in the blood circulation.
Decreased circulating antidiuretic hormone concentration
Concentration of growth hormone-releasing hormone above the upper limit of normal in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating growth hormone-releasing hormone concentration
Any deviation of the concentration of a protein in the amniotic fluid from normal limits
Abnormal amniotic fluid protein concentration
Concentration of alpha-fetoprotein in the amniotic fluid below lower limit of normal.
Decreased amniotic fluid alpha-fetoprotein concentration
Concentration of vitamin E in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Increased circulating vitamin E concentration
Concentration of calcitonin, a 32-amino acid polypeptide hormone that is produced primarily by the parafollicular cells of the thyroid, in the blood circulation outside of normal limits.
Abnormal circulating calcitonin concentration
Concentration of calcitonin, a 32-amino acid polypeptide hormone that is produced primarily by the parafollicular cells of the thyroid, in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating calcitonin concentration
Concentration of thyrotropin releasing hormone below the lower limit of normal in the blood circulation.
Decreased circulating thyrotropin releasing hormone concentration
Concentration of uroporphyrin in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating uroporphyrin concentration
Concentration of pentacarboxylporphyrin in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Increased urine pentacarboxylporphyrin level
Concentration of hexacarboxylporphyrin in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Increased urine hexacarboxylporphyrin level
Concentration of dehydroepiandrosterone in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Increased circulating dehydroepiandrosterone concentration
Concentration of coproporphyrin in erythrocytes above the upper limit of normal.
Increased erythrocyte coproporphyrin concentration
Concentration of uroproporphyrin in erythrocytes above the upper limit of normal.
Increased erythrocyte uroproporphyrin concentration
Concentration of apolipoprotein E below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating apolipoprotein E concentration
Concentration of apolipoprotein E above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating apolipoprotein E concentration
Reduction in the size of the acrosome of the head of spermatozoa.
Acrosomal hypoplasia
Oocyte maturation arrest (OMA) can manifest as failed in vitro fetilization/intracytoplasmic sperm injection (IVF/ICSI) attempts using affected oocytes.
Oocyte maturation arrest
A structural anomaly of the anus.
Abnormal anus morphology
A functional anomaly of the anus.
Abnormal anus physiology
Reduced muscle tone of the sphincter of the anus.
Weak anal sphincter tone
Diminished activity of the enzyme 2,4-dienoyl-CoA reductase in muscle tissue.
Reduced muscle 2,4-dienoyl-CoA reductase activity
Diminished activity of the enzyme 2,4-dienoyl-CoA reductase in liver tissue.
Reduced liver 2,4-dienoyl-CoA reductase activity
Inflammation of blood vessels in the mucosa of the nasal cavity.
Nasal mucosa vasculitis
Pituitary blastoma is a distinctive anterior hypophyseal tumor of infants
Pituitary blastoma
Axonal spheroids are bubble-like biological features that form on most degenerating axons.
Peripheral axon spheroid formation
Activity of the enzyme carboxylesterase 1 in liver tissue below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced liver carboxylesterase 1 activity
A structural anomaly of the dermis, the layer of skin that lies beneath the epidermis and above the subcutaneous layer.
Abnormal dermis morphology
Deposition of a largely amorphous hyaline (transparent and homogeneous) substance around blood vessels in the dermis layer of the skin.
Perivascular dermis hyaline deposition
Deposition of a largely amorphous hyaline (transparent and homogeneous) substance around blood vessels in the wall of the small intestine.
Perivascular small intestinal hyaline deposition

Abnormally large keratohyalin granules (KHG). KHG are typically present in the stratum granulosum of the epidermal layer of the skin (and epithelium of the mucosae). KHG are protein structures found in the keratinocytes of the stratum granulosum.
Large keratohyaline granules
Reduced amount of lipoic acid in muscle tissue.
Decreased muscle lipoic acid content
Activity of cystathionine gamma-lyase in the liver below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic cystathionine gamma-lyase activity
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the digestive system.
Digestive system neoplasm
Arthrosis, i.e., of degenerative joint disease, affecting the lumbar vertebral column.
Lumbar spondylosis
Activity of the enzyme acid maltase (also known as alpha-1,4-glucosidase) below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating acid maltase activity
The concentration of ribitol in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.
Increased circulating ribitol concentration
Concentration of 7-dehydrocholesterol in the blood circulation outside the limits of normal.
Abnormal circulating 7-dehydrocholesterol concentration
Concentration of 7-dehydrocholesterol in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating 7-dehydrocholesterol concentration
Concentration of lathosterol in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating lathosterol concentration
Concentration of desmosterol in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating desmosterol concentration
Concentration of sialic acid in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating sialic acid concentration
The synovial fluid (also known as synovia, i.e., the fluid found in the cavities of synovial joints) contains increased quantities of white blood cells.
Purulent synovial fluid
The presence of inclusion bodies within the cytoplasm of muscle cells that demonstrate immunoreactivity for calsequestrin 1.
Muscle fiber calsequestrin 1-containing inclusion bodies

A myxoma (A benign tumor composed of myxomatous tissue composed of loosely-arranged spindle, polygonal, and stellate cells) localized to the palate. Clinically, such tumors may present as a sessile nodule on the hard palate.
Palatine myxoma
A myxoma (tumor of primitive connective tissue) localized in the vagina.
Vaginal myxoma
Abnormally reduced amount of collagen fibers in the dermis.
Decreased dermal collagen
Abnormal shape of keratohyaline granules in dermal keratinocytes.
Irregularly shaped keratohyaline granules

Tubular shadows are characterised by a complete absence of cells in the testicular tubules, meaning that germ cells as well as somatic Sertoli cells are absent. The cells have been replaced by hyalinization.
Tubular shadows
Presence of many apocrine hidrocystoma (cysts) on the margins of the eyelids.
Multiple eyelid margin cysts

The fibrous sheath is a structure in the midpiece of the sperm flagellum surrounding the outer dense fibers. It comprises two longitudinal columns and tranverse ribs. In case of altered location of the longitudinal column in the fibrous sheath the symmetrical structure is lost, most commonly with the columns not being opposite to each other, which can be visualised by electron microscopy.
Altered location of the longitudinal column in the fibrous sheath
A myxoma (tumor of primitive connective tissue) localized to the uterus.
Uterine myxoma
A myxoma (tumor of primitive connective tissue) localized to the the cervix of the uterus.
Uterine cervix myxoma
Penetrance describes the proportion of genotype positive individuals that develop disease given a lifespan of 80 years. For example, penetrance of Neurofibromatosis type 1 is close to 100%.
Typified by complete penetrance

A rare benign chondroid and osteoid matrix-producing neoplasm of bone characterized by extensive myxoid changes. OMX originate from bony cortices and have been observed in the nasal region, as well as the tibia and radius.
Osteochondromyxoma
A low-grade central nervous system tumor composed of dysplastic ganglion cells, usually presenting in children or young adults and located in the cerebral hemispheres.
Gangliocytoma
A gastrinoma, a neuroendocrine tumors characterized by the secretion of gastrin with resultant excessive gastric acid production, that is localized to the duodenum.
Duodenal gastrinoma
A primary thymic neuroendocrine tumor.
Thymic carcinoid tumor
Count of eosinophils in the bone marrow above the upper limit of normal.
Bone marrow eosinophilia
Applied to a sign or symptom that is worsened by treatment with lithium.
Exacerbated by lithium exposure
Activity of glycogen debrancher enzyme (also known as amylo-1,6-glucosydase, 4-alpha-glucantransferase) in liver tissue below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic glycogen debrancher enzyme activity

Insertion of the neck and midpiece into the head of a spermatozoon on an axis that diverges from the midline axis of the spermatozoon head. This term applies if the proportion of spermatozoa with this defect is above the upper limit of normal.
Asymmetrical insertion of the midpiece into the head
Sharply angled insertion of the neck and midpiece into the head of a spermatozoon. This term applies if the proportion of spermatozoa with this feature is above the upper limit of normal.
Bent sperm neck
The concentration of 3,6-epoxydicarboxylic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urine 3,6-epoxydicarboxylic acid level

Presence of biliary sludge (a mixture of particulate solids that have precipitated from bile) in the gallbladder. Such sediment consists of cholesterol crystals, calcium bilirubinate pigment, and other calcium salts. Sludge is usually detected on transabdominal ultrasonography.
Gallbladder biliary sludging
Applied to a sign or symptom that is worsened by treatment with amiodarone.
Exacerbated by amiodarone exposure
A swelling or enlargment localized to the ureter. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Ureteral mass
Width of the cavum septum pellucidum above the upper limit of normal, which is defined as a separation of greater than one cm of the leaves of the cavum septum pellucidum.
Wide cavum septum pellucidum
Underdevelopment of the trochlear nerve, which is the fourth cranial nerve and one of the ocular motor nerves that controls eye movement.
Hypoplastic trochlear nerve
A closed sac of tissue (cyst) located in the thymus. Thymic cysts are a rare, benign anomaly, are usually asymptomatic, and mostly occur in the anterior mediastinum .
Thymic cyst
A closed sack of tissue (cyst) located in the uterus.
Uterine cyst
A swelling or enlargment localized to the urinary bladder. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Urinary bladder mass
A series of indentations or erosions on a normally smooth margin of the inner layer of the cortex (i.e. the endosteum) of bones.
Endosteal scalloping
A benign (noncancerous) tumorlike malformation made up of an abnormal mixture of cells and tissues that originates in the urinary bladder.
Urinary bladder hamartoma
A swelling or enlargment localized to the peritoneal cavity. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Peritoneal mass
A swelling or enlargment localized to the Fallopian tube. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Fallopian tube mass
Congenital absence of the pyramids, that is, of the paired structures located at the medial aspect of the ventral medulla that flank the anterior median fissure.
Aplasia of the pyramids of the medulla oblongata
A deformity of the posterior skull with bulging of the midportion of the occipital bone that is often associated with a benign variant of the mendosal suture.
Bathrocephaly
Downward pointing exostoses of the occipital bone situated in the tendinous insertions of the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles.
Occipital horn

A developmental defect characterized by failure to develop of the pituitary stalk. The pituitary stalk, also known as the infundibulum or infundibular stalk, is the connection between the hypothalamus and the pituitary gland.
Absent pituitary stalk
A structural anomaly of the pituitary stalk, also known as the infundibulum or infundibular stalk, is the connection between the hypothalamus and the pituitary gland.
Abnormal pituitary stalk morphology

A developmental defect characterized by a discontinuity of the pituitary stalk. The pituitary stalk, also known as the infundibulum or infundibular stalk, is the connection between the hypothalamus and the pituitary gland.
Interrupted pituitary stalk
Unintentional movement in one area of the face produced during intentional movement of another area of the face.
Facial synkinesis
Unintentional movement in one area of the body produced during intentional movement of another area of the body.
Synkinesis
History of exposure to birds.
Exposure to birds
Loss of sensation to the area of buttocks, perianal space and thighs.
Perianal anethesia

Instillation of 2.5% phenylephrine drops into the eye does not induce blanching of eye redness. Failure to blanch suggests redness caused by scleral vessel engorgement (e.g., scleritis) or extravascular cause (e.g., hemorrhage), not episcleritis or conjunctivitis.
Phenylephrine does not induce blanching of eye redness
A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to ethanol (alcohol).
Fetal alcohol exposure
Diminished ability of cells to transport cobalamine from the extracellular space to the cytoplasm.
Reduced cellular cobalamin uptake
A localized area of cell death, often accompanied by infiltration of inflammatory cells, in the brainstem.
Focal necrotic brainstem lesion
A localized area of cell death, often accompanied by infiltration of inflammatory cells, in the optic nerve.
Focal necrotic optic nerve lesion
A localized area of cell death, often accompanied by infiltration of inflammatory cells, in the thalamus.
Focal necrotic thalamus lesion
Accumulation of fluid in the interstitial spaces of the skin. This finding can be appreciated my microscopic examination of a skin biopsy.
Interstitial dermal edema
Shoulder abduction contracture

A type of shoulder contracture characterized by decreased internal rotation of shoulder, that is, by a chronic reduction in active and passive ability to internally rotate the humerus at the shoulder joint (if the arm is flexed at the elbow, Internal rotation of the shoulder rotates the forearm towards the center of the body).
Shoulder external rotation contracture

A type of thumb contracture characterized by a chronic reduction in active and passive ability of the metacarpal-phalangeal and/or interphalangeal joints of the thumb to bring from medial side to neutral position, where the neutral position for the thumb is when the distal and proximal segments of the thumb joint are in linear alignment.
Thumb adduction contracture
Hip internal rotation contracture
Elevated circulating saccharopine concentration
Activity of fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase (EC 3.1.3.11) in the liver below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase activity
Activity of carbamoylphosphate synthetase 1 in the liver below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic carbamoylphosphate synthetase 1 activity
Reduced number of small nerve fibers in the skin.
Reduced intraepidermal small nerve fiber density
A developmental defect characterized by the presence of a supernumerary femoral artery.
Femoral artery duplication

Collagen VII is the major molecular constituent of anchoring fibrils in the skin. Collagen VII is synthesized as three identical pro-alpha1(VII) polypeptide chains, which are hydroxylated and glycosylated in a coordinated manner and then fold into triple-helical procollagen VII in the endoplasmic reticulum (ER). Mature collagen VII undergoes a multistep fibril polymerization process to form the anchoring fibrils. Mutant pro-alpha1(VII) polypeptide chains or procollagen VII molecules do not pass the ER quality control and are retained in the ER or designated for ubiquitin-proteasome degradation resulting in reduced amounts of collagen VII in the skin.

A structural anomaly of the Eustachian tube (ET). The ET is a biomechanical valve between the nasopharynx and the middle ear. Physiologically, it controls the passive adaptation of the middle ear air pressure to the ambient air pressure primarily via direct muscular actions of the soft palate. In the closed state it protects the middle ear. Inadequate function of the ET causes middle ear ventilation disorders.

Cortical myoclonus mainly affects the distal upper limbs and face, which reflects the largest cortical representations of these body areas. It is often focal, but may be multifocal, bilateral or generalized, as a consequence of intracortical and transcallosal spreading of abnormal activity. It typically occurs on voluntary action and may affect speech and gait. Cortical myoclonic jerks are stimulus sensitive, typically to touch, but sensitivity to visual stimuli is also described. Most patients with cortical myoclonus have both positive myoclonus and NM, occurring either independently or together as a complex of the two kinds of myoclonus. If cortical myoclonus is prolonged and lasts for hours, days or weeks, it is called epilepsia partials continua and is considered to be a rare form of focal epileptic status. Focal cortical myoclonus almost always points to an underlining lesion of the sensori-motor cortex, which produces hyperexcitability (e.g. vascular, inflammatory or neoplastic).

The presence of woolly hair on the scalp. The term woolly hair refers to an abnormal variant of hair that is fine, with tightly coiled curls, and often hypopigmented. Optical microscopy may reveal the presence of tight spirals and a clear diameter reduction as compared with normal hair. Electron microscopy may show flat, oval hair shafts with reduced transversal diameter.
Reduced level of platelet-activating factor acetylhydrolase.

An abnormally increased head circumference in a growing child. Head circumference is measured with a nonelastic tape and comprises the distance from above the eyebrows and ears and around the back of the head. The measured HC is then plotted on an appropriate growth chart.

An abnormally reduced head circumference in a growing child. Head circumference is measured with a nonelastic tape and comprises the distance from above the eyebrows and ears and around the back of the head. The measured HC is then plotted on an appropriate growth chart. Microcephaly is defined as a head circumference (HC) that is great than two standard deviations below the mean of age- and gender-matched population based samples. Severe microcephaly is defined with an HC that is three standard deviations below the mean.
Recurrent abnormal consumption of food, liquids, or objects that could have negative consequences for the individual.

A structural anomaly of the muscles of the trunk and head.

Preauricular sinus is an occasional finding and most frequently appears as a small pit close to the anterior margin of the ascending portion of the helix. The opening has also been reported along the postero superior margin of the helix, the tragus or the lobule. Preauricular sinus may lead to the formation of a subcutaneous cyst that is intimately related to the tragal cartilage and the anterior crus of the helix.
A problem occurring during any phase of the male sexual response cycle that prevents the individual from experiencing satisfaction from the sexual activity

Polyarthritis refers to a joint disease that involves at least five joints. One or more signs of inflammation, including pain, movement restriction, swelling, warmth, and redness, are seen in the joints involved. Polyarthritis is defined as symmetric if at least half of the joints involved are affected in a symmetric (i.e., both right and the left) fashion.
A type of arthritis that affects up to four joints in the first six months of disease.

Perimenopause, or the menopausal transition, encompasses that period of time during which physiologic changes mark progression toward a woman's final menstrual period. This phase begins with the onset of menstrual irregularities and continues until a woman reaches menopause, or one year after amenorrhea has occurred. Perimenopause can last for a variable amount of time, the median of which is four years.

Clinical relevance

In clinical parlance, findings are occasionally interpreted as being distinctive or minor, reflecting a subjective clinical impression of the importance of a feature for the differential diagnosis. A minor finding is taken to be one that is likely to have high utility in distinguishing the correct diagnosis from other candidates in the differential.

The presence of an increased amount of muscle fibers with an increased diameter. This feature can be ascertained by microscopic examination of a muscle biopsy sample. Together with fiber size variation and atrophied muscle fibers, and hypertrophied muscle fibers are commonly found in myopathies.

An increased volume of the endomysium, which is a connective tissue sheath that surrounds each muscule fiber. Together, bundles of muscle fibers form a fasciculus, surrounded by another layer of connective tissue called the perimysium.

Subsarcolemmal, eosinophilic glass-like regions in the cytoplasm of muscle fibers. Hyaline bodies show significant reactivity to myofibrillar ATPase after acid pre-incubation and with immunohistochemistry, show intense reactivity with only slow myosin heavy chain. Electron microscopy of the affected areas show a lack of myofibrils and a uniform, finely granular matrix, sometimes suggesting a filamentous nature, containing few scattered nuclei and mitochondria.

Any structural anomaly of the cementum, which is the mineralized connective tissue covering the dental root. The cementum allows anchoring of the fibers of the periodontal ligament. A condition in which epileptiform abnormalities are believed to contribute to the progressive disturbance in cerebral function. Detection of the presence of CD19 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD19 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).
CD19 expression
Detection of the presence of CD20 on the cell(s) of interest with the use of anti-CD20 antibodies conjugated to a chromogen (for immunohistochemistry) or fluorophore (for flow cytometry).
CD20 expression
information about the patient's previous surgical treatments that might be relevant to the presenting illness or to provide optimal clinical management.
Past surgical history

Any structural abnormality of a superficial temporal artery, originating from the external carotid artery and passing over the zygomatic process. The superficial temporal artery is located on the superficial parts of the forehead and sides of the head and face.
Abnormal superficial temporal artery morphology
Patchy inflammation of the superficial temporal artery, forming isolated foci of arteritis.
Skip lesions on temporal artery biopsy

Any anomaly of brain-evoked potentials, defined as potentials generated by exteroceptive stimuli reflect synchronised activity by neuronal and axonal groups in the central nervous system (CNS) resulting from the arrival of nerve impulses after stimulation of a peripheral nerve or its receptors. Depending on the type of stimulus, evoked potentials are categorised as visual (VEP), auditory (AEP), or somatosensory (SSEP). Motor evoked potentials (MEP) occur when the brain's motor area is stimulated. They result from the activation of a sufficient number of motor units.
Abnormal brain-evoked potentials
The presence of an infectious agent in the sputum, as characterized by sputum culture or other investigation.
Sputum infectious agent
Growth of mycobacterium avium in a sputum culture.
Positive Mycobacterium avium sputum culture
A test result demonstrating the presence of an antigen (marker such as a protein against which an antibody reacts) specific to an infectious agent.
Positive bloodstream infectious agent antigen test
Demonstration of an antigen specific to Cysticercosis in the bloodstream.
Positive bloodstream Cysticercosis antigen test

Involuntary attacks of compulsive paroxysmal shouting. The shouting behaviors may be extremely loud and not related to the ongoing mental state of the affected individual. Shouting episodes may occur in bouts and last for several hours.
Klazomania

Coprolalia denotes the involuntary utterance of obscenities. Intent is an important classifier in coprolalic behaviors, and unfortunately it remains unclear how to objectively distinguish coprolalia from common swearing.
Coprolalia
Continuous groaning, moaning, grunting, and shrieking.
Continuous involuntary vocalizations
Congenital absence or underdevelopment of the uterine cervix.
Aplasia/hypoplasia of the uterine cervix
Underdevelopment of the uterine cervix.
Cervical hypoplasia
A serous papillary adenocarcinoma that arises from the lining of the peritoneum
Primary peritoneal serous papillary adenocarcinoma
Any kind of test for an infectious agent in skin positive.
Positive skin infectious agent test

A test for fungus, e.g., fungal hyphae, in a skin specimen (usually a skin scraping), demonstrates the presence of fungi. Most commonly, a skin scraping is obtained using a small scalpel blade, the specimen is placed on a clean glass slide, a drop of potassium hydroxide (KOH) is added, and the specimen is examined microscopically for fungal structures such as hyphae or yeast.
Positive skin fungus test
Count of eosinophils in nasal secretions (for instance, nasal discharge) above the upper limit of normal.
Nasal secretion eosinophilia
Count of neutrophils in nasal secretions (for instance, nasal discharge) above the upper limit of normal.
Nasal secretion neutrophilia

Concentration of methionine in the cerebrospinal fluid above the upper limit of normal.

Decreased CSF histidine concentration

Abnormal CSF albumin concentration
Increased CSF albumin concentration

Abnormal CSF carnosine concentration

Abnormal concentration of sebacic acid in the urine.
Abnormal urine sebacic acid concentration
Elevated concentration of sebacic acid in the urine.

Increased level of gamma-aminobutyric acid in urine
Abnormal concentration of hexanoylglycine in the urine.

Elevated concentration of hexanoylglycine in the urine.
Increased level of hexanoylglycine in urine

Abnormal amount of carbon dioxide in umbilical cord blood
Abnormal carbon dioxide level in cord blood
An abnormal level of blood oxygen in the cord blood.
Abnormal oxygen level in cord blood
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to a head trauma.
Triggered by head trauma
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to anesthetics.
Triggered by anesthetics
The most dramatic and severe form of hair loss characterized by an absence of hair follicles.
Atrichia
Abnormal proportion of helper T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Abnormal helper T cell proportion
Increased proportion of helper T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Increased helper T cell proportion

An increased proportion of CD8-positive, alpha-beta effector memory RA TEMRA T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. These cells have the phenotype CD45RA-positive, CD45RO-negative, and CCR7-negative.
Increased proportion of CD8-positive, alpha-beta TEMRA T cells

An decreased proportion of CD8-positive, alpha-beta effector memory RA TEMRA T cells compared to the total number of T cells in the blood. These cells have the phenotype CD45RA-positive, CD45RO-negative, and CCR7-negative.
Decreased proportion of CD8-positive, alpha-beta TEMRA T cells
An abnormal proportion of circulating CD4-positive helper T cells relative to total T cell count.
Abnormal proportion of CD4-positive helper T cells
Abnormal proportion of gamma-delta T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Abnormal proportion of gamma-delta T cells
Increased proportion of gamma-delta T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Increased proportion of gamma-delta T cells
Decreased proportion of gamma-delta T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Decreased proportion of gamma-delta T cells
Abnormal proportion of immature gamma-delta T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Abnormal proportion of immature gamma-delta T cells
Increased proportion of immature gamma-delta T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Increased proportion of immature gamma-delta T cells
Decreased proportion of immature gamma-delta T cells relative to the total number of T cells.
Decreased proportion of immature gamma-delta T cells

Abnormal finding by magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), which uses non-ionizing radiation via a strong magnetic field and radio frequency energy to generate three dimensional images. This term comprises findings that are specific to MRI. Findings such as ventricular spetum defect that can be detected by multiple modalities should be coded separately.
Abnormal cardiac magnetic resonance imaging finding
Increased duration of myocardial T2 time without gadolinium contrast. Elevated T2, which can detect myocardial edema.
Elevated myocardial native T2
Areas of high signal intensity in magnetic resonance imaging of the heart appearing 10 to 15 minutes after injection of the intercellular contrast agent gadolinium.
Myocardial late gadolinium enhancement
Areas of high signal intensity in magnetic resonance imaging of the pericardium appearing around 10 minutes after injection of the intercellular contrast agent gadolinium.
Pericardial late gadolinium enhancement

Increased duration of myocardial T1 time without gadolinium contrast. T1 mapping consists of quantifying the T1 relaxation time of a tissue by using analytical expressions of image-based signal intensities. A fundamental principle of MR imaging is that the signal intensity of pixels is based on the relaxation of hydrogen nuclei protons in a static magnetic field. The T1 relaxation times between two tissues vary substantially. Edema, fat infiltration, and fibrosis also cause differences in T1 relaxivity.
Elevated myocardial native T1
Tightening of smooth muscle surrounding the bronchi and bronchioles with consequent wheezing and shortness of breath.
Bronchoconstriction

Pronuclei formation is a critical process during fertilisation. Normally, there are two pronuclei (2PN), including the paternal pronucleus and the maternal pronucleus, in the zygote after fertilisation. It is generally accepted that multiple pronuclei (MPN) formation is due to the abnormal extrusion of the second polar body or to abnormal fertilisation with multiple sperm. The MPN therefore can cause infertility and recurrent failure of IVF/ICSI.
Formation of multiple pronuclei during fertilization
An excessive, irrational, and debilitating fear of carrying out a physical movement due to a feeling of vulnerability to painful injury or reinjury.
Kinesiophobia
Decreased renal tubular reabsorption of bicarbonate.
Impaired renal tubular reabsorption of bicarbonate
A congenital human papillomavirus (HPV) infection of the newborn. Congential HPV infection can manifest as condyloma cuminata in the newborn.
History of congenital HPV infection
Necrotizing ileitis
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against desmoglein-1, a dermal cell adhesion molecule.
Anti-desmoglein-1 antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against desmoglein-3, a dermal cell adhesion molecule.
Anti-desmoglein-3 antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against envoplakin, a cytoskeletal linker protein that links intermediate filaments to cellular junctions.
Anti-envoplakin antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against periplakin.
Anti-periplakin antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against desmoplakin-1.
Anti-desmoplakin I antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against desmoplakin-II.
Anti-desmoplakin II antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against BP230.
Anti-BP230 antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against BP180.
Anti-BP180 antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against laminin-332.
Anti-laminin 332 antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against laminin-6.
Anti-laminin 6 antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against laminin gamma-1.
Anti-laminin gamma1 antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against a laminin. Laminins are major components of the basement membrane.
Anti-laminin antibody positivity

The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against an integrin. Integrins are a family of cell adhesion molecules with 24 known integrin heterodimers. Integrins transduce mechanical and biochemical signals from fibrotic extracellular matrix into the cell, activate latent TGFbeta, and subsequently modulate fibroblast adhesion, migration, and growth.
Anti-integrin antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against transglutaminase 6.
Anti-transglutaminase 6 antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against LAD-1, which is the soluble 120 kDa ectodomain of BP180.
anti-LAD-1 antibody positivity

The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against LABD97, which is structurally identical to a portion of the extracellular domain of BPAg2. BPAg2, a 180 kDa bullous pemphigoid antigen, is a transmembrane protein important for basement membrane cohesion.
Anti-LABD97 antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against gliadin.
Antigliadin antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against reticulin.
Anti-reticulin antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against collagen type VII.
Anti-type VII collagen antibody
A perception that one's body is moving or swaying despite lack of motion of the body.
False perception of self-motion

A perception of unsteadiness of dizziness that is not characterized bythe spinning sensation of classic vertigo, but rather by an oscillatory perception (rocking, bobbing, or swaying despite the fact that the subject is not moving).
Non-spinning vertigo
Decreased lymphocyte count during infections.
Infection-associated lymphopenia
Megaurater associated with obstruction or an adynamic ureteral segment in the ureterovesical junction.
Primary obstructive megaureter
A type of hydrocele testis in which both the proximal and distal portions of processus vaginalis get obliterated while the central portion remains patent and fluid accumulates within it.
Encysted hydrocele of the cord

Congenital hydrocele occurs when processus vaginalis is patent and communicates with the peritoneal cavity. This communication allows the movement of peritoneal fluid but is too small to allow the intra-abdominal contents to herniate through.
Congenital hydrocele

Infantile Hydrocele is a type pf hydrocele in which the processus vaginalis gets obliterated at the level of the deep inguinal ring. However, the portion distal to it remains patent and allows fluid accumulation.
Infantile hydrocele
A decreased proportion of circulating mucosal-associated invariant T (MAIT) cells relative to total T cell count.
Reduced proportion of mucosal-associated invariant T cells
Onset of a phenotypic abnormality or a disease during childbirth or in the period immediately following.
Puerpural onset
Extracellular tissue deposition of fibrils that are composed of fragments of and/or intact serum amyloid A protein, a hepatic acute phase reactant.
AA amyloidosis
Category of fracture. Terms from this subontology can be used together with terms in the subontology that descends from Bone fracture (HP:0020110).
Fracture type
A type of fracture in which the broken bone is not completely separated.
Greenstick fracture
A type of fracture in which the break is in a straight line across the bone.
Transverse fracture
A type of fracture in which the break spirals around the bone.
Spiral fracture
A type of fracture in which there is a diagonal break across the bone.
Oblique fracture
A type of fracture in which the bone is crushed, causing the broken bone to be wider or flatter in appearance.
Compression fracture
A type of fracture in which the break is in three or more pieces and fragments are present at the fracture site.
Comminuted fracture
A type of fracture in which the same bone is fractured in two places, so there is a floating segment of bone.
Segmental fracture
A type of fracture in which there is an open wound or break in the skin near the site of the broken bone.
Open fracture
A type of fracture in which the broken bone that does not penetrate the skin.
Closed fracture
A type of fracture that is localied near to a a tendon or ligament and a small fragment of bone is separated from the main mass of bone as a result of physical trauma.
Avulsion fracture
A type of fracture in which the ends of the fractured bone are no longer aligned.
Displaced fracture
A widespread rash.
Exanthem
A reaction characterizeds by capillary dilatation, leukocytic infiltration, redness, heat, pain, swelling localized to the in the intestinal tract.
Intestinal inflammation

Any abnormality of programmed cell death (apoptosis), which is defined as the orchestrated collapse of a cell characterised by membrane blebbing, cell shrinkage, condensation of chromatin, and fragmentation of DNA followed by rapid engulfment of the corpse by neighbouring cells. Apoptosis is distinguished from death by necrosis by the absence of an associated inflammatory response.
Abnormal apoptosis
A reduced amount of programmed cell death upon stimulation of the FAS receptor, which normally induces caspase-8 dependent apoptosis.
Decreased FasL-mediated apoptosis

A type of proteinuria characterized by increased permeability of the glomerular capillary wall to macromolecules (particularly albumin), whereby protein excretion can reach 20 g/24 h and consists mainly of albumin.
Glomerular proteinuria
A structural defect associated with abnormal development of the lung.
Abnormal lung development
Abnormal pulmonary alveolar system development
A diffuse and specific increase in the number of alpha-cells.
Pancreatic alpha-cell hyperplasia
A congenital hand malformation characterized by the coalescence of the coalescence of third and fourth metacarpals (i.e., those corresponding to the middle and ring fingers).
3-4 metacarpal synostosis
Any structural anomaly of the iliac artery.
Abnormal iliac artery morphology
Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in the iliac artery.
Iliac artery aneurysm
Any deviation from normal intensity or subject of a person's interests, which can be defined as a state of giving selective attention to something.
Abnormal interest
A type of abnormal interest characterized by a persistent and intense focus on parts of a toy/object. For example, affected individuals may spin the wheels on a toy car rather than drive the toy car.
Persistent preoccupation with parts of objects
Highly restricted, fixated interests that are abnormal in intensity or focus (e.g., strong attachment to or preoccupation with unusual objects, excessively circumscribed or perseverative interests).
Fixated interests
The presence of any atypical form of expressive language.
Abnormal language feature
Atypical language features characterized by first vs. second or third person pronoun errors such as using 'you' or 'he/she' in place of 'I'.
Pronoun reversal

Production of sound done without will or conscious control. Involuntary vocalizations include tics, stereotypies vocalizations as part of dystonia or chorea, continuous vocalizing behaviors such as groaning or grunting, pathological laughter and crying, and others.
Involuntary vocalization
The number of times facial expressions are produced in a given period is lower than expected given the social and cultural context.
Reduced frequency of facial expressions
Moving another person's hand, body part, or body to communicate a desire, e.g. pushing or pulling someone toward a desired object or placing someone's hand on something.
Use of another person's body to communicate
A fixated interest in a specific topic that is atypical for the social context of the individual, such as topics of a non-social nature like fossils or vacuum cleaners.
Fixated interest with abnormal focus
An abnormally intense interest in a topic or object that is not atypical for the social context of the affected person.
Fixated interest with abnormal intensity
Unusual interest in sensory aspects of the environment.
Sensory seeking
Diminished use of typical non-verbal conversational gestures such as shaking the head to indicate no or nodding the head to indicate yes.
Reduced production of gestures

Impairment in a child's ability to be able to play in a way that involves peer collaboration. Collaborative play involves things such as verbal and non-verbal communication (e.g., self-initiated interactions), turn-taking, sharing, reciprocity, and collaborative problem-solving. It is often contrasted to parallel play, which involves a form of social play in which two children do similar activities near each other and often mimic each other. Typically developing children develop collaborative play between the ages of 4 and 5.
Reduced collaborative play
Lack of interest in peers of comparable age and social groups is evident when an individual, such as a child, shows more interest in socializing with adults rather than children their own age.
Ignores peers
Decreased sharing of interests with others appropriate to culture and developmental level.
Reduced sharing of interests

An absence or reduction in object sharing. Object sharing is an early emerging social skill in which a child will share objects with parents or peers during object play. Object sharing typically develops within the first two years of life.
Reduced object sharing

Abnormal expressions (movements or position of muscles of the face that convey the emotional state of an individual to observers during social interactions) comprising abnormalities of quantity, range, context-appropriateness, and quality.
Abnormal communicative facial expressions
Production of facial expressions that are misaligned with the social context.
Facial expressions that do not match the context
Spontaneous production of communicative facial expressions that have poor quality or are exaggerated or muted.
Abnormal quality of facial expression
Abnormality in the use of gestures defined as hand, shoulder, and head movements that convey a shared meaning within a culture that replace or supplement verbal communication.
Abnormal gesture use

Reduced ability to conduct a reciprocal (back and forth) conversation, as expected for language level. May be characterized by deficits in the ability to make comments about discussion topics of others, failure to ask questions, and not building a conversation on comments of others. Affected persons may not know what to say next in a conversation, may not notice if others are bored with a given topic, may conduct a one-sided conversation (talking but not listening), or may veer off topic more than is socially acceptable.
Poor conversational reciprocity

A condition in which the permanent teeth, because of deficiency of growth in the jaw or segment of jaw, assume a path of eruption that intercepts a primary tooth, causes its premature loss and produces a consequent malposition of the permanent tooth.
Ectopic tooth eruption
A developmental anomaly characterized by undergrowth of the corpus cavernosum.
Corpus cavernosum hypoplasia
Concentration of the nucleobase thymine in the blood circulation above the normal range.
Elevated circulating thymine concentration

Elevated hydrogen gas level in exhaled breath following oral administration of lactose. In individuals with lactose intolerance, undigested lactose in the colon will be metabolized by colonic bacteria, releasing hydrogen gas.
Positive lactose hydrogen breath test
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to a medication.
Triggered by exposure to medication
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to allopurinol.
Triggered by allopurinol
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by oral zinc supplementation.
Ameliorated by oral zinc supplementation
A root of a tooth that is more rounded than normal.
Curved dental root

The four-chamber (4Ch) view of the fetal heart is the most widely used screening examination for the detection of structural cardiac abnormalities during routine fetal ultrasonography. In the healthy normal fetus, the apical 4Ch view demonstrates four well-developed chambers, a concordant atrioventricular (AV) connection, unobstructed AV valves (mitral and tricuspid valves), the foramen ovale flap opening into left atrium (LA), and an intact interventricular septum. Additionally, the pulmonary venous opening can be visualized at the LA wall. Any structural deviations from normal anatomy may lead to congenital heart disease that can be determined by the 4Ch view of the fetal heart's ultrasound imaging.
Abnormal four chamber view of the fetal heart
A hamartomatous lesion (benign focal lesions composed of disorganized tissue elements) localized in the spleen.
Spleen hamartoma
Deposits of immunoglobulins and complement components along the dermoepidermal junction.
Positive lupus band test
Formation of vacuoles (a space within a cell that is empty of cytoplasm, lined with a membrane, and filled with fluid) in the cytoplasm of erythroid precursors in the bone marrow.
Bone marrow erythroid vacuolization
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to an electromagnetic field.
Triggered by electromagnetic field
Information about current and past exposure to metals, dust, fibers, fumes, chemicals, biologic hazards, radiation, noise, and/or vibration at work or home.
Exposure history
History of exposure to asbestos, a fibrous mineral with physical and chemical properties that make it resistant to heat and degradation.
Asbestos exposure
Information about current or past medications taken by an individual.
Medication history
History of having taken aminoglycoside antibiotics.
Aminoglycoside exposure
History of having taken statins, also known as HMG-CoA reductase inhibitors.
Statin exposure
History of having taken a potassium-sparing diuretic exposure such as amiloride, eplerenone, spironolactone, and triamterene.
Potassium-sparing diuretic exposure
History of having taken carbamazepine.
Carbamazepine exposure
History of having taken valproate (valproic acid).
Valproate exposure
History of having taken hydralazine.
Hydralazine exposure
History of having taken a calcium channel blocker such as amlodipine, nicardipine, nifedipine, verapamil, or diltiazem.
Calcium channel blocker exposure
Triggered by nickel

Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure (cutaneous contact) to poison ivy, poison oak, and poison sumac. These three plants each contain urushiol. Contact with these plants is the most common causes of clinically diagnosed allergic contact dermatitis.
Triggered by poison ivy, poson oak, or sumac
A past medical history of having been fed exclusively by breast feeding.
History of exclusive breast feeding
A part of the past medical history consisting of information about the typical food intake of an individual.
Nutrition history
A history of ingestion of a relatively high amount of foods containing high levels of oxalate, such as green-leaf vegetables, tea, nuts, chocolate and rhubarb.
High dietary oxalate intake
A history of ingestion of honey in recent weeks.
Recent honey ingestion
A history of eating raw egg whites.
Raw egg-white ingestion
Applied to a sign or symptom that is worsened by administration of sodium channel blocking agents such as phenytoin, carbamazepine, oxcarbazepine, lamotrigine, topiramate, and zonisamide.
Exacerbated by sodium channel blocking agent exposure
Addiction to inhaled nitrous oxide gas (N2O) is a growing concern.
Addictive nitrous oxide use
A past medical history of a recent blood transfusion.
Recent blood transfusion
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by administration of colchizine.
Ameliorated by colchicine
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by administration of vitamin D.
Ameliorated by vitamin D
Applied to a sign or symptom that is worsened by administration of phenytoin.
Exacerbated by phenytoin exposure
Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to anngiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor such as benazepril, captopril, enalapril, fosinopril, and lisinopril.
Triggered by angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor
History of having been treateed with prostaglandin E1.
Prostaglandin E1 exposure
History of having been treated with 5-fluorouracil.
5-fluorouracil exposure
History of having been treateed with 6-mercaptopurine.
6-mercaptopurine exposure
History of having been treateed with isoniazid.
Isoniazid exposure

The cavum septum pellucidum (CSP) is an important fetal midline forebrain landmark that is normally visible by prenatal sonography. This term refers to the lack of visiblity of the CSP on prenatal sonography. The CSP normally can be visualized between 18 and 37 weeks of gestation. Lack of visualization of the CSP in this time period generally requires follow up and may indicate the presence of underlying malformations such as malformations of the corpus callosum. The lack of CSP before 18 weeks or after 37 weeks of gestation (or postnatally) is considered a normal finding.
Absent cavum septum pellucidum

Fetal abdominal cysts are usually detected during the second trimester anomaly scan or discovered incidentally at later gestations. However, a definitive diagnosis is often not made until postnatal life. The most common etiologies of fetal abdominal cysts are: ovarian, gastrointestinal cystic duplication, liver and choledochal, meconium pseudocysts, mesenteric and adrenal. Following identification of a cyst, careful morphological assessment allows the prediction of their natural history and importantly, the likelihood of surgical intervention being required postnatally.
Fetal abdominal cyst

Fetal bowel dilatation is characterized by fluid-filled intestinal loops which measure at least fifteen millimeters long or seven millimeters in diameter. Ultrasonographic image of dilated fetal bowel is a sign of intestinal mechanical or functional obstruction and its prevalence will depend on the underlying condition: bowel atresia or stenosis, malrotation with volvulus, meconium ileus, total colonic aganglionosis, and meconium plug syndrome. The etiology of fetal bowel dilatation is a difficult prenatal diagnosis since ultrasound has limited accuracy for bowel evaluation.
Fetal bowel dilatation
Enlargement of the chamber of the left heart ventricle.
Left ventricular dilatation

A fetal ultrasound finding defined by flattening of the occiput with pointing of the frontal bones and brachycephaly with an increased cephalic index. It is characterized by keel shaped deformity of forehead with midline ridge, bilateral fronto temporal constriction with compensatory biparietal expansion, supra orbital and lateral orbital retrusion and hypotelorism. This finding is said to resemble a strawberry.
Fetal trigonocephaly

A prenatal anomaly of the outflow tract. Fetal ultrasound may not always be able to easily and accurately describe the outflow anomaly, but can detect abnormal anatomy. Often, follow up with a fetal echo is recommended, but fetal ultrasound is limited.
Abnormal fetal heart outflow tract
History of events that precede the current presenting condition and are thought to be of potential relevance, having occurred in the hours, days, or weeks before the current condition.
Recent past medical history
Medical history of a viral illness in recent weeks.
History of recent viral illness
Medical history of a dental procedure in recent weeks.
History of recent dental procedure
Any structural anomaly of the hepatic artery or its branches.
Abnormal hepatic artery morphology
Abnormal increase in size of the hepatic arteries.
Hepatic artery hyperplasia
Areas of necrotic tissue within a lymph node.
Lymph node necrosis
Neurons that contain more than one nucleus.
Multinucleated neuron
A history of an injury that occurred several hours, days, or weeks before the current presenting complaint and is located on the other side of the body relative to the current presenting complaint.
History of recent contralateral injury
Occuring on the left and right in succession. This term can refer to alternating sides of the body (e.g., Alternating hemiplegia) or alternative sides of the visual field (e.g., some migraine auras).
Alternating laterality
A benign tumor arising from the epithelial surface of the cervix and usually caused by Human Papillomavirus infection.
Cervical squamous cell papilloma
A benign smooth muscle neoplasm that arises in the liver.
Liver leiomyoma

Description of conditions in which only an incomplete but relatively high proportion of individuals with a given genotype exhibit the disease regardless of age assuming a full lifespan of 80 years. There is no commonly accepted definition for incomplete, but high penetrance, but we suggest that this term be applied if at least 80 percent but less than 100 percent of individuals with the given genotype would manifest the disease with a full lifespan.
Typified by high penetrance

Description of conditions in which only a moderate proportion of individuals with a given genotype exhibit the disease regardless of age assuming a full lifespan of 80 years. There is no commonly accepted definition for moderate penetrance, but we suggest that this term be applied if at least 20 percent but less than 80 percent of individuals with the given genotype would manifest the disease with a full lifespan.
Typified by moderate penetrance

Description of conditions in which only a low proportion of individuals with a given genotype exhibit the disease regardless of age assuming a full lifespan of 80 years. There is no commonly accepted definition for low penetrance, but we suggest that this term be applied if at least some but less than 20 percent of carriers would manifest the disease with a full lifespan.
Typified by low penetrance
Decreased activity of the enzyme succinyl-CoA 3-ketoacid CoA transferase.
Decreased Succinyl-CoA 3-ketoacid CoA transferase activity

Activity of the enzyme phytanoyl-CoA hydroxylase (PhyH; EC 1.14.11.18) below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts. PhyH plays a role in the catabolism of phytanic acid, a branched-chain fatty acid that is a normal constituent of the human diet.
Reduced phytanic acid oxidase activity in cultured fibroblasts

Diminished activity of hydroxysteroid 17-beta dehydrogenase 4 (HSD17B4), also known as D-bifunctional protein (DBP), a peroxisomal enzyme that catalyzes multiple steps of beta-oxidation of very long chain fatty acids.
Reduced bifunctional protein activity
Reduced plasmalogen concentration in the blood circulation.
Decreased circulating plasmalogen concentration
Infection with live, attenuated varicella-zoster virus following vaccination. This is an extremely rare event that may indicate immunocompromise.
Post-vaccination varicella zoster virus infection
History of having been treated with corticosteroid medications in recent weeks.
Recent steroid exposure
Eruption of permanent teeth behind deciduous (baby) teeth before they have fallen out, resulting in a double row of teeth. This phenomen is typically observed between the ages of 5 to 7 years.
Shark teeth
A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the pons.
Pontine T2 hypointensity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against antigens present on the surface of thrombocytes such as the glycoproteins GPIIb/IIIa, GPIb/IX, and GPIa/IIa.
Anti-platelet antigen antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against a voltage-gated potassium channel.
Anti-voltage-gated potassium channel antibody positivity
A history of following a vegan diet characterized by avoidance of food sourced from animals including meet, fish, and dairy products.
Vegan diet
One or more previous pregnancies in which the fetus developed hydrops fetalis.
History of previous pregnancy with hydrops fetalis
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by ingesting a potassium supplement.
Ameliorated by potassium supplements
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by ingesting niacin (vitamin B3).
Ameliorated by niacin
Applied to a sign or symptom that is worsened by treatment with a medication.
Aggravated by exposure to medication
Applies to bleeding that is significantly reduced by treatment with vitamin K.
Bleeding ameliorated by vitamin K
History of having been treated with an antiretroviral agent.
Anti-retroviral therapy exposure

History of having been treated with a potassium-wasting diuretic such as thiazide (chlorothiazide, chlorthalidone, hydrochlorothiazide, indapamide, metolazone) and loop (bumetanide, ethacrynic acid, furosemide, torsemide) diuretics.
Potassium-wasting diuretic exposure
History of having been treated with a tricyclic antidepressant medication.
Tricyclic antidepressant exposure

A higher than expected amount of attrition of teeth, as menifested by loss of tooth characteristics including rounding or sharpening of incisal edges, loss of cusps, and fracturing of teeth, to an extent that is deemed more than would be expected at a given age.
Excessive dental attrition
Pain improves or worsens with changes in body position.
Positionally dependent pain
Concentration of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) in red blood cells (erythrocytes) outside of the normal range.
Abnormal erythrocyte adenosine triphosphate concentration
Concentration of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) in red blood cells (erythrocytes) below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced erythrocyte adenosine triphosphate concentration
Concentration of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) in red blood cells (erythrocytes) above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated erythrocyte adenosine triphosphate concentration

A type of spermatogenesis maturation arrest in which the block of developmental occurs in the spermatogonial stage. Testicular histology shows seminiferous tubules with Sertoli cells and spermatogonial cells but no further differentiated cells like spermatocytes or round spermatids.
Spermatogonial maturation arrest
Concentration of neuron-specific enolase above the upper limit of normal in the blood circulation.
Elevated circulating neuron-specific enolase concentration
Concentration or activity of an alpha-mannosidase as measured in leukocytes is below the limits of normal.
Reduced leukocyte alpha-mannosidase activity
Concentration or activity of alpha mannosidase above the upper limit of normal in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating alpha-mannosidase activity
Concentration or activity of cathepsin D as measured in leukocytes is below the limits of normal. The reduction in cathepsin D activity can also be measured in fibroblasts.
Reduced leukocyte cathepsin D activity
Concentration or activity of N-sulfoglucosamine sulfohydrolase as measured in leukocytes is below the limits of normal.
Reduced leukocyte N-sulfoglucosamine sulfohydrolase activity
Pseudohyperkalemia describes a falsely elevated potassium level upon measurement of the serum electrolyte concentration due to disruption of cells during the collection or processing of the sample.
Pseudohyperkalemia

Concentration or activity of an enzyme is above or below the limits of normal in cultured fibroblasts. Fibroblasts are easy to grow in culture and are the main cell type involved in producing extracellular matrix. They are used as a convenient model system for measuring enzyme activity for enzymes that are not expressed in blood cells. Usually, the test is done in fibroblasts for convenience rather than for the investigation of a pathophysiology specific to fibroblasts.
Abnormal enzyme activity in cultured fibroblasts
Concentration or activity of N-sulfoglucosamine sulfohydrolase as measured in cultured fibroblasts is below the limits of normal.
Reduced heparan-alpha-glucosaminide N-acetyltransferase activity in cultured fibroblasts
Concentration or activity of N-acetylgalactosamine-6-sulfate sulfatase as measured in cultured fibroblasts is below the limits of normal.
Reduced N-acetylgalactosamine-6-sulfate sulfatase in cultured fibroblasts

Concentration or activity of N-acetylglucosamine-6-sulfatase (EC 3.1.6.14) as measured in cultured fibroblasts is below the limits of normal. N-acetylglucosamine-6-sulfatase hydrolyzes heparan sulfate and keratan sulfate.
Reduced acetylglucosamine-6-sulfate sulfatase activity in cultured fibroblasts
Activity or concentration of in the level of porphobilinogen deaminase (EC 4.3.1.8) in erythrocytes below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced erythrocyte porphobilinogen deaminase activity
Concentration or activity of holocarboxylase synthetase (EC 6.3.4.10) as measured in cultured fibroblasts is below the limits of normal.
Reduced holocarboxylase synthetase activity in cultured fibroblasts
Concentration or activity of alpha mannosidase outside of the limits of normal in the blood circulation.
Abnormal circulating alpha mannosidase activity
Concentration or activity of alpha-N-acetylgalactosaminidase (EC 3.2.1.49) as measured in cultured fibroblasts is below the limits of normal.
Reduced alpha-N-acetylgalactosaminidase activity in cultured fibroblasts
Activity or concentration of arginase (EC 3.5.3.1) in red blood cells below the lower limit of normal. Arginase catalyzes the last step of the urea cycle.
Reduced erythrocyte arginase activity
Concentration or activity of mitochondrial acetyl-CoA acetyltransferase (EC 2.3.1.9) as measured in cultured fibroblasts is below the limits of normal.
Reduced mitochondrial acetyl-CoA acetyltransferase activity in cultured fibroblasts
Concentration or activity of beta-mannosidase (EC 3.2.1.25) as measured in cultured fibroblasts is below the limits of normal.
Reduced beta-mannosidase activity in cultured fibroblasts
Acitivity of 3-methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase (EC 6.4.1.4) below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.
Reduced 3-methylcrotonyl CoA carboxylase activity in cultured fibroblasts
Acitivity of branched-chain alpha-keto acid dehydrogenase complex (EC 1.2.4.4) below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.
Reduced branched-chain alpha-keto acid dehydrogenase activity in cultured fibroblasts
Activity or concentration of in the level of galactose-1-phosphate uridylyltransferase (GALT; EC 2.7.7.12) in erythrocytes below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced erythrocyte galactose-1-phosphate uridylyltransferase activity
Activity of adenosine deaminase in red blood cells outside the limits of normal.
Abnormal erythrocyte adenosine deaminase activity
Acitivity of isovaleryl-CoA dehydrogenase (EC 1.3.99.10) below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.
Reduced isovaleryl CoA dehydrogenase activity in cultured fibroblasts
Acitivity of glycerol kinase (EC 2.7.1.30) below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.
Reduced glycerol kinase activity in cultured fibroblasts
Concentration of vitamin A above the upper limit of normal in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating vitamin A concentration
Concentration of hyaluronic acid in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating hyaluronic acid concentration
A reduction in the intensity of the breath sound as ascertained by auscultation of the lung.
Diminished breath sounds
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against anti-adenylate kinase 5 (AK5).
Anti-AK5 antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against anti-alpha-amino-3-hydroxy-5-methyl-4-isoxazolepropionic acid receptor (AMPAR).
Anti-AMPAR antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Amphiphysin.
Anti-Amphiphysin antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Rho GTPase-activating protein 26 (ARHGAP26).
Anti-ARHGAP26 antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Carbonic anhydrase-related protein VIII (CARPVIII).
Anti-CARP VIII antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against contactin-associated protein-like 2 (CASPR2).
Anti-CASPR2

The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against CV2/CRMP5. Anti-CV2/CRMP5 autoantibody is the most commonly detected anti-neuronal autoantibody. Patients with typical paraneoplastic chorea show fully developed chorea in the course of weeks to months with acute inflammation in the striatum.
Anti-CV2/CRMP5 antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against dipeptidyl-peptidase-like protein 6 (DPPX).
Anti-DPPX antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against FGFR3.
Anti-FGFR3 antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against gamma-aminobutyric acid A receptor, i.e., GABA(A)R.
Anti-GABA(A)R antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against gamma-aminobutyric acid B receptor, i.e., GABA(B)R.
Anti-GABA(B)R antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against glutamic acid decarboxylase 65 (GAD65).
Anti-GAD65 antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Gephyrin.
Anti-Gephyrin antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against glial fibrillary acidic protein (GFAP).
Anti-GFAP antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Glycine receptor (GlyR).
Anti-GlyR antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Homer-3.
Anti-Homer-3 antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Hu.
Anti-Hu antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against immunoglobulin-like cell adhesion molecule 5 (IgLON5).
Anti-Iglon5 antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against inositol 1,4,5-trisphosphate receptor 1 (ITPR1).
Anti-ITPR1 antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against kelch-like protein 11 (KLHL11).
Anti-Kelch like protein 11 antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against leucine-rich glioma-inactivated 1 (LGI1).
Anti-LGI1 antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Ma.
Anti-Ma antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Ma2.
Anti-Ma2 antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Ma1.
Anti-Ma1 antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against metabotropic glutamate receptor 1 (mGluR1).
Anti-mGluR1 antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against metabotropic glutamate receptor 5 (mGluR5).
Anti-mGluR5 antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against neurexin-3alpha.
Anti-neurexin-3alpha antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against P/Q-type voltage-gated calcium channels (VGCCs).
Anti-P/Q-type VGCC antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against microtubule-associated protein 1B (MAP1B).
Anti-MAP1B antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against protein kinase Cgamma.
Anti-PKCgamma antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Ri, an antineuronal antibody.
Anti-Ri antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Septin-5.
Anti-Septin-5 antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against seizure-related 6 homolog like 2 (SEZ6L2).
Anti-SEZ6L2 antibody

The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against SOX1. Anti-SOX1 antibodies, also known as antiglial nuclear antibody (AGNA), are specifically found in paraneoplastic neurological disorders. Since SOX1 is expressed in neuronal precursor cells in the developing central nervous system, it has been used as an early marker of neural stem cells.
Anti-SOX1 antibody

The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Tr/DNER. Anti-Tr antibodies are directed against cerebellar Purkinje cells (termed anti-Tr or PCA-Tr). Anti-Tr autoantibodies are frequently associated with Hodgkin lymphoma (HL). Anti-Tr antibodies are defined by a specific staining pattern in cerebellar tissue that is characterized by punctate immunoreactivity in both the dendritic tree and soma of Purkinje cells but not in their axons. This characteristic pattern is indicative of the presence of anti-Tr antibodies. The Delta/Notch-like epidermal growth factor-related receptor (DNER) was identified as the target antigen of anti-Tr.
Anti-Tr/DNER antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against the axon initial segment protein tripartite motif 46 (TRIM46).
Anti-TRIM46 antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against TRIM9/TRIM67.
Anti-TRIM9/TRIM67 antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Yo.
Anti-Yo antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against titin.
Anti-titin antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Zic family member 4 (ZIC4).
Anti-Zic4 antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against Sj/inositol 1,4,5-trisphosphate receptor.
Anti-Sj/ITPR1 antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against dopamine-2 receptor.
Anti-D2 R antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against glutamate kainate receptor subunit 2 (GluK2).
Anti-GluK2 antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against low-density lipoprotein receptor (Lrp4).
Anti-Lrp4 antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against ryanodine receptor.
Anti-ryanodine receptor antibody
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against the voltage-gated potassium channel Kv1.4.
Anti-Kv1.4 antibody
Voluntary failure to use spoken language (at whatever level attained) in selective social contexts over a period of time.
Selective mutism

An abnormally limited range of facial expressions demonstrated by a lack of nuance of facial expression to match specific social situations or an inability to demonstrate a normal range of emotions with one's face.
Limited repertoire of facial expression
An unusually strong interest in others in general or tendency to develop a strong interest in certain individuals.
Excessive interest in others
There is a diminished interest in all individuals, including both peers and non-peers.
Reduced response to another's attempt to get direct attention
Abnormally high or low-pitched vocalization or speech.
Abnormal pitch
Speech characterized by weak (e.g. tangential/circumstantial) or absent (e.g. word salad) connections between ideas.
Loose association
Consistent use of an invented word that is unique to an individual.
Neologism
Use of language that is overly formal, precise, detailed, or pedantic for the social context.
Overly formal/pedantic language
Hand stereotypies within the medial plane of the body.
Midline hand movements
Abnormal rise and fall of the voice in speech and vocalization.
Abnormal Intonation
Speech that is abnormally fast or slow
Abnormal speech rate
Speech with abnormal rhythm or pattern
Abnormal speech rhythm

Spontaneous production of communicative facial expressions that have poor quality or are perceived as odd or mechanical. This may include inaccurate mimicry of typical facial expressions. These expressions may be difficult to interpret for someone who is not familiar with the individual making the expression.
Ambiguous facial expression
A tendency to make facial expressions that are exaggerated and a failure to make subtle facial expressions in a social context when a subtle expression is more appropriate.
Exaggerated facial expression
A tendency to produce facial expressions with decreased intensity or expressivity which appear muted or flat.
Muted facial expression

The state of having abnormal relationships with others. This does not describe specific aspects of one's social aptitudes but rather a state which may come about from these aptitudes, such as lacking peer relationships or lacking close friends.
Abnormal peer relationships
Abnormal movements of face and head.
Abnormal movements of face and head
Abnormal movements of the upper extremities.
Abnormal movements of the upper extremities
Abnormal movements of the whole body.
Abnormal movements of the whole body
A social interest in others that is abnormal given the social context. This can include an increased interest with another person or an abnormal lack of interest in other people.
Abnormal interest in others
A lack of awareness of social rules in multiple social settings, which are simple or intuitive to others in the same social setting.
Reduced social insight
Reduced awareness of expected conventions, which are normal and expected for particular social settings or interactions.
Reduced awareness of convention

The state of having abnormal relationships with others. This does not describe specific aspects of one's social aptitudes but rather a state which may come about from these aptitudes, such as lacking peer relationships, lacking close friends, or having a relational network that is abnormal given one's cultural context.
Abnormal relationship
A reduced ability to imitate a task or the movements of others.
Abnormal social imitation
An abnormality in one's tendency to initiate social interactions.
Reduced attempt to get or direct another's attention
Abnormality in the way one responds to social cues such as a verbal cue (which should cause one to shift attention) or someone sharing their emotions (which should elicit a sympathetic response).
