Abnormally increased curvature of the penis.
Angulation of penis
A past medical history of a procedure or catheterization involving the urethra.
History of urethral procedure or catheterization
Abormal enlargement of the penis owing to accumulation of fluid.
Penile swelling
Activity of the enzyme alpha-1,4-glucosidase activity in muscle tissue is below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced muscle alpha-1,4-glucosidase activity

A brown tumor is a bone lesion that results from bony resorption by excess osteoclastic activity, and replacement by fibrous tissue and giant cells. Brown tumor is an uncommon pathognomonic sign of hyperparathyroidism.
Brown tumor

Flame-figures are composed of a central part consisting of collagen fibers and eosinophilic granules, surrounded by a histiocytic and eosinophilic infiltrate. Subsequently, eosinophils tend to disappear and are replaced by phagocytic granulomas, consisting of histiocytes and sometimes giant cells, around the flame figures.
Dermal flame figures
Applied to a sign or symptom that is present during pregnancy and becomes worse following birth.
Postpartum exacerbation
History of having taken retinoids.
Retinoid exposure
History of having been treated with propylthiouracil.
Propylthiouracil exposure

History of spending a substantial amount of time outdoors with occupation or hobbies related to the outdoors, including hunting, gardening, farming, agriculture, horticulture, miners, working in wet fields.
History of outdoor activities
A sinus tract is an abnormal channel that originates from the skin or a mucous surface to a deep-seated focus of suppuration.
Draining sinus tract in skin
Past medical history of surgical replacement of the cornea with corneal tissue from a donor.
Corneal transplant history
Breakage of the capsule of the lens. This is most often observed as a complication of lens surgery, but this term refers to lens capsule rupture not related to surgery or major trauma.
Spontaneous lens capsule rupture
A past medical history of wearing contact lenses.
Contact lens wearer
Increase in thickness of the mucosa of the airways above the upper limit of normal.
Airway mucosal thickening
Increased (more negative) voltage across the nasal epithelium.
Hyperpolarized transepithelial nasal potential difference
An adhesion between the conjunctiva of the eyelid and the cornea.
Corneopalpebral synechiae

Intraductal papilloma is a benign tumor found within breast ducts. The abnormal proliferation of ductal epithelial cells causes growth. A solitary intraductal papilloma is usually found centrally posterior to the nipple affecting the central duct. Multiple intraductal papillomas are located peripherally, found in any breast quadrant affecting the peripheral ducts.
Breast intraductal papilloma
Precipitous labor is extremely rapid labor and delivery, usually defined as expulsion of the fetus within less than 3 hours of commencement of regular contractions.
Precipitous labor
Maternal history of a pregancy with two fetuses in the uterus.
Twin pregnancy
A swelling or enlargment localized to the vagina. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Vaginal mass
Pain that is elicited by palpation of the region inside of the costovertebral angle, which is formed by the 12th rib and the spine.
Costovertebral angle tenderness

Pain that is elicited by moving the uterine cervix. This finding can be ascertained by pelvic exam. Cervical motion tenderness is a gynecological exam finding that could be indicative of peritoneal infection.
Cervical motion tenderness
Fluid that originates from the urethra that is not urine, pre-ejaculate or semen.
Abnormal penile discharge
The presence of an extra digital crease in and individual with normal joint anatomy.
Supernumerary finger flexion crease
Refers to a phenotypic abnormality that mainly affect large joints.
Large joint predominance
Refers to a phenotypic abnormality that affects a single joint.
Monoarticular
An abnormality of the upper palmar crease whereby the crease widens and ends between the second and third fingers and is said to resemble a hockey stick.
Hockey-stick palmar crease
The amount of succinyladenosine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary succinyladenosine level
The amount of 5-hydroxymethyluracil in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary 5-hydroxymethyluracil level
The amount of creatinine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased urine creatinine level
The amount of deoxyuridine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary deoxyuridine level
The amount of dihydrouracil in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary dihydrouracil level
The amount of dihydrothymine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary dihydrothymine level

The amount of sulfatides in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal. Sulfatides are derived from GalCer via esterification of a sulfate group to 3-hydroxyl of the galactose moiety.
Elevated urinary sulfatide level
The amount of xanthurenic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary xanthurenic acid level
Presence of N-acetylglucosamine-rich oligosaccharides in the urine.
Increased urinary N-acetylglucosamine-rich oligosaccharide level
The amount of 2'-deoxyadenosine (dAdo) in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary 2'-deoxyadenosine level
Positive (abnormal) result of the 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine urine test, which indicates the presence of alpha-ketoacids in the urine.
Positive 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine urine test
The amount of dolichol in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary dolichol level
The amount of bile acids in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased urinary bile acid level
The ratio of creatine to creatinine concentration in the urine is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary creatine/creatinine ratio
The amount of thymidine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Elevated urinary thymidine level
The amount of glutarylglycine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
Elevated urinary glutarylglycine level

Detection of indican in the urine. Urinary indican concentration may be elevated in small bowel bacterial overgrowth. Indican is produced by bacterial deconjugation of dietary tryptophan to indole which is absorbed at all levels of the intestine, but principally from the small bowel.
Elevated urinary indican level
Dacryolith is a concretion (accumulation of sediment) within the nasolacrimal system.
Dacrolith
Activity of gamma-glutamylcysteine synthetase (EC 6.3.2.2) in erythrocytes below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced erythrocyte gamma-glutamyl cysteine synthetase activity
The activity of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH)-cytochrome b5 reductase in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide-cytochrome b5 reductase activity
Activity of alpha-methylacyl-CoA racemase (AMACR; EC 5.1.99.4) below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.
Reduced alpha-methylacyl-CoA racemase activity in cultured fibroblasts

Volume of semen in ejaculate below the lower limit of normal. This finding can be ascertained by semen analysis. Comment: Sperm are produced within the testis, in the process of spermatogenesis, then travel through the male reproductive tract (the seminiferous tubules, epididymis, vas deferens, prostate and urethra). As the sperm travel, seminal fluid is added from the seminal vesicles, prostate, testis and epididymis and periurethral glands. The function of the ejaculate is to transport sperm into the female genital tract and to provide a suitable environment for sperm survival during this transit.
Low semen volume
Applies to an abnormality that is situated in (or predominant in) the elbow.
Elbow localization
Abnormal enlargement of the visible portion of the distal nail matrix that extends beyond the proximal nail fold, which is refered to as the lunula.
Enlarged lunula
Applies to an abnormality that is situated in (or predominant in) the heel.
Heel localization
Thin, red to reddish-brown lines of blood (hemorrhages) under the nails. Splinter hemorrhages run vertically under the nails.
Splinter hemorrhages

Lateral thrust (LT) refers to an abnormal knee joint motion in the early stance phase where the knee joint center moves laterally. Also known as varus thrust, LR is defined as the dynamic worsening or abrupt onset of varus (bow-leg) alignment as the limb accepts weight (stance phase), with a return to less varus and more neutral alignment during lift-off and the non-weight-bearing (swing) phase of gait, varus thrust is a potent mechanical risk factor for medial knee osteoarthritis progression.
Lateral thrust

A contusion is a region of injured tissue in which blood capillaries have been ruptured without laceration (bruise). Brain contusions are bruises of the cortical surface that damage the surface from the outside inward, producing disruption of tissue and vessels. The term cerebral contusion describes the pathology of focal necrosis and hemorrhage, typically observed in older children, involving particularly cerebral cortex and subcortical white matter. Such lesions are usually found in coup and contrecoup, as well as inferior orbital, frontal, and temporal locations. Cerebral contusions cause permanent damage to tissues of the cerebrum. The etiology of cerebral contusion is trauma to the head.
Cerebral contusion
A mass of accumulated hardened fecal matter.
Fecolith
Appendicitis is inflammation of the vermiform appendix. Appendix a hollow organ located at the tip of the cecum, usually in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen.
Appendicitis
A severely scarred portion of infarcted ventricular myocardium that does not contract normally but instead bulges outward while the rest of the ventricle contracts during systole.
Left ventricular aneurysm
An abnormal form of the heart seen upon chest radiography in which the heart displays an upturned apex and slight concave pulmonary artery segment. This configuration is said to resemble a boot.
Boot-shaped cardiac silhouette
Hydrosalpinx is a distension or dilatation of the fallopian tube in the presence of a distal tubal occlusion.
Hydrosalpinx
An increase in the level of 3-methylhex-2,4-dienedioic acid or 3-methylhex-3,4-dienedioic acid in the brain identified by magnetic resonance spectroscopy (MRS).
Elevated methylhex-dienedioic level by MRS
Increased signal (contrast enhancement) surrounding the liver observed on computer tomography or magnetic resonance imaging following administration of contrast agents.
Perihepatic enhancement

The in vitro contracture test determines the sensitivity of freshly obtained skeletal muscle specimens to caffeine or halothane applied to a bathing solution. Muscles from persons susceptible to malignant hyperthermia have lower contracture thresholds for these agents than do normal muscle.
Reduced in vitro contracture test threshold
Reduced strength (amplitude) of the F-wave, which is an electrophysiological artifact produced by antidromic activation of motoneurons following distal electrical stimulation of motor nerve fibers.
Reduced F-wave amplitude
Abnormal increase in size of peroxisomes.
Enlarged peroxisomes

A non-malignant growth, or enlargement, of the adrenal glands, specifically the cortex, although the cortex cannot be definitively identified by conventional imaging. Adrenal cortical hyperplasia is defined radiologically as a non-malignant growth, or enlargement, of the adrenal glands.
Adrenocortical hyperplasia
Accumulation of lymphocytes in the parotid gland. This feature is generally defined as a count of lymphocytes per area that is above normal limits on histopathological examination.
Lymphocytic infiltration of the parotid gland

A granuloma (a focal aggregate of immune cells that forms in response to a persistent inflammatory stimulus) localiyed to the bone marrow. A granuloma characteristically demonstrates the compact organization of mature macrophages, which may or may not be associated with other inflammatory cell types.
Bone marrow granuloma
The presence of intracellular inclusion bodies (aggregates of stainable substances, usually proteins) in neurons.
Neuronal intranuclear inclusion bodies
Wasting (shrinking) of the pancreas.
Pancreatic atrophy
Number (count) of pancreatic acinar cells reduced below normal. This feature can be ascertained by pancreas biopsy.
Decreased pancreatic acinar cell density

An abnormal result of the the filipin test. In this test is based on the reaction of unesterified cholesterol with fluorescent antibiotic filipin giving a strongly fluorescent, stable cholesterol-filipin complex suitable for in situ detection. An abnormal test result is present if there is a perinuclear accumulation of staining in lysosomal storage organelles (LSOs).
Unesterified cholesterol accumulation in cultured fibroblasts
Accumulation of foamy cells (lipid-laden macrophages) in the parenchyma of the liver.
Hepatic lipid-laden macrophage infiltration
Accumulation of foamy cells (lipid-laden macrophages) in the parenchyma of the spleen.
Splenic lipid-laden macrophage infiltration
Concentration or activity of N-acetylglutamate synthase in liver tissue below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic N-acetylglutamate synthase activity
Ingestion of large amounts of licorice.
Excessive licorice consumption
Applies to an abnormality that is situated in (or predominant in) the shoulder.
Shoulder localization

Intrauterine devices (IUDs) are used for contraception. Rarely pregnancy occurs despite the presence of an IUD. Such pregnancies are associated with an increased risk of spontaneous abortion and preterm delivery due to infection, and a higher risk of maternal septic complications.
Pregnancy conceived despite intrauterine device
The mother of a fetus or index patient has a history of folate deficiency during the corresponding pregnancy.
Maternal folate deficiency
The mother of a fetus or index patient has a history of abnormally low zinc levels during the corresponding pregnancy.
Maternal zinc deficiency
Intrauterine devices (IUD) are commonly used for contraception. IUD complications are rare, but include perforation, pelvic infection, expulsion, missing strings, and difficult IUD removal.
Use of intrauterine device

A past medical history of a recent central venous catheter (CVC). A CVC is an indwelling device inserted into a large, central vein (most commonly the internal jugular, subclavian, or femoral) and advanced until the terminal lumen resides within the inferior vena cava, superior vena cava, or right atrium. CVCs can be a necessary producre for critically ill patients with indications such as total parenteral nutrition administration, dialysis, plasmapheresis, medication administration, and hemodynamic monitoring, and to facilitate further complex interventions such as transvenous pacemaker placement. Complications include arrhythmia, central vein stenosis, and sepsis.
History of recent central venous catheter
A past medical history of a recent depence on total parenteral nutrition (TPN), which refers to intravenously administered nutrition being the only source of nutrition the patient is receiving.
History of total parenteral nutrition dependence
This refers to testicular pain that is lessened or made more bearable by elevation of the testicle.
Pain alleviated by testicle elevation

An abnormal enlargement or swelling localized to the abdominal wall (the skin, fascia, and muscle encases the abdominal cavity and viscera). The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Abdominal wall mass
The tympanic membrane protrudes (swells outwards). This feature may be observed with otoscopy.
Tympanic membrane bulging
Applies to pain of the ear that is worsened, aggravated, or exacerbated by touching or moving the tragus or pinna.
Ear pain exacerbated by manipulating tragus or pinna

An abnormal enlargement or swelling localized to the side of the neck. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Lateral neck mass
Applies to an abnormality that is situated in the occiput (back part of the head).
Occipital location
Abormal enlargement of the front part of the neck owing to accumulation of fluid.
Anterior neck swelling
Abnormal enlargement of the uvula related to an abnormal accumulation of fluid.
Uvular swelling
Flow of pus (purulence) from the Stensen duct. The Stensen duct is also known as the parotid duct and is the route that saliva takes from the major salivary gland (parotid gland) to the mouth.
Purulent drainage from Stensen duct
History of having received gastric bypass surgery. This is a procedure that reduces the functional volume of the stomach and is used to treat morbid obesity.
History of gastric bypass surgery

Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about by exposure to volatile organic compounds (VOCs), which comprise various organic chemicals which are released as gases from different liquids or solids.
Triggered by volatile organic compounds
A medical history of having undergone radiation therapy, which is a treatment that uses ionizing radiation for purposes such as the control the growth of malignant cells in cancer treatment.
History of radiation therapy
Failure to record otoacoustic emissions (OAE), i.e., sounds generated from the cochlea in response to an acoustic stimulus and transmitted across the middle ear to the external ear canal.
Absent otoacoustic emissions

The tympanic membrane (eardrum, myringa) is a thin, semitransparent, oval membrane, approximately 1 cm in diameter, that separates the external acoustic meatus from the tympanic cavity. Thickening refers to an increase of the dimension across the membrane.
Thickened tympanic membrane
Filum terminale lipomas (FTLs) are a type of lumbosacral lipoma in which the fat is entirely within the filum terminale and separate from the conus medullaris.
Filum terminale lipoma
The relative concentration of tetrahydrocortisol plus 5-alpha-tetrahydrocortisol relative to that of tetrahydrocortisone is below the lower limit of normal.
Low tetrahydrocortisol (THF) plus 5-alpha-THF/tetrahydrocortisone (THE) ratio
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against soluble liver antigen.
Anti-soluble liver antigen/liver pancreas antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against thrombospondin type I domain-containing 7A.
Anti-thrombospondin type I domain-containing 7A antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against sperm antigens.
Antisperm antibody positivity
Concentration of ficolin 3 in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating ficolin 3 concentration

A structural abnormality of the seminal vesicle. The seminal vesicles are a pair of glands that also include the prostate gland and the bulbourethral glands and are located in the pelvis superior to the rectum, inferior to the fundus of the bladder and posterior to the prostate. The seminal vesicles contribute around 70% of the fluid that will eventually become semen.
Abnormal seminal vesicle morphology
A cyst (sac-like mass that may contain serous liquid or semisolid material) caused by distention of the seminal vesicle due to atresia of the ejaculatory duct.
Seminal vesicle cyst
History of exposure to respirable crystalline silica (SiO2).
Silica dust exposure
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against osteoprotegerin.
Anti-osteoprotegerin antibody positivity
A past medical history of having had a surgical procedure to remove the adrenal glands.
History of adrenalectomy
Activity of the enzyme mitochondrial citrate synthase (EC:2.3.3.1) in muscle tissue is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated mitochondrial citrate synthase synthase activity

Activity of the enzyme lactate dehdrogenase (LHD; 1.1.1.27) in muscle tissue is below the lower limit of normal. LDH catalyzes the conversion of pyruvate to lactate and back, as it converts NAD+ to NADH and back.
Reduced muscle lactate dehydrogenase activity
Activity of the enzyme Phosphoglycerate mutase (PGM) in muscle tissue is below the lower limit of normal. PGM is an enzyme that catalyzes step 8 of glycolysis (EC 5.4.2.11).
Reduced muscle phosphoglycerate mutase activity
Activity of the enzyme muscle phosphorylase kinase (PhK) in muscle tissue below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced muscle phosphorylase kinase activity
Acitivity of 3-beta-hydroxysteroid-delta-5-desaturase, also known as Sterol C5-desaturase (EC 1.3.3.2), or SC5D below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.
Reduced 3-beta-hydroxysteroid-delta-5-desaturase activity in cultured fibroblasts
Activity of glucose-6-phosphatase (EC 3.1.3.9) in the liver below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic glucose-6-phosphatase activity
Activity of glucose-6-phosphate translocase in liver below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic glucose-6-phosphate translocase activity
The presence of red blood cells (RBCs) in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). The CSF normally does not contain RBCs (erythrocytes).
Cerebrospinal fluid erythrocytes
The concentration of cholestanol in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal. Cholestanol is the 5-alpha-dihydro derivative of cholesterol.
Elevated CSF cholestanol concentration
The concentration of apolipoprotein B in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF apolipoprotein B concentration
The concentration of myelin basic protein in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF myelin basic protein concentration
The concentration of pyridoxal-5'-phosphate in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced CSF pyridoxal-5'-phosphate concentration
The concentration of thymine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF thymine concentration
The concentration of 5-hydroxymethyluracil in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF 5-hydroxymethyluracil concentration
The concentration of N-carbamyl-beta-aminoisobutyric acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF N-carbamyl-beta-aminoisobutyric acid concentration
The concentration of N-carbamyl-beta-alanine in the cerebrospinal fluid is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF N-carbamyl-beta-alanine concentration
The concentration of dihydrouracil in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF dihydrouracil concentration
The concentration of dihydrothymine in the cerebrospinal fluid is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF dihydrothymine concentration
Concentration of angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating Angiotensin-converting enzyme concentration
The activity of 3-hydroxyisobutyrate dehydrogenase in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased 3-hydroxyisobutyrate dehydrogenase activity
The activity of 3-hydroxyisobutyryl-CoA hydrolase in the blood corculation is below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced circulating 3-hydroxyisobutyryl-CoA hydrolase activity
Acitivity of 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl coenzyme A lyase (HMG CoA lyase) below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.
Reduced HMG-CoA lyase activity in cultured fibroblasts
The activity of acyl-CoA oxidase activity in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced circulating acyl-CoA oxidase activity
Activity of the enzyme xanthine oxidase below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced circulating xanthine oxidase activity
The activity of methylmalonate semialdehyde dehydrogenase ( EC 1.2.1.27) in cultured fibroblasts is below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced methylmalonate semialdehyde dehydrogenase activity in cultured fibroblasts

An abnormal enlargement or swelling localized to the pharynx (i.e., the throat, the space that connects the nose and mouth to the larynx and esophagus). The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Pharyngeal mass
The presence of hidden (occult) blood in the stool.
Positive stool occult blood test
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort that occurs when passing stool.
Painful defecation
Medical history of a recent ingestion of a caustic substance, i.e., a highly acidic or alkaline chemicals that can cause severe burns to the mouth and digestive tract when swallowed.
Recent history of caustic substance ingestion
Failure to pass meconium (the first stool following birth) in the first 48 hours of life.
Delayed passage of meconium

The second sound can remain single throughout the respiratory cycle due to either absence of one component or to synchronous occurrence of the two components. Since the pulmonary vascular impedance increases with age, many normal patients over age 50 have a single S2 or at most a narrow physiologic split on inspiration because P2 occurs early. A single second sound, however, is usually due to inability to auscultate a relatively soft pulmonic component. Such inability is rare in healthy infants, children, and young adults and is uncommon even in older persons under good auscultatory conditions using a rigid stethoscopic diaphragm.
Single second heart sound
The gradient (in this case, drop) in pressure across the aortic valve is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated aortic transvalvular pressure gradient
A past surgical history of the implanation of an artificial heart valve.
Prosthetic heart valve

Hyperoxia test is the initial method to distinguish critical congenital heart disease (CCHD) from pulmonary disease. The test consists in measuring an arterial blood gas at room air and 100% inspired oxygen after 10 minutes. Neonates with congenital heart disease are usually not able to increase PaO2 above 100 mm Hg during 100% oxygen administration. In patients with pulmonary disease, PaO2 generally increased greater than or equal to 100 mm Hg with 100% oxygen as ventilation-perfusion discrepancies are overcome. A positive result indicates the cardiac origin and further cardiac workup is indicated to rule out CCHD.
Failure to increase oxygen saturation on hyperoxia test
Placement of the nipples at a higher than normal location.
High-set nipples
The amount of calveolin-3 in muscle tissue is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased muscle caveolin-3 level
Concentration of an enyzme in a tissue is above or between the limit of normal. This term is intended to be used for enzymes that can be measured in multiple tissues other than blood.
Abnormal tissue enzyme activity
Cell dealth (necrosis) located in the spleen.
Splenic necrosis
A carcinoid tumor of the pancreas (CTP) is a rare neuroendocrine tumor arising from the serotonin-secreting cells (enterochromaffin or Kultscitsky's cells).
Carcinoid tumor of the pancreas
The concentration of dihydroxyphenylacetic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating dihydroxyphenylacetic acid concentration
Lower than appropriate concentration of acetoacetate in states such as hypoglycemia in which the normal response would be to elevate acetoacetate.
Inappropriately low concentration of acetoacetate
Lower than appropriate concentration of beta-hydroxybutyrate in states such as hypoglycemia in which the normal response would be to elevate acetoacetate.
Iappropriately low concentration of beta-hydroxybutyrate
Concentration of 3-hydroxybutyryl-carnitine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating 3-hydroxybutyryl-carnitine concentration
The concentration of 5-amino-4-imidazolecarboxyamide in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF 5-amino-4-imidazolecarboxyamide concentration
The concentration of tumor necrosis factor alpha in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating tumor necrosis factor alpha concentration
The activity of concentration of pyrimidine 5-prime-nucleotidase (EC 3.1.3.5) in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced circulating pyrimidine 5-prime-nucleotidase activity
The increase in prolactin concentration (PRL) following stimulation with thyrotropin (thyrdoid releasing hormone) as compared to baseline PRL concentration is below the lower limit of normal.
Diminished prolactin response to thyrotrophin-releasing hormone stimulation
The concentration of complement component 1s (C1s) in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating complement component 1s concentration
The concentration of cortisol-binding globulin in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced circulating cortisol-binding globulin concentration
The concentration of thyroglobulin in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.
Decreased circulating thyroglobulin concentration
The concentration of granulocyte-macrophage colony-stimulating factor (GM-CSF) in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating granulocyte-macrophage colony-stimulating factor concentration
The concentration of D-2-hydroxyglutaric acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF D-2-hydroxyglutaric acid concentration
A swelling or enlargment localized to the esophagus. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Esophageal mass
The presence of crystals (microscopic solids that form distinct lattices, with definable fixed angles, faces, walls) in the joint (synovial) fluid.
Synovial fluid crystals
Giant gastric folds are recognized at endoscopy as an increase in the size of the gastric rugae and a lack of flattening.
Enlarged gastric folds
The count of lymphocytes located in the epithelial layer of the gastric mucosa is above the upper limit of normal.
Gastric intraepithelial lymphocytosis
The count of lymphocytes located in the epithelial layer of the mucosa of the small intestine is above the upper limit of normal.
Small intestinal intraepithelial lymphocytosis
Increased response (echo) of lung tissue of a fetus observed on prenatal sonography. Increased echo response is conventially displayed as a higher degree of brightness.
Fetal lung hyperechogenicity
A histopathological finding characterized by inflammation of the arterial and/or capillary and/or venous blood vessels, leading to a change in the vascular wall as a whole.
Necrotizing vasculitis

Any structural anomaly of the proximal convoluted tubule, which is the first tubular component of the nephron and arises as a continuation of the Bowman space from the tubular pole of the renal corpuscle. The proximal convoluted tubule is located within the renal cortex.
Abnormal proximal convoluted tubule morphology
Presence of Leishmania, a parasitic protozoan, in a tissue specimen. Leishmania is responsible for leishmaniasis.
Demonstration of Leishmania in tissue
Demonstration of cysts of Pneumocystis (a genus of related fungal species) in respiratory secretions such as nasopharyngeal secretions or pleural fluid.
Pneumocystis cysts in respiratory secretions
An aggregation of macrophages (forming in response to chronic inflammation) localized in or on the spinal cord.
Spinal cord granuloma
Reduced ability to absorb folate in the diet. This finding can be measured by a folic acid loading test in which blood concentration of folate is measured after oral administration of folic acid.
Impaired folate absorption

Abnormally elevated quantiy of hydrogen measured by a hydrogen breath test (HBT). HBTs administer substrates such as glucose, lactulose, lactose and fructose and subsequently measure hydrogen exhaled in the breath using a gas chromatograph.
Positive hydrogen breath test
A history of a plant skin puncture preceding the current presenting condition by hours, days, or weeks.
History of recent plant thorn skin puncture
Nondetectable kappa chain in the blood circulation.
Absent circulating immunoglobulin kappa chain
A circumscribed whitish-yellow mass in the posterior chamber associated with retinal folds and sometimes retinal detachment and is said to resemble a retinal glioma.
Pseudoglioma
Swelling due to fluid acculuation of the papillary dermis.
Papillary dermal edema
The number of beats per minute (bpm) of the fetal heart is above the upper limit of the normal for the gestational age. Fetal tachycardia is thus defined as a heart rate greater than 160-180 bpm.
Fetal tachycardia
The amount of 3-hydroxykynurenine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary 3-hydroxykynurenine level
The amount of 2-oxoadipic acid in the urine, normaliyed for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
2-oxoadipic aciduria
The concentration of methionine sulfoxide in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating methionine sulfoxide concentration
The concentration of pipecolic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating pipecolic acid concentration
The amount of pipecolic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary pipecolic acid level
Concentration of saccharopine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF saccharopine concentration

Concentration in the bloodstream of glycylproline above the upper limit of normal. Glycylproline is a dipeptide composed of glycine and proline, and is an end product of collagen metabolism that is further cleaved by prolidase (EC 3.4.13.9).
Elevated circulating glycylproline concentration
Concentration of octanoylcarnitine (C8:0) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating octanoylcarnitine concentration
Concentration of decanoylcarnitine (C10:0) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating decanoylcarnitine concentration
Increased concentration of 2-hydroxyphenylacetic acid in the urine.
2--hydroxyphenylacetic aciduria
Amount of 4-hydroxyphenyllactic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
4-hydroxyphenyllactic aciduria
The amount of beta alanine in the urine, when normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary beta-alanine level
The concentration of beta-alanine present in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF beta-alanine concentration
The concentration of 2-aminoadipic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating 2-aminoadipic acid concentration
The amount of N-carbamoyl-beta-alanine present in urine, when adjusted for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary N-carbamoyl-beta-alanine level
Concentration of cystathionine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF cystathionine concentration
The amount of gamma-glutamylphenylalanine level in the urine, when normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary gamma-glutamylphenylalanine level
Concentration of aspartylglucosamine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating aspartylglucosamine concentration
The amount of saccharopine in the urine, when normalized to urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary saccharopine level
Abnormal increase in size of the tectal plate (also known as the tectum or the quadrigeminal plate). The tectum is the dorsal portion of the midbrain (brainstem).
Tectal plate enlargement

A swelling or enlargment localized to the retroperitoneal region. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Retroperitoneal mass
A lighter than expected T1 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brainstem. This term refers to a localized hyperintensity affecting a particular region of the brainstem.
Focal T1 hyperintense brainstem lesion
A type of fracture that occurs in the trabecular cancellous bone just beneath the subchondral bone plate without disruption of the articular surface.
Subchondral fracture

An abscess (i.e., a circumscribed area of pus or necrotic debris) localized in the area surrounded by the deep fascia of the neck including the pharynx, larynx, trachea, upper esophagus, thyroid, and parathyroid glands. Infections of pharyngeal, tonsillar, and laryngeal origin affect this space, which includes the parapharyngeal and retropharyngeal spaces.
Deep neck abscess
Anlarged and edematous epiglottis. This sign can be observed on a lateral radiograph of the neck and it suggests a diagnosis of acute infectious epiglottitis.
Epiglottic enlargement

Increase in the anterior posterior dimension of the prevertebral space, which is located in the neck region between the anterior part of the cervical spine and the deep layer of the deep cervical fascia running between the transverse processes of the spine.
Prevertebral space enlargement
Increase in diameter of the third cranial nerve (oculomotor nerve). This feature can be observed by magnetic resonance imaging and may be accompanied by contrast enhancement.
Third cranial nerve thickening
Concentration of sphoingomyelin in tissues above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated tissue sphingomyelin concentration
Medical history of recent iodinated or radioiodine contrast use.
History of recent iodated contrast medium administration

Difficulty inserting a nasogastric tube (NGT), a flexible plastic tube that is placed through the nose and esophagus into the stomach and used to administer drugs or for feeding. There are certain circumstances that may make NGT insertion difficult. They are esophageal narrowing, comatose or intubated patients, and patients who have sustained severe facial or skull injuries.
Difficulty passing nasogastric tube

A falcine sinus that does not involute but persists beyond birth is defined as a persistent falcine sinus. In the 20-mm embryo stage, the primitive falx cerebri contains the sagittal plexus, a meshwork of anastomotic venous channels from which the superior sagittal sinus and straight sinus are thought to develop. A persistent falcine sinus represents a persistent channel of the caudal anastomotic loops of the sagittal plexus.
Persistent falcine venous sinus
A medical history in a male of not having been circumcized.
Penis uncircumcised
A medical history of use of facial makeup.
History of facial cosmetic use
A feeling of clicking or snapping at the knuckle (metacarpophalangeal joint) upon extension of flexion of the finger.
Snapping sensation at metacarpophalangeal joint
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the forearm.
Forearm
A type of displaced fracture in which there has been a rotation of the distal fracture fragment in relation to the proximal portion.
Rotational fracture
Applies to an abnormality that is situated on the skin in areas where bones are close to the surface (bony prominences).
Localized over bony prominences
A past medical history of wearing tight shoes, toe-box shoes, or high heel shoes.
History of compressive footwear
Reduced skin turgor means reduced elastic recoil of the skin to its normal contour after being pinched in a fold.
Decreased skin turgor
Medical history of recently eating wild mushrooms.
Recent foraged mushroom consumption
Refers to symptomatology that begins in the proximal limbs and subsequently affects the distal limbs.
Proximal to distal progression

The selective paralysis of voluntary fascio-pharyngo-glosso-masticatory movements with preservation of reflexive and automatic functions is referred to as autonomic-voluntary dissociation, which is a distinctive feature of Anterior opercular syndrome (also known as Foix-Chavany-Marie syndrome).
Autonomic-voluntary dissociation of facial movements
A swelling or enlargment localized to the mass. The word mass is usually used at an early stage of the diagnostic workup before the precise nature of the swelling has been determined.
Jaw mass
Exposure to continuous light at night, including night-shift work or a nocturnal lifestyle.
Excessive nocturnal light exposure
Past medical history of a woman who is menstruating, i.e., not premenstrual or post-menopause.
Menstruating female between menarche and menopause
PPROM (preterm premature rupture of membranes) occurs at less than 37 weeks of gestation. PPROM can happen spontaneously, during preterm labor, or following a procedure such as amniocentesis.
Preterm premature rupture of membranes
A past medical history that indicates that the patient had a surgical procedure involving the abdomen.
History of abdominal surgery
The thickness of the Descement membrane is above the upper limit of normal.
Thickened Descemet membrane

Right bundle branch block (RBBB) represents an abnormality in the intraventricular electrical conduction system of the human heart, generating enlarged QRS and modified vectors on the electrocardiogram (ECG). Incomplete RBBB (IRBBB) is defined by (i) QRS duration between 110 and 120 ms in adults; (ii) rsr, rsR, or rSR in leads V1 or V2. The R or r deflection is usually wider than the initial R wave. In a minority of patients, a wide and often notched R wave pattern may be seen in leads V1 and/or V2; (iii) S wave of greater duration than R wave or greater than 40 ms in leads I and V6 in adults; and (iv) Normal R peak time in leads V5 and V6 but greater than 50 ms in lead V1. The first 3 criteria should be present to make the diagnosis. When a pure dominant R wave with or without a notch is present in V1, criterion 4 should be satisfied.
Incomplete right bundle branch block
Onset of signs or symptoms of disease during the period of a woman's life shortly before the occurrence of the menopause.
Perimenopausal onset
Onset of signs or symptoms of disease during the period of a woman's life after the occurrence of the menopause.
Postmenopausal onset
Spastic weakness found in only one upper or lower extremity.
Spastic monoplegia

Mosaic attenuation pattern in the lung is a term used to describe regions of differing pulmonary attenuation on CT imaging. It is a non-specific finding, although is associated with several conditions such as obstructive small airway disease, occlusive vascular disease (in which case is called mosaic perfusion pattern), pulmonary oedema, and parenchymal diseases.
Mosaic attenuation pattern in lung

The ratio of aldosterone concentration to renin concentration is above the upper limit of normal. If aldosterone is expressed in ng/dl and plasma renin activity is expressed as ng/ml/hr, then values above 20 with aldosterone level above 15 are considered indicative of primary aldosteronism.
Elevated aldosterone:renin ratio

An increase in the gas content inside the bowel associated with distension of the abdomen and hydroaeric noises. The most common symptom of meteorism is a bloated sensation. It may be associated with abdominal discomfort. Some individuals may also complain of a distended stomach and excessive belching and/or passage of flatus.
Meteorism

Normal subjects display an increase in the concentration of ammonia in the blood following an ischemic exercise test. This term refers to an increase in ammonia that is below the lower limit of normal.
Failure to elevate ammonia on ischemic exercise
Frequent fluctuations of blood pressure between normal and high levels, changing more dramatically than normal.
Labile Hypertension

The axon reflex (also known as the flare response) is a response that is stimulated by peripheral nerves of the body that travels away from the nerve cell body and branches to stimulate target organs. In the human skin, there are three different phenomena mediated by axon reflex mechanism; flare, sweating and pilomotion. Stroking or intradermal injection of histamine or substance P into the human skin pro- duces widespread vasodilatation (flare) and plasma extravasation (wheal). This term refers to the failure of intradermal hista injection to elicit flare.
Absent axon flare response after intradermal histamine injection

Response to the cold pressor test below the lower limit of normal. The cold pressor test is a simple and validated test in which the subject immerses one hand or foot into ice water for 1 to 3 minutes while blood pressure (BP) and heart rate are monitored. The cold stimulus activates afferent sensory pathways that, in turn, trigger a sympathetic response resulting in an increase in BP.
Reduced sympathoneural responses to the cold pressor test
Fecal analysis for Giardia antigen is abnormal. Tests include direct fluorescent-antibody (DFA), which detect sintact organisms, and enzyme immunoassays (EIAs), which detect soluble stool antigens.
Positive stool Giardia antigen test

Loss of a substantial amount of blood during delivery (some definitions stipulate 1000 ml or more), typically associated with manifestations such as low blood pressure, a rapid heart rate, dizziness, light-headedness, fatigue, and weakness.
Excessive blood loss during delivery

Endocarditis infection occurs along the edges of the heart valves. Damage to the cardiac endothelium followed by platelet and fibrin deposition results in a sterile lesion known as nonbacterial thrombotic endocarditis (NBTE) or vegetation. Microbes entering the bloodstream via routine or invasive procedures adhere to the vegetation and are engulfed in an outer meshwork of fibrin and platelets. Subsequent rapid microbial multiplication in a protected area of impaired host defense leads to vegetation growth and continuous bacteremia.
Cardiac valve vegetations
The anteroposterior dimension of the chest on the lateral radiograph is often relatively narrow compared with the chest width on the frontal radiograph.
Thoracic cage flatness
Lack of the oocyte extracellular matrix region (zona pellucida). This feature can be observed following follicular aspiration (retrieval of eggs for fertility treatments).
Absent zona pellucida

The presence of the umbilical cord (UC) between the fetal presenting part and the cervix, regardless of the membrane status (intact or ruptured). Descent of the UC through the cervix is essential for diagnosing cord prolapse. It can be either overt (past the presenting part) or occult (alongside the presenting part).
Umbilical cord prolapse
The relative concentration of deoxypyridinoline (Dpyr) to that of pyridinoline (Pyr) cross-links in urine is above the upper limit of normal.
Increased ratio of deoxypyridinoline to pyridinoline cross-links in urine
The amount of thymine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary thymine level
The amount of indoleacetic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated urinary indoleacetic acid level

Activity of phosphorylase kinase in liver tissue below the lower limit of normal. Phosphorylase kinase (PhK) has a major regulatory role in the breakdown of glycogen. The enzyme PhK comprises four copies each of four subunits, encoded by PHKA1, PHKA2, PHKB, and PHKG.
Reduced hepatic phosphorylase kinase activity
Activity or concentration of ornithine transcarbamylase in the liver below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced hepatic ornithine transcarbamylase activity

The amount of quinolinic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal. Quinolinic acids is a pyridinedicarboxylic acid that is pyridine substituted by carboxy groups at positions 2 and 3. It is a metabolite of tryptophan.
Elevated urinary quinolinic acid level

A developmental anomaly characterized by an additional rectum that is typically lined with intestinal mucosa with one or more cell types of the gastrointestinal tract overlying submucosa and smooth muscle layer.
Rectal duplication

Abrnormal reduction in the height of the mucosa of the small intestine. The mucosa is arranged in regular circular folds (the circular valves of Kerckrin), the mucosal surface is covered with small projections called villi, which are slender, about 1.5-2 mm long projections of the mucosa into the lumen. In between the villi are the crypts. This term refers to a pathological thinning of these structures.
Thinned small intestinal mucosa
A congenital anomaly characterized by underdevelopment of one or both seminal vesicles, which are the two small glands that store and produce the majority of the fluid that makes up semen.
Seminal vesicle hypoplasia
The distance around the abdomen of a fetus, generally as measured by prenatal sonography, is below the lower limit of normal.
Small fetal abdominal circumference

The diaphragm normally projects up into the thoracic cavity. In the presence of malformations such as enlarged lungs, the diaphragm may appear abnormally flat or even everted (with the middle of the diaphragm projecting downwards into the abdominal cavity).
Prenatal flattened diaphragm
Dense floating particles in amniotic fluid, said to resemble snowflakes. This finding can result from shedding of the epidermis in conditions such as Harlequin ichthyosis.
Snowflake effect in amniotic cavity
An abnormally increased thickness of a leaflet of the mitral valve.
Thickened mitral valve cusp
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the serum that react against parietal cell antigens.
Antiparietal cell antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against intrinsic factor.
Anti-intrinsic factor antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV).
Anti-human immunodeficiency virus antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of poliovirus.
Anti-polio virus antibody positivity
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against the N-Methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptor NR2A subunit.
Anti-NR2A antibody positivity
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against streptolysin O.
Antistreptolysin O antibody positivity
Concentration or activity of 5-aminoimidazole-4-carboxamide ribonucleotide formyltransferase; EC 2.1.2.3) a in a tissue is below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced tissue tissue AICAR transformylase activity

Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with an agent that reduces gastric acidity such as proton pump inhibitors, histamine receptor blockers,omeprazole, esomeprazole, dexlansoprazole, pantoprazole, lansoprazole, famotidine, or ranitidine.
Ameliorated by gastric acid-reducing therapy
The presence of an antibody in the blood circulation that is directed against a coagulation factor.
Anti-coagulation factor antibody positivity
Excessively rapid eating of food.
Tachyphagia

Concentration of argininosuccinate synthetase (EC 6.3.4.5) in body tissues is below the lower limit of normal. Clinically, argininosuccinate synthetase is measured in the liver or in cultered skin fibroblasts.
Reduced tissue argininosuccinate synthetase activity

Acitivity of aspartoacylase below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts. Aspartoacylase (EC 3.5.1.15), also called aminoacylase-2, is an enzyme that hydrolyzes N-acetyl-L-aspartic acid (NAA) to aspartate and acetate.
Reduced aspartoacylase activity in cultured fibroblasts
Acitivity of malonyl-CoA decarboxylase (EC 4.1.1.9) below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.
Reduced malonyl-CoA decarboxylase activity in cultured fibroblasts
Concentration or activity of medium-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase (EC 1.3.8.7;MCAD) in tissues is below the lower limit of normal.
Reduced tissue medium-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase activity
Acitivity of cystathionine beta-synthase (EC 4.2.1.22) below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.
Reduced cystathionine beta-synthase activity in cultured fibroblasts

Activity of the enzyme glycogen phosphorylase in muscle tissue is below the lower limit of normal. Glycogen phosphorylase (EC 2.4.1.1) is also known as amylophosphorylase, muscle phosphorylase a and b, polyphosphorylase, and myophosphorylase.
Reduced muscle glycogen phosphorylase activity

Activity of the enzyme 6-phosphofructokinase in muscle tissue is below the lower limit of normal. 6-phosphofructokinase (EC 2.7.1.11) is also known as phosphofructokinase I and phosphohexokinase. The PFKM gene encodes the muscle isoform of phosphofructokinase. PFK catalyzes the irreversible conversion of fructose-6-phosphate to fructose-1,6-bisphosphate and is a key regulatory enzyme in glycolysis.
Reduced muscle 6-phosphofructokinase activity

Concentration or activity of alpha-N-acetylglucosaminidase (EC 3.2.1.50) below the lower limit of normal. This enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts. It is also known as alpha-acetylglucosaminidase, N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminidase, N-acetyl-alpha-glucosaminidase, and alpha-D-2-acetamido-2-deoxyglucosidase.
Reduced tissue alpha-N-acetylglucosaminidase activity
Activity of succinyl-CoA:3-oxoacid-CoA transferase (SCOT, or OXCT1; EC 2.8.3.5) below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.
Reduced succinyl-CoA:3-oxoacid-CoA transferase activity in cultured fibroblasts

A non-suppressible aldosterone excess, defined as an abnormal result of one of any four suppression tests. These tests use oral sodium loading, oral fludrocortisone, oral captopril, or saline infusion to suppress aldosterone secretion.
Blunted aldosterone response to aldosterone suppression test
An abnormal enlargement or swelling in the flank, which is the fleshy part of the side of the body between the ribs and the hip.
Flank mass
A fluid-filled sac or pouch-like mass that is a distention of a preexisting bursa in a joint, tendon sheaths or bursae. Synovial cysts contain synovial fluid and are lined by synovial membrane.
Synovial cyst
Deposition of brown pigmentation in the conjunctiva.
Brown pigmentation of the conjunctiva
Limitation of simultaneous ankle dorsiflexion and knee extension during mid-stance of gait.
Gastrocnemius contracture

Reduced thickness of the outer nuclear layer in the middle region of the retina. The outer nuclear layer (ONL) of the retina contains the nuclei of the cone and rod photoreceptors. Loss of the cellular machinery found in these nuclei causes irreparable loss of the photoreceptors and the capacity for visual function. This feature can be appreciated by directional optical coherence tomography.
Central thinning of the outer nuclear layer of the retina

Heterogeneous, increased parenchymal echogenicity. This imaging appearance is caused by multiple tiny cysts smaller than or just approaching the size necessary for detection, which disrupt the echo pattern without being clearly distinguishable, and appear as white grains on renal ultrasound, mainly in a subcapsular location.
Sonographic renal salt and pepper pattern

A form of ductus venosus agenesis in which the umbilical vein connects via the portal sinus to the portal venous system (PVS) without giving rise to the ductus venosus. In some cases an intrahepatic shunt from a portal to a hepatic vein can be detected prenatally. This variant has been reported to have a favorable prognosis.
Ductus venosus agenesis with intrahepatic drainage

A form of ductus venosus agenesis in which umbilical vein does not connect to the portal venous system. The liver is bypassed and the umbilical vein drains into a systemic vein such as the inferior vena cava. This variant has been reported to have an unfavorable prognosis due to a presumed association with congestive heart failure and hydrops.
Ductus venosus agenesis with extrahepatic drainage and liver bypass
The concentration of D-gyceric acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated circulating D-glyceric concentration
The concentration of D-carboxylic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is above the upper limit of normal.
Elevated CSF D-glyceric acid concentration
Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by ingestion of riboflavin (Vitamin B2).
Ameliorated by riboflavin
An increased concentration of interleukin-1beta in the blood circulation.
Increased circulating interleukin 1beta concentration
Concentration or activity of myeloperoxidase (EC 1.11.1.7) as measured in neutrophils is below the limits of normal.
Reduced neutrophil myeloperoxidase activity

Reduction in diameter of the jugular foramen, an opening in the base of the skull that is located behind the carotid canal and is formed by the temporal bone and the occipital bone. The inferior petrosal sinus, three cranial nerves, the sigmoid sinus, and meningeal arteries pass through the jugular foramen.
Jugular foramen stenosis
The presence of extraluminal gas within the bowel wall.
Intramural intestinal gas

Hepatobiliary scintigraphy is a nuclear imaging technique that permits evaluation of the liver and biliary system for acute and chronic cholecystitis, biliary atresia, biliary obstruction, and post-surgical biliary leak. With this investigation, a radiotracer is administered intravenously, bound to albumin, transported to the liver, and excreted into the biliary system. This term refers to a longer than normal time for the radiotracer to be visualized in the gallbladder. This finding may be a sign of chronic gallbladder disease or partial obstruction of the common bile duct.
Delayed scintigraphic gallbladder filling
Pancreatic arteriovenous malformation is defined as an abnormal vascular net, developed from one or more feeding arteries and enlarged early draining veins, creating an arteriovenous shunting.
Pancreatic arteriovenous malformation

A pulmonary cavity is a gas-filled area of the lung in the center of a nodule or area of consolidation and may be clinically observed by use of plain chest radiography or computed tomography. Cavities are present in a wide variety of infectious and noninfectious processes.
Pulmonary cavitation
Calcification, that is, pathological deposition of calcium salts in the spleen.
Splenic calcification
Abnormal reduction in the length of the esophagus.
Short esophagus
A full-thickness injury of the wall of the stomach.
Gastric perforation
A gastric volvulus occurs when the stomach rotates on itself at least 180 degrees along its transverse or longitudinal axis.
Gastric volvulus
inheres in
inheres in part of
